Notes: There's that great article that came out somewhere this week, maybe ESPN, I can't remember, but it was an interview with a scout where he said (paraphrasing) 'what we're looking for is someone who can grow, someone who's not the finished product'. Oh, I found it, it was ESPN. 'I'm looking for late bloomers.' Basically, players have a ten year NFL window where they're good, if they're good. He wants guys who haven't started theirs yet for whatever reason. Either they're young, or they're new to the game or whatever. Well Ade Aruna is just the kind of guy he's talking about, and he's also the kind of guy who goes higher than we think he will. He played his first down of football as a senior in high school, so he's got all the rawness you'd expect him to have. Nothing surprising about that. But man, what a specimen. We all saw it at the combine 6'6, 262, turned in a 4.6 forty and led all defensive linemen with a 38.5 inch vert. Good wingspan huge hands. He's not the bendiest guy in the world but he's not stiff either, and he's built like a brick shithouse. And he's just getting started. Give him two or three years in an NFL strength and condition program and no one will be able to keep him from setting the edge. He's a project, for sure, but he's the kind of project NFL teams are always taking chances on. Sometimes they work out (Michael Strahan, Terrell Owens, Jamie Collins, Terron Armstead, Larry Allen), sometimes they don't (literally hundreds of dudes), but NFL teams are gonna keep taking them.

We all fell in love with Cappa's vicious tape when they showed it over and over again at both the Senior Bowl and the combine, but I think we fall into a trap of overrating nasty players (Teller, Ragnow, Harrison Phillips, etc...), especially when they play along the lines. It's easy to love those guys, granted, and it's a plus trait on any prospect, but unless they bring more translatable skills to the table (a la Quenton Nelson), a mean streak isn't gonna be enough to sustain a successful career. I remember reading plenty about Ereck Flowers's mean streak back in 2015 (it's true, google it), and look where that's got him. We can't write off Jonathan Bullard yet but he's struggled so far and he too was lauded for his nastiness. Billy Turner, Ra'Shede Hageman, Chance Warmack. Eric Fisher. It's a nice characteristic for a player to have, but it's more of a bonus. Another check in the 'pros' column. But it shouldn't outweigh their weaknesses; sheer nastiness can't overcome a hefty 'cons' column. So, why am I bringing this up now, when I have the Chiefs drafting a nasty player ahead of his draft grade? I can't remember, honestly. I had an idea when I started then I trudged along and this is what came out. Oh wait, I remember, I was gonna say something about how Cappa's viewed as a nasty, effort guy, but I think he's more like Nelson with some real, translatable skills. That was my point. For one, I don't think he's being given enough credit for his athleticism. On tape, I see a guy who ought to be able to hold up at tackle, and though he struggled some early in the week, I thought eventually the Senior Bowl bore that out. He'll need to improve his footwork no surprise coming from a D2 school but once he does I think it will complement his quickness. What I'm getting at here is I think he can be a left tackle (and maybe finally oust nasty Fisher... and here I'm using 'nasty' in a different way). Regardless, I think Cappa will appeal to the Chiefs first for his versatility. He's got the athleticism to play either tackle spot and the strength (and demeanor) to play guard. In two or three years I think he'll be starting somewhere along the Chiefs line, and that makes him worth a fourth round pick.

We've all made the connection between the Raiders new DB coach (Derrick Ansley) and Minkah Fitzpatrick in the first. Ansley coached Minkah last year as the DB coach at Alabama, and the way Saban spews love for Minkah, you have to think his position coach feels the same way. That match didn't work out in the first as the Raiders opted to trade down, but what about now, with a different Alabama DB? Averett's a great athlete and has all the technique that comes from starting at the position for two years at Alabama. If you want a CB who's gonna cover a guy, Averett's gonna have some appeal. He's a hard guy for WRs to shake. And he's got great reaction time to everything happening around him. He's not a playmaker which is why he won't go earlier. He'll be stuck on a guy's hip but he won't turn and find the ball. He actually reminds me quite a bit of Chris Houston. They're roughly the same height (5'11 and 6'0), they both ran in the 4.3s, and they both have similar issues with the ball in the air. That comp is gonna make Falcons fans cringe he really struggled in Atlanta with that specific aspect of his game but most of my fellow Lions fans remember him fondly. He was our number one guy for a few years and improved dramatically at playing the ball. He still got beat from time to time, but he was nowhere near as rough for us as he'd been in Atlanta and was absolutely a legitimate #1 CB. I don't know if Averett will follow a similar trajectory, I only know his issues are in fact fixable, despite some people saying they aren't. And with his cover skills, if he fixes his ball skills, he would wind up as the best CB in the class.
He is smaller than the rest of the CBs on their team but he has good enough speed to make up for it. He should come in and be their nickel corner right away.

Arden Key is a high-risk high-reward player who a team may try and gamble on. He is a lengthy, natural pass-rusher with a legit arsenal of pass-rush moves and an excellent bend-and-rip. His run defense is hit or miss, leaving me to believe he's better off in a 3-4 OLB role. Key brings a lot of red flags due to leaving the team early in the season and struggling with his playing weight, but his pass-rushing talent could be there for the taking. For a young and upcoming team like Chicago, with a lot of solid playmakers on defense but a tough division, I could see them being the ones to gamble on Key. They don't really have a true pass-rusher on roster, and after the top guys it's kind of slim pickings on that department.

Les Snead has never been one to shy away from character concerns, and I don’t see why he’d stop now. To be entirely fair, Key appears to have a “different” kind of character concerns. He doesn’t appear to be troublesome, but he did have some personal issues to get over this past year. The exact nature of those issues is still unknown to the public, but reports say Key interviewed well at the Combine, so I don’t see his stock being destroyed too badly. The Rams are the kind of organization to take a chance on a top-10 talent with red flags, and they do so right here.

This is a risky pick, and honestly not sure will happen since the Bears typically shy away from "character concerns" Key has stated that he is an open book and will sit down to discuss what he was facing when he left his team at LSU. This pick if it pans out could be a solid steal for the Bears.

At this point of the draft it's about talent over need. I wouldn't advocate a strict BPA approach, but it's absolutely where the grades start to separate and teams begin drafting guys who might not fill their biggest holes, but who sit atop their boards. Despite signing the Honey Badger during the offseason the Texans could still use some help at safety. Andre Hal has been far better that they could have ever hoped, but he's limited as a player, and he's not the sort of guy who's gonna stop the Texans from taking a safety if one sits atop their board (and it's telling, I think, that they keep bringing 2 4th round safeties in for visits). Armani Watts is a guy they've brought in, and I imagine they've seen plenty of him as he plays his collegiate ball up the road in College Station. Houston has done a good job in the offseason of stopping the bleeding in their secondary (especially with the addition of Mathieu) but adding Watts to it does more than stop the bleeding, it makes it a strength. Plus I think he and Mathieu complement each other well, Watts is a rangy athlete who's one of the better cover safeties in the draft, and he's a good playmaker too. Where he struggles is in run support where he can be hit or miss, and he's a little bit too much of a risk taker. Mathieu will cover for a lot of those issues. I know the Texans have needs on the edge and along the interior of the line, but the value doesn't match up here, or they can be addressed later. You're not finding a guy who fits like a glove the way Watts does if you wait any longer than this.
Eric Berry is one, if not, the best SS in the entire league, but the Chiefs don’t have a coverage-oriented complement to him. Armani Watts is perfect for that role.

The Vikings need offensive line help, here's offensive line help. There's not much separating Corbett, Ragnow, and Braden Smith (not to mention some of the tackles) and I expect they'll fall in different orders on different teams' boards, but I like Corbett's upside best due to his smarts, the calm with which he plays, the way he rises to the occasion (I thought he was the best offensive lineman at the Senior Bowl), his leadership, and all the shit he's had to overcome to make it to this point. Five years ago you would never have expected him to be here, and I like the guys who overcome the odds. I like that kind of drive. I also like the way he models his game after fellow Nevada alum Joel Bitonio, who I think is one of the best guards in the league. Like, he hovered around him as a freshman and studied him, the way he prepared, his calmness, the way he interacted with his teammates. It almost sounds a little bit stalker y, to be honest, but I'm sure big bro Joel was cool with it. That's a good role model to have, considering how good he turned out as a pro. And I think Corbett could be better.

In fact, he's the only OL guy they've brought in for a private visit worth a first rounder. Also in fact, they need OL help, or Russell is going to have a short career with Andrew Luck.
This narrative has already been written. Price fits in right alongside Elflin and fills a need for the Vikings at Guard. While being able to pick up the Giants 4th round selection (108).
Another easy pick here. Price is very talented and could start as soon as that injury heals.
The Price was right ;)

As a Vikings fan, I know we need interior lineman bad, and any 3-round mock that doesn’t have them taking an interior lineman in the first 3 rounds should be tossed aside.  Price can play at all the interior line positions, bolstering the interior with Elflein.
Can start at guard or center, may miss a bit of camp but the injury doesn't seem serious enough to drop him down on the draft board.
Giants need Line help, Price falls becauase of his injury, he can play anywhere IOL.

The Bucs move up a few spots here to slide into the end of the first round a grab that valuable 5th year option on the rookie deal. Billy Price's freak injury was unfortunate at the combine, but it allows him to fall a bit here. Tampa gets a OL that can take JR Sweezy's place on the line, but he can also spot start in other positions when injuries occur.
The Vikings need to protect that shiny expensive QB so they grab a great interior blocker who is athletic and strong.
Price is the best Center in the draft, and Chargers try to shore up their OL by taking him here.
Minnesota needs to protect Kirk cousins and they get a guy who definitely could have gone higher had it not been for the injury during the bench press at the combine.
Another Buckeye for the interior of MIN's line
Not worried about the pec injury, the Vikes get Price who can play all over the interior of their line

I keep seeing like, 4th & 5th round grades on HIll, and I'm like, what? Did you see the way he dominated all those stud linemen at the Senior Bowl? Will Hernandez? Step aside. Tyrell Crosby? Out of my way. Wyatt Teller? Please. I have to admit I was like, damn, who is that guy? So I poured over his tape and I came to the conclusion he was vastly underrated (I had him going even higher than this in my first mock), would be a perfect fit as a big, penetrating tackle in a 4 3, and hoping like hell he didn't end up on the Vikings. So thanks Falcons, for ensuring he didn't end up on the Vikings. I guarantee Hill's going higher than he's projected to go, one of those guys who all the experts call a surprise when his name gets read, but who anyone paying attention will be expecting. Guys with his skill set just don't last very long in the draft. I think he has a chance to be better than some of the guys who went in the first. And while on the surface he might not look like the freaky Sparq athletes the Falcons tend to like, if you dig a little deeper into the numbers, you'll find he has the fifth highest rating of the 26 guys who are listed at 310+. Comparing him to the 290 pound guys is an injustice, those guys play different roles. And the Falcons brass has spent a lot of the pre draft process meeting with him, that's gotta be a good sign.

Hill is a riser due to an excellent senior bowl week. He performed very well against some of the best guards in the draft. He is a decent athlete but has had trouble translating that into his playing game consistently. Should be a solid prospect with a chance for further development

As of this moment, the Chiefs have not retained Bennie Logan, so finding a replacement is paramount. B.J. Hill had nice production in college, but his athletic ability still give him plenty of room to grow. He’s intriguing.

Hill had a great combine and the Dolphins have a gap left by Suh. While he probably doesn't bring as much inside pressure as Suh hes definatley a good run blocker and has the athletic potential to add some sacks.
Scarbough would be a nice 1-2 punch with Drake, Scarbough can do the heavy work with Drake being the feature back.

Eric Wood's gone. Richie Incognito's gone (probably). Russell Bodine might suck. John Miller and Vlad Ducasse might really suck. Ryan Groy's good, and they've added Tyrell Crosby to the mix, but that's not enough. You can't have Shady running behind a buncha broke linemen. You can't roll McCarron or Rudolph out behind that. You gotta upgrade. Smith's one of those mid round rocks you can toss into your line and look up ten years later and he's still there, a set it and

The Cowboys are in a rare position of needing help on the OL and they are fortunate to find Braden Smith available here. Smith has a high ceiling but needs to improve his technical schools as a blocker

As they shuffle around their line, they need to find the best possible additions, and Smith is a plug and play Guard who can improve the chance of Luck surviving a season, and helping their run game without Gore

As they shuffle around their line, they need to find the best possible additions, and Smith is a plug and play Guard who can improve the chance of Luck surviving a season, and helping their run game without Gore
Vikings biggest need is OL. Smith offers versatility along the offensive front.

The Vikings badly need an interior lineman and this pick is between Billy Price and Braden Smith. I think Price is a better prospect, but Smith does not have the potential injury concern, which leads the Vikings to see him as a safer pick.

Similar to the Giants, the Colts right side of the line talent, and that's an issue given Andrew Luck's health. Indy would be smart to target the top OL on the board, and in this case that's Auburn's Braden Smith. Smith is a powerful blocker who can drive down in the run game and anchor well in the pass game. Smith played a lot of RT at Auburn, and is definitely capable of kicking out if need be.

Denver’s OL was very poor in 2017, but some of that had to do with health. The return of Ronald Leary and trading to acquire Jared Veldheer really only leaves the Broncos with one glaring hole at RG. Braden Smith fills that hole at a solid value.
The Bucs have to shore up their offensive line, especially at Guard. Smith achieves that here.
Jags get the best OG OTB and fill a big need.
He is a good OG
Braden Smith has perfect size and very good technique, he'll start day 1 and looks to be a solid guard for aslong as the Bucs need him to.

Similar to the Giants, the Colts right side of the line talent, and that's an issue given Andrew Luck's health. Indy would be smart to target the top OL on the board, and in this case that's Auburn's Braden Smith. Smith is a powerful blocker who can drive down in the run game and anchor well in the pass game. Smith played a lot of RT at Auburn, and is definitely capable of kicking out if need be.
The Colts finally address their offensive loan issues with a guard who has a few holes in his game but should be an upgrade on what they have currently.

Another guard! I don't know what the record is for interior Olineman being selected in the first round is, but this year that record might be broken. The Vikings need Olineman pretty badly. They're spending $28m/yr on Cousins, so they better protect him. Like the Jaguars they could also use an upgrade at OT as well, but ultimately Braden Smith is the best non-Center remaining. And the Vikings have that spot locked.

I don't think it's gonna be easy for the Browns to trade down from four, that's how much they like Chubb. In fact I think they like him so much, they'll make a quick move back up. Did they immediately have seller's remorse after trading with the Bucs, or was this their plan all along? I can't say. But what they get out of essentially moving down one spot is the 38th pick in the second round instead of the 64th. All the rest of their picks are the same (well, now they've got the 113th pick in the fourth round instead of the 114th, so basically the same). I'd call that a win. And they got the guy they wanted at four anyway. I think they really, really, really like Chubb. I've thought it for over a month now, before all the silly season stuff really started to heat up, and I'm still thinking it now. So they hop back up from seven and over the Colts to grab him. Like everyone else, I imagine the Broncos were targeting Barkley, but there's lots of good backs in this draft, I don't think they'll do anything rash. And for those of you thinking the Broncos will target Rosen here, see above. I think Rosen's gonna be a hard guy to pull the trigger on. I think if Mayfield or Darnold or maybe even Allen were here, Elway might jump. But I can't see it for Rosen. We all know about his physical gifts and I'm in agreement, I think he's the most gifted QB overall of all these guys. But we also know there's more to playing QB in the league than talent, and to me, that's where Rosen doesn't measure up (again, see Jets pick above for my explanation). I don't think he'll be scared off by Rosen's intelligence or curiosity, I think that stuff's way overblown. But the teammates don't love him thing? That's real. That's... well, like I said, Rosen might be a dick. An immobile dick, with injury concerns. And then there's that business of football being his A#1 pursuit right now, but who knows what the future holds. Come again? Is this gonna be another Jake Plummer situation where he falls in love with Handball, or in Rosen's case, space travel or some shit? That's concerning, and I don't think Elway will take him. I think Rosen will make him nervous this high. I also don't think the Broncos will want to drop below ten, which rules out the Dolphins, Bills and Cardinals as trade partner, unless they get blown away. The trade with Cleveland isn't blown away, but it's a good enough haul, to add a second round pick for dropping two spots. And most importantly, it keeps them in the top ten.

Tampa is in a great spot with 4 QBs off the board in the first 5 picks. They have strong needs at RB, OL, and DL and the 3 best non-QB prospects play those positions. They can pretty much take whoever falls to them.

TRADE. The Texans give the Browns a third round pick and next year's first round pick to move to #4 overall. JJ Watt was a great player but age caught up to him. He's also not as athletic or strong as needed for the position. Never was. Chubb will make everyone forget Watt altogether.

Indianapolis produced the second lowest sack total in 2017 with just 25.0. Adding Chubb, the top pass-rusher in the class, immediately upgrades the defense for the Colts, who already have promising pieces in the secondary.
As tempted as they would be to move down, the Colts didn't want to go past 6 for a reason. They get their guy and are damn happy about it.

But Saquon! But Nelson! But - they have Marlon Mack so they could likely use a compliment instead of a feature back, and the now have a bevy of picks in the 2nd to nab some IOL help. Chubb comes to his expected destination here.

Combine motor and athleticism, and you get Bradley Chubb. Combine Bradley Chubb and Myles Garrett, and you have a scary death machine of a pass-rush in Cleveland. With the Browns bringing in Hyde, I highly doubt that the Browns will want to waste any of their top 5 picks on him. Saquon Barkley has a chance at becoming the best RB ever, but in Cleveland's eyes, I think it's easy for them to pass up on him when you consider what they have already at the position, and what they could have on defense when bringing in Chubb.
Back on the clock, the Browns nab Chubb. He's fallen outrageously far considering his talent. You can hear the NFL.com writers typing 'Have the Browns won the offseason!?!?!?!' already.
I like Henry Anderson and Margus Hunt had a nice season in 2017, but the Colts need DE help. Chubb gives Indy a blue-chip defensive prospect.
I have not been overly impressed with Chubb, or this Edge class in general, but Indy's very pressing need for pass rushing help makes this the pick. I went back and forth with Chubb and Roquon Smith.
Browns skip on barkley because of the deep draft at HB. Pair Chubb with Garrett for a great pass rush for 5 years

After trading down with New York, the Colts are in great position to still grab a top talent while also loading up on second round draft picks to fill out the roster with talent. Bradley Chubb would be a logical choice for a defense lacking front-7 talent, and specifically a premier pass rusher. Jabaal Sheard is solid, but Chubb would bring an aggressive, high-motor pass rush to the Colts defense. His bend is a slight concern, but his explosiveness and hand usage should make him a high floor defensive end who will also be a force against the run.

Colts GM Chris Ballard must be happy teams pick QBs so high. He 
walks out of the draft as a winner as well by getting the player he was 
most likely going to pick at 3 anyways and gets 3 second rounders to 
show for it. Chubb is one heck of a player that should transform the 
Colts stagnant pass rush but do be wary of his overall agility with a 
less than spectacular 3 cone drill at the combine.

I'm not convinced it's an incredibly strong DE class, so maybe pouncing on Chubb isn't a bad thing, as he is the only truly elite (albeit likely benefiting from a weak class) talent at DE I see here, and pair him with Myles Garrett. DE is a premium position, and you want them cheap. Also, I just don’t see how they can afford to give Hyde, DJ, and Barkley the contracts that they would be, unless they let DJ go, which would be absolutely ridiculous.

The Colts were made an offer they couldn’t refuse by the Jets to move down to #6. They pick up two 2nd-round picks this year and one in the future, while still grabbing the best defensive player in the draft. Chubb was likely the guy they were taking at #3 anyways. Indy has Jabaal Sheard, but after switching to a 4-3 this offseason, they need to grab someone better than Margus Hunt or Tarrell Basham to start across from him, since John Simon, the Colts’ starter opposite Sheard in their 3-4, is better suited for a SAM LB role in their new scheme.

Best player available here. If a quarterback needy team gets ansty, Cleveland could entertain a trade back. It is a little to high to select Denzel Ward, and there is solid depth at cornerback in this class. Forming a pass-rushing trio of Garrett, Ogbah, and Chubb would be terrifying foro AFC North offensive lines to deal with. No coach has ever said no to more pass rushers.
As many teams lately have shown, you win big games with big defense. Chubb provides an extra line of terror for the Browns.
The colts get a very solid edge defender at number 6 after the trade down. The draft has deep depth at running back, more than edge, this is the reason for Chubb over Barkley.
This pick is both BPA and who I think is the best option for them. Chubb on one side and Garrett on the other is scary.
The Colts need defense and what better to solidify a defense than a quick, elusive pass-rusher.
colts will be rocking a FULL chubb w this one
Unexpected but ELITE
The Colts grab the best EDGE prospect in this draft, and probably the best defensive prospect in the draft.  They are in dire need of a pass rusher.
Chubb's the BPA here, I know they got Thomas last year who's a very similar edge player but this is such a key position and one where it's better to have too much rather than too little.
Although I see Chubb as a top 15 pick in last years draft, hes still the best EDGE player available. They could go Nelson here but I think Chubb will be more impactful earlier on.
The most complete Edge. Talent, positional value, and need align
The Colts have a ton of needs, so trading down was the right move. They still end up with Chubb at 6 and extra draft picks from the Jets trade.

Many believe that Josh Rosen is the pick to be made here, but knowingDave Gettleman he is going after the best Hog Molly in the draft. Bradley Chubb steps in and replaces JPP to become the next elite DE for the Giants. Prior to the JPP trade I had considered going with Barkley here to give Eli an effective ground game and take some pressure off himself. I believe Eli has a few more decent years left in him and a developmental QB will be available later on.

Buffalo, like the Jets, also need a day one guy. They don't see the value in trading their entire arsenal for someone who will need to develop for a few years and they hold off on trading with the Browns. The Browns have tons of picks though and try to mirror their first round pick from last year. Chubb is an outstanding defensive end who totally demolished players across from him, with two 10 sack seasons back to back. He may not be Myles Garrett, but without a doubt a nasty edge rusher you want on your team.
Hue is on record saying he would love to have Chubb, and given that QB is resolved, he's the Best Player Available.

Browns resist the trade down offers as they look to finally use the draft capital they have to get their guys now. They take the best defensive player in this draft and a surefire difference maker to put alongside Myles Garrett

Cleveland has a roster with a decent amount of holes, but they can kind of afford a luxury pick here at 4, so they do just that and take Bradley Chubb. Although Chubb's combine left a bit to be desired (especially that 3-cone drill), he is by far the best pass rusher in this draft class and still worth a top-10 selection. The Browns improve their defensive line with the talented Chubb to place alongside Miles Garrett, terrifying AFC North quarterbacks for years to come.
An athletic machine with comparable grades to some of the better edge rushers in recent years. His size and athleticism should allow him to join this DL immediately and made an impact

If I were Cleveland I would use this pick to provide a weapon such as Saqon Barkley or Derrius Guice to help Sam Darnold. But they apparently love Bradley Chubb and have him rated as their best player in the entire draft. The addition of Chubb gives Cleveland a scary young duo on the offensive line with 2017 #1 overall pick Myles Garrett.

I have Barkley ranked above Chubb but I still have Chubb as a blue chip prospect and he plays a much more valuable position. Plus, I love Carlos Hyde and a Hyde/Duke Johnson combo is well above average already. Ogbah is decent but I'm not letting him stop me from drafting a blue chip edge prospect. Furthermore you can rotate Garrett, Chubb, and Ogbah and run some nascar packages where you can have all 3 of them on the field on 3rd downs.
Big debate in the war room between Chubb and Barkley, but the Colts go for the premium position and wait on RB until pick 36/37.

I've been projecting this pick since before the CFB season even ended. A lot of fans will want the Browns to trade down, but that would be a mistake imo. Chubb, while isn't that level of EDGE that a Myles Garrett, Mack, or Miller are, he's still a stud. Ultimately EDGE is the most important non-qb position on the team. And combining Chubb with Garrett will form a awesome duo for at least the next 5 years. You build a Defense starting with the DL then DBs. And the Browns still have a bunch of picks in the top100 to get studs later in the draft, and even trade back up if they want. The only team I'd even consider trading down to would be the Bills for both 1sts, Then draft Landry and a DB.

Man the Browns are in a good spot this year. John Dorsey must be like a kid in a candy shop with all these picks. Does he trade this one and acquire even more draft capital? I think it all depends on what happens with that 2nd pick. Maybe we even see a situation similar to SF-CHI where Denver comes up one spot just incase. If they do stand in here and draft I think the easy choice is Bradley Chubb. Pairing him with Myles Garrett should be terrifying for every offensive line on their schedule. Being able to grab the best 2 DE prospects in back to back drafts and a franchise QB? That is a recipe for future success.Now about that coach..

With Rosen still on the board it's very possible any of Buf/Ari/Den jump to this spot. If Cleveland stays I expect them to continue building there DL and pairing Chubb with Myles. It's going to be awful playing OT against the Browns this season.
A slight overdraft but worth it. Huge upside and a high-effort player

I feel like a broken record, but Speaks is another tough evaluation. I guess it makes sense that the fourth rounders are tough evaluations. If they were easy they'd all be first rounders or UDFAs, one end of the spectrum or the other. These are the guys that fall somewhere in between, the ones with good tape and bad tape, great tape and awful tape; freaky athleticism but little production, little athleticism and freaky production. The paradoxes, the yeah, buts. But at this point he's good value for what he might be able to do, which again, is something you can say about a lot of fourth rounders. It's a little disconcerting that he was essentially a non
Tremendously athletic but he has trouble putting it all together on the field. Could use some coaching but has tons of potential
Speeks is another sleeper in this draft. He could come in as a rotational edge rusher and will contribute well.

Yes, the Panthers have more of a need at WR, RB, S, probably the interior of the line, you get the idea. Everyone's full of needs right now. But I keep saying it, in the third round and especially the fourth round, that's when the picks start to take on a BPA feel. That's when you got more of your WTFs, and your WhoTFs, and your 'I've heard of that guy, who says I haven't?' Cause you can't really count on a third or fourth rounder to step in and play right away, can you? So how is it filling a need? I mean, you hope they can handle it, but more often than not they can't, and that doesn't make them bad picks. These are ten year investments, if you do it right. (And there are just so many WRs left and so few OTs).  On that note, Matt Kalil still sucks, right? I haven't watched him as much since he left Minny, but I remember him sucking pretty hard, and I haven't really heard anything coming out of Charlotte to the contrary. I know you're tied to him for awhile but he's got an out on his contract after next year, maybe start thinking about what's next? I know Moton was a second round 2017 grab, but he's more of a guard/right tackle kinda guy, right? O'Neill pure left side, baby. He's also a bit of a project, but man if he comes good...

I really like O’Neill’s fit in Minnesota. He’s the epitome of the type of offensive lineman John DeFilippo’s caters to. I believe he could realistically play any OL position except for C in the ZBS Flip will implement in Minnesota. He can play inside for a few years, while being groomed to eventually take over at left or right tackle.
O'Neill is the Belle of the Ball to many scouts and pundits, he will need to get stronger to remain competitive but would be a good fit here in LA.

O'Neil has all the physical traits of a good tackle, he's also very athletic and aslong as you are versatile you can fit in on the Patriots line. If he strengthens up I could see him starting at LT next season.
A third straight OT to close out round one. Adding a future starter to keep Wentz upright

Another draft crush for the Pats. OT is a huge need for the Pats (I need to see Garcia play before I crown him LT of the future). They just missed out on McGlinchey and Miller in the first, but no matter, I think O'Neil has the highest ceiling for any OT in the draft, but he needs a little seasoning to be ready.

The SuperBowl Champs! They could adds a WR for Wentz making Kirk an option and maybe another RB behind Ajayi, making Guice an option. But Jason Peters is old and coming off an ACL. The primary need is protecting Wentz for the future. They need a LT. O'Neil is that guy. They can add DBs and Offensive weapons later in the draft. Getting that guy to protect Wentz is priority #1.

Eagles may need a new OT very soon so they grab the best on the board, and possibly the BPA. O'Neil is still learning but has a ceiling of a Franchise LT. He can fit in well here and be a fixture as a Swing until the time comes to start

They can kick Remmers inside and feel safe with O'Neill as an RT as he continues to grow and mold his craft. He's a safe starter and has star potential, and with the turn around their line made last year, this is a good environment to grow in
Ereck Flowers improved slightlty last year, but is still underperforming. The Solder signing locks down the left side, but the right side is still left with some questions.

Losing Nate Solder hurts, and the Patriots will likely give 2nd-year player Antonio Garcia get the first crack at replacing him, but they still need to add competition for the LT spot. Brian O'Neill is an incredibly high upside prospect, but still needs a lot of time to develop, specifically in the weight room. He is an incredibly athlete for his size, excellent as a lead blocker, and he has very workable footwork and technique. Functional strength and hand usage is easily the biggest issue, and time in an NFL weight program could do him well. Dante Scarnecchia has an excellent track record getting the best out of his linemen, and if he can harness O'Neill's athleticism, he could easily be a franchise LT.
O'Neill can start day 1 on the right for the reigning champs and eventually move over to the blind side. Hope you like it Eagle bros.
Absolute STEAL of the draft OT3

Losing Nate Solder hurts, and the Patriots will likely give 2nd-year player Antonio Garcia get the first crack at replacing him, but they still need to add competition for the LT spot. Brian O'Neill is an incredibly high upside prospect, but still needs a lot of time to develop, specifically in the weight room. He is an incredibly athlete for his size, excellent as a lead blocker, and he has very workable footwork and technique. Functional strength and hand usage is easily the biggest issue, and time in an NFL weight program could do him well. I thought about having the Eagles trade down, but I don't know of anyone who has extreme value in the first round here. So the Eagles get a tackle that can contribute early... even if it is a tad bit of a reach.
Ronnie Stanley has Left Tackle locked up but Baltimore needs a tackle on the other side from him and O'Neill slots in there well.

I expect the Falcons might get a lot of trade action on this pick, but in the end I think there are two or three guys they decide are too good to pass up on. Now, I'm the one always saying WRs go higher than we think, it's like my draft day mantra. Then I did this mock and they didn't, so what gives? Well after careful consideration, I'm thinking this year that might not be true. There are a couple of drafts over the past decade where WRs didn't go higher than we thought they would, and this draft just feels so jumbled at the top (and deep), it's difficult to justify grabbing one early. I'm sure some FO is gonna fall in love with a guy and snag him before we think he will, but I've kinda already had that happening with Sutton (the most likely guy to be grabbed early, I think, given his unique skill set amongst the top rated guys). This pick, even, while lower than we thought Ridley would go overall is higher than we had the Falcons drafting a WR. I'm sure most of their fans are coming into this draft thinking WR is a 2
I'm sure Ravens fans are pretty bored with this pick but he is just a great fit. They will feel better about it when he is beating Steelers DBs across the field for a huge gain.

Ridley slides in the draft, but the Saints will grab him at 27th overall. Ridley, who is the best pure route runner in the class, can fit in the slot or on the outside, versatility that will be valuable for the Saints who have another dominant outside receiver in Michael Thomas. There are questions about Ridley’s size and age, but the value at 27th overall for who some argue is the best receiver in the class is too good to pass up.
Ridley is the most Pro Ready receiver, and Ozzie loves Bama guys more than Bama guys like their cousins. It‘s mocked a ton, but not for unfounded reason. Just ask Marlon Humphrey.
Ridley is the most Pro Ready receiver, and Ozzie loves Bama guys more than Bama guys like their cousins. It‘s mocked a ton, but not for unfounded reason. Just ask Marlon Humphrey.

For anyone wondering why I have WRs like Calvin Ridley going so late in the first, the reason is because they are all WR's I wouldn't take within the first 20 picks. That isn't a knock on Calvin Ridley, I just think that his talent level is on par with this pick in this range. Calvin Ridley is fast, and a very polished route runner. WR is a need for the Falcons, especially after losing Gabriel. Calvin Ridley is a great pick to revamp the WR corp, and take attention away from just Julio Jones.
He's fallen kinda far, and he's really quite a good player. He'll help Stafford out and I feel like he just sort of fits in at about this spot.
Most pro ready WR, crisp on routes, a little on the old side, but should contribute to the Browns passing attack immediately.

Some have soured on him recently but Ridley is pro ready and versatile. Baltimore's need for receiving help is less desperate after signing Brown and Crabtree, but the need is still fairly severe, and Ridley is a safe pick.
Baltimore need a WR desperately, Ridley is old and slow but is the most WR1 ready prospect in the draft

Following the somewhat surprising release of Dez Bryant, Dallas's WR corp is in pretty rough shape with only Allen Hurns, T-Will, and Cole Beasley. Dallas has been eyeing up a handful of top WRs, and the release of Dez indicates that they may have their guy. To me, Calvin Ridley is the best fit with Dak Prescott's game. Ridley is a very smooth route runner with good hands and solid agility, and he makes his money on intermediate routes which is perfect for Dak. Instead of trying to force the ball to a jump-ball WR like Dez, Dak can focus now on hitting precise routes to a guy like Ridley.

Calvin Ridley is the 1st WR to be taken off the board all the way down
at #16. I think Ridley is the perfect number 2 receiver and will 
complement Michael Crabtree and elevate the Ravens offense that
hasn't showed much progress since they won the Super Bowl 6 years
ago. Ridley is the best route runner in the class and could
really have an impact on whatever team drafts him because of his
speed and separation skills.

I can't have you guys passing on what's considered the #1 WR in the class, even if it is a somewhat weak WR class. Unless Dez comes to Baltimore, I just don’t know how to change this one to anyone not WR.

Trade details: GB trades picks #45 and 101 | CLE trades pick #35 After the release of Jordy Nelson for financial reasons, the Packers find themselves with a need at WR opposite Davante Adams. Ridley falling presented the Packers with a value scenario they could refuse. Ridley is definitely one of the 32 best players in this draft, and I had been considering him since the Ravens at pick #16. I just didn’t like him as a fit more than another player until now.

This is probably the most common pick among mocks. I was really tempted to put both Derrius Guice and Leighton Vander Esch here, but instead to add to their receiver depth. It's commonly known that Ozzie Newsome loves Alabama players, this pick makes sense.

I like the Jags to take Ridley as they need a competent 3rd receiver and honestly a trio of Ridley, Lee and Moncrief has the potential to make Bortles look good, even though they’re all probably WR2 material. TE is a bigger need, but that class is deep and none of them make sense for a first round pick, if Ridley hits the Jags stand be in contention for the super bowl once again

Ridley can be a very valuable slot weapon for the Falcons. Gabriel had been productive in that role under Shanahan but he has left to Chicago. Ridley will be very good in the short and intermediate, and over the middle.
Dissapointed that Lamar didn't fall the Cards decided to get current QB Sam Bradford some much needed help to throw too.
After trading Kelvin Benjamin, the Panthers need some targets to give to Cam Newton. Ridley could be a day one starter and fill that role perfectly.
the 47 year old finds a home
Solid choice
Pretty boring pick at this point, but Ridley belongs to the Ravens.  Their GM loves Bama players, and it’s relatively good value here as the first receiver off the board.
I'm not super high on this WR class but Ridley is far and away the best one and he's very good value this far down.

The late run on receivers continues. Tennessee’s biggest need is probably DE, but with Landry and Hubbard off the board there are no viable options here. Sure they spent their first round pick on a WR last year, but they still could use more receivers for Mariota to throw to. Ridley is considered a “safe” pick. Gotta get Cam some protection and some weapons. Fortunately for them Calvin Ridley is still on the board. His age is a major concern for me, but he's still a top 3 WR in this class. That said there next biggest need is WR. Even if he had an unspectacular combine and is maybe a little older than people would like the tape doesn't lie. Ridley is going to be a great #2 in this league unlike a lot of 1st WRs lately will make an impact this season.

Calvin Ridley as somehow become underrated throughout the draft process by a surprising amount of people. I can understand concerns after his average combine and the fact that he's 24 but his tape is fantastic. One of the best Route Runners in the class he should easily be able to get separation at this level and make whatever team he goes to better.

The Colts are shifting to a zone defense that may or may not have some Tampa 2 elements (Colts fans weren't exactly sure in the forums I visited). On top of that, Ballard's on record as liking tall, long CBs. Davis, at 6'1 and with freakishly long arms, fits his type. To me, Davis is a steal here. I have him rated in my top three at CB, right behind Ward and Alexander. I just think he's a battler. Yes, he'll get a penalty here and there while he's battling, but give me a guy like that any day. He's huge for a corner, his press is great, and I just can't shake the tape against Mike Williams. I thought he gave the future first rounder more trouble than any DB Williams faced. I love the idea of him playing for Indy, I think he'll be perfect in your zone. It wouldn't surprise me at all if he ends up being the best CB in the draft. As it stands the Colts have Quincy Wilson, himself a second rounder last year who certainly flashed, and Pierre Desir, who's bounced around the league for awhile. They absolutely have to add another body into the mix.
Stopping the pass is a huge key to success in the NFL. With their first two picks in the draft the Raiders look to improve theirs. Davis is a fast lanky corner and could be a pro bowler for years

A steal here, but that's just how things shake out. They find a replacement in their CB corps, and have a young promising player to contribute to give trouble to opposing WRs. Also, value over everything here.

A steal here, but that's just how things shaked out. They find a replacement in their CB corps, and have a young promising player to contribute to give trouble to opposing WRs. Also, value over everything here.
Physical corner to pair up with Patrick Peterson.

Trading away Marcus Peters was one of the most shocking moves in the offseason, and they haven't done much to replace him. Landing Kendall Fuller for Alex Smith was excellent, but he's more of a slot CB (but he may have to play outside due to need). Regardless, improving their CB corp is a must, and getting a true man coverage CB like Carlton Davis could work well. Davis is extremely physical with opposing receivers right form the snap, and is an excellent hand-fighter. He struggles at times with opening his hips to defend inward-breaking routes, but the NFL is much more generous in allowing CBs to be physical to disrupt routes from the start.

Gaines, Cleveland is still looking for another starting outside corner, and Davis has an intriguing skill set for them.
Fuller and Amerson aren't enough after letting Peters go
Another player who was falling. I think Davis is a good fit in KC and gives them much needed help.
Yes
I like Davis more than most people, he's a big, physical receiver with good ball skills.

The Vikings have no problem dropping down a few spots to add a fourth rounder, and the 49ers have to get above the Seahawks (or at least they'll think they will) to grab the guy they want. It's hard to believe 20+ picks have come off the board since the last CB was drafted, but it goes to show the disparity between the top 6/7 guys and everyone else. I suspect it's also surprising to see that the next guy off the board is Ward, but I don't think it will be come draft day. Remember a couple of years back, when another DB from Middle Tennessee came off the board three picks from now, at the top of the third round? When the Titans drafted Kevin Byard we were all like, what? Well, a lot of us were anyway. And now he's coming off a season where he led the league in picks. I can see a similar draft trajectory for Ward, who's one of the best CBs who fit the "Seattle model" for the position. That is, he's got the long arms and the tall frame that teams who run Seattle's D want. On top of that he ran a 4.45 at his pro day and from what little tape I could find, he plays as fast as he times. I think he's the classic case of a guy some team's gonna fall in love with, then hear that a lot of other teams have sneakily fallen in love with him too (in Ward's case, that would be Atlanta, Seattle and the Chargers), and once the Falcons and Chargers pass on him, Lynch is gonna decide to jump the Seahawks to make sure they get him.

Calling Worley a safe LB is, in my opinion, a fair thing to do. He may not have highlight reel plays or be a 1st round name, but he shows up, does his job, and does it well, which is exactly what the Broncos need.

It's Ozzie's last draft, I say he's going for it, leave on a high note. I also think Kirk would have at least been in the discussion at nineteen, so when he drops and they have a chance to go up and get him, they do it. They've already added a third rounder to their haul thanks to their first round trade with Dallas, so they offer one of them to the Bears to come up. I know there's a lot of depth at WR and there would have been a lot of guys available at pick 52 (not to mention a bunch of TEs), but Kirk's a different kind of talent, and he can plug in as the Ravens returner right away. I suspect he's number one on a lot of boards at this point, and it's only the depth of the draft at his position and some needs elsewhere that sees him dropping. So I say the Ravens pounce, and totally remake their WR corps in a matter of two rounds. I imagine Chicago will consider picking him themselves before deciding that given all the WR depth they could use the extra pick (plus, it's becoming a thing that Pace trades down in the second round).

I don't think anyone is better than the Pittsburg Steelers at picking wide receivers. So the gears started spinning when I heard Kirk has a meeting with the Steelers on Friday. Bryant has crazy talent but it hasn't worked out yet and he is a free agent next year. Kirk could be an excellent slot receiver for the Steelers. He will see lots of looks with AB and Juju drawing extra defenders

They may need a different type of receiver, but you can't pass on value here for Kirk. He's an extremely talented WR who they can use to give Rodgers even more opportunities to move the ball downfield without Jordy.
BPA. Fills a need. What is there not to like? Also it will give their QB a chance to have more than one receiving option than Larry Fitz
Using the traded pick from the Patriots, the Cardinals pick up Kirk, who is a Golden Tate-type receiver who is great at finding soft spots in zones and great hands to go with it.

Jordy Nelson is officially out in Green Bay, and Randll Cobb probably doesn't have much longer either. Behind Davante Adams, it's pretty bare for Green Bay. Rodgers, for as good as he is, could use some more legit playmakers. Christian Kirk is one of the best WRs with the ball in his hand. He has explosive upfield speed and sharp cuts to work himself into space. He may project as a bit more of a slot WR due to his smaller frame, but his route-running makes him a very capable outside WR. Whether he plays outside or takes over for Cobb in the slot, he is a great weapon for Rodgers to utilize.

After this round, Denver has two picks in the fifth then they're done, so dropping down ten spots to add another fifth will appeal to them, especially since they’ve got so many other picks around here. For Dallas, they're shocked to see this big unit still on the board and decide to pounce. Okorafor's raw, but he's gigantic and athletic and those guys get drafted and those guys get played. I'm sure the plan is to plug Fleming in at RT and shift Collins back to guard (it has to be), so Chuks will be insurance in case Fleming doesn't work out at RT, insurance against another injury to Tyron Smith, or worst case a swing tackle (he has experience on both the right and left sides). If he can get some of his technique and consistency issues sorted out, he has a chance to man the right side in Dallas for a long, long time. And while they still need to add a linebacker or two, I'd bet almost any amount of money Jerry's got his eyes on Josey Jewell, who can maybe be had in the fifth or sixth. I'd be shocked if Dallas came out of the draft without him. Well, not shocked. Surprised, let's say that. No need for hyperbole.

Cleveland needs to invest in protecting Darnold. While I have seen some Browns fans say they're set at OT, I don't think you can have too much potential. Okorafor is a great athlete for his size but he need to get stronger and meaner

The good thing about the will he/won't he evaluation on Williams (or I suppose it's more like can he/can't he play tackle) is that the Giants have needs all over their offensive line, and it's no secret they want to fix it. Gettleman actually said as much publicly, and they're in a good spot to do it, even if they stay put. But Williams's versatility makes him a special case, and there's a lot of teams around here looking at offensive linemen, especially ones with the potential to play both tackle and guard (including the hated Eagles, at the next pick). If we look at Williams's pre 2017 tape, you'd think you were watching a top 10 pick. Then 2017 happened, and things fell apart a little bit for him. I did like the way he came back after injury, though. That was more like the guy from before, and a good sign that Williams is on his way back to being that guy. Sure, the Giants have a lot of other needs too, especially since they're switching to a new defensive scheme, but they're not gonna fill them all in this draft. It's just not doable. That's why the trade up makes sense for a guy like Williams. Get the best guys, not the most guys. It'll be nice to have his fifth year option too. From the Seahawks perspective, they need better picks, and they often trade down from the late first. This will surprise exactly no one.
The Bills traded OT Cordy Glenn to move up to 12 and get their QB of the future. They use the 22nd pick to get younger at LT and protect their most important asset.

The Giants don't need a new QB, they need to protect the one they have. The center and guard positions are rock solid but right and left tackle need upgrades. Williams will slot in to the LT position immediately.

Ravens go pure BPA here and the pick is Williams, who also fills a need at OT. Williams is the highest graded tackle in this draft and the Ravens add some protection for Joe Flacco. Williams will most likely line up at RT opposite 2016 first round pick Ronnie Stanley at LT.

The best Tackle in this draft goes to the Seahawks who desperately need to preserve Russell Wilson’s career. The trade back wasn't a *perfect* value, but it was necessary as they are desperate for picks to fix their O line, Defense, and, well, everything else.

The Giants trade down here for good reason. Their offensive line is abyssmal, Manning is just getting older, Odell Beckham is showing that front office who's boss, and they have no run game. Basically their whole offense is a giant dumpster fire. Also don't forget that JPP isn't with the Giants anymore. I think the Giants have as much incentive to trade down as the Bills have incentive to trade up, because no pick at 2 is going to change the fact that there's still a good chance the Giants will still be picking top 5 next year. Connor Williams is the best, most technically sound OT in the draft, and by god the Giants need him.
It's a good idea to keep your old, but still good Quarterback alive and Williams has all the tools to do that.

Another guy I don't see falling this far, Williams is the perfect pick for the Bengals. He can play tackle or guard depending on where their biggest need is.

Cleveland has done well to add talent in the offseason, but losing future Hall of Fame LT Joe Thomas really hurts their progress. Thomas was renowned for his ability to win with technique, and that's why I could see Cleveland eyeing up the top technical OT in this class Connor Williams. While Williams struggled with injuries this season, his end of year tape and 2016 tape show a player with excellent footwork, hand usage, and quality athleticism to be a longterm LT in the NFL.

I hate to be boring, but I think the Patriots have enough holes in their roster to where they shouldn't be looking into trading their firsts for Lamar Jackson, and I definitely don't think they're going to. Williams seems to be the consensus number 1 tackle in this draft class. After spending a pick on someone to help protect Luck, I have their next pick being on a weapon for Luck. Indy's WR corps consists almost entire of smaller, slot type receivers. While TY Hilton is an excellent field stretcher, the Colts lack a true boundary WR who can win with size. Courtland Sutton is a big 6'3 receivier with legitimate athleticism and jump ball capabilities. He fights through contact to make catches, and can extend the play after the catch. Separation is Sutton's biggest issue, but his role as a big-bodied target is something Indianapolis needs to balance their receiving corp.

Sutton, Ridley, Moore, Kirk, Chark, etc. could all be options here. I honestly have no idea who Baltimore would prefer in this scenario. Sutton is big and fast and a big red zone target. He'll also be able to high point those Cam Newton rocket deep balls.

The Falcons have a good roster right now. Their biggest need might be DT across from Grady Jarrett. However their Offense has been missing that piece across from Julio for a while now. This offense can truly be unleashed with the addition of Suttton. The Hope is Sutton can be the next Alshon Jeffrey. He compares really well. And having him opposite of Julio with this RB groups gives the Falcons a loaded offense for Matt Ryan to lead another super bowl run.

The fourth round is where we often start to see need taking a back seat to 'guys we love', so in that spirit I've really poured over the visit lists and meetings and just generally tried to get an idea who teams have loved throughout the process, not just who they're said to love lately (which I hesitate to believe, especially if it's come out over the past two weeks). It's pretty clear to me that Cincinnati really likes DaeSean Hamilton. And while at first glance WR doesn't seem like a need for the Bengals, I wouldn't say they've exactly got it covered either. LaFell's 31 and his contract runs out at the end of the year, Tyler Boyd's been mostly nondescript over his first two seasons, save for the TD that sent the Bills to the playoffs, and who knows what they've got with John Ross? It's way too early to give up on him (or Boyd, for that matter), but the Cincy brass has to be concerned with the way his rookie season went. Even AJ Green will turn 30 this offseason, wow, that's hard to believe. But the most telling thing is that if they do like Hamilton, they're gonna have to grab him here. He's not lasting until their next pick. So that's what I have them doing. Hamilton's an easy guy to love. I hesitate to call anyone bust proof, but Hamilton might be as close as it gets. I think he's probably the best route runner in the class (him or Ridley), and there's always room for guys like that in the league. He may never lead the league in yards or catches, and he'll drop a pass now and again, but if you want a guy who consistently gets open, Hamilton's the guy for you.

The Vikings have Diggs and Theilen on the outside and now Hamilton could slide in as a slot receiver. Hamilton is kind of a jack of all trades master of none type receiver. He has a knack for being open that could make him a NFL player for years to come
Best route runner in the draft
While WR isnt the biggest need, Hamilton has a lot of potential to pass up on. He has great route running and I think he could eventually transition into a solid WR 1 or 2.

I admit it, I really like the idea of Dallas drafting Dallas Goedert. What's messed up is I can kinda see Jerry liking it too. I mean, maybe? Could you really put it past him? It'll be interesting to see how Jerry plays around come draft day, given the draft's in his palace and he's nothing if not a showman. In that spirit I tried to find a way to move the Cowboys up, but I couldn't find a way to get them past New Orleans, so the dream dies (I'm only mentioning it so that when Dallas does do something crazy like trade up for Goedert on draft day, you guys can all be like 'hey, that guy on Reddit called this shit, good on him'. I live for those kind of faraway plaudits that I'll never know even happened). So I know a lot of Saints fans prefer Gesicki, and I admit it seems to be about a 50/50 split atop TE boards. Here's a few reasons I have Goedert higher, and why I think FOs will too. 1) Sure, Gesicki tested off the charts, but can we say Goedert wouldn't have too? Watching tape, I don't see that big of a difference between the two of them athletically. Gesicki's a great athlete for the position, but I didn't see anything that told me he was gonna run a 4.54 either. That was surprising. Maybe Goedert would have surprised too, had he been healthy enough to run. I suppose we'll never know. 2) Goedert has the potential to be a better blocker. This is the big one to me. For all of Gesicki's strengths, blocking is a major red flag. It's not just that he's high cut and not really built for it, it's that he genuinely doesn't seem to care. And he was blocking for one of the best college RBs in decades, you think he would have cared. Goedert's no great shakes as a blocker, but he's far more willing and he's got a frame conducive to holding up. He improved his technique this year too, something you can't say about Gesicki at all. If Goedert can cut down on all of the one handed catch attempts, he can be one of the best TEs in the game. In New Orleans, with Drew Brees, he'll thrive.

I haven't been following many Cowboys mock drafts but this has to be a popular pick. Jason Witten is getting up there in age and Goedert is a very talented pass catcher. Plus, Dallas in Dallas. Can't pass that up.

Dallas is Engram-lite. Big body receiver. He did well against weak competition but I'm not sold that he'll do as well against NFL level competition. That said, Flacco needs weapons, and Dallas is most definitely that.
How do you make your new QB love you? Give him a TE. The best damn TE in the class.
Goedert will be a mismatch on LBs at the next level and is great at high pointing the ball in the air. Needs to vastly improve his blocking at the next level to be an all-around TE.

The Jags could use some pass catchers to replace Lewis, Hurns, and Robinson. Their fans will say that they have replacements in place, but many are largely untested. Goedert is raw, but has the size and ability to step in early and be a target for Bortles.
This seems like a popular pick, more weapons after NO were rumored to be chasing Jimmy Graham during FA

Coby Fleener was a big letdown, and New Orleans swung and missed in trying to lure Jimmy Graham back. Aside from Michael Thomas, New Orleans doesn't have much consistency in receiving threats. Cameron Meredith is a high upside pickup, but nabbing another athletic pass-catching TE for Drew Brees could go a long way. Goedert has excellent hands and is a great route-runner at each level. He uses his body well and maintains balance to make plays. He's not a Jimmy Graham caliber athletic TE, but he reminds me of a Zach Ertz consistent receiving threat.

After a trade down, the Dolphins reinforced their interior OL with their first-round pick. Now, they look to fill their last glaring hole on offense. Goedert is NFL-ready as a receiver, and he possesses the frame you look for when searching for a competent blocking tight end. He needs to work on consistency in regards to the latter, but I believe he has the most potential in this class, in terms of being an all-around contributor at TE.

Elway's collecting pieces for his offense to compliment his defense. Goedert is a bit of a luxury pick, but the Broncos have significant need at TE, and Goedert's talent will be too much to pass up this late in the game.
The Jimmy Graham role is finally filled. Goedert is mostly receiver but he would be very productive, Brees and Graham were great.
Ravens get the best TE of the class who can help them early.
but did he used to play basketball?
Small School = Good
Adding Goedart adds a big recieving threat which they are missing at TE, he can't block but he can make some amazing catches in the red zone.
Athletic TE with highlight reel catches. Improving as blocker. Played against low level of competition.
Goedert might be a bit of a reach, but I believe he's going to become the next Jason Witten. Gets Brees the 3rd down guy he needs to keep the chains moving
The Eagles decide to get another redzone target for Carson Wentz and a new TE to make up for the loss of Trey Burton.
NE can run their 2 TE sets and has an insurance policy for Gronk

I did this mock before the signed Watson. It might even help Goedert having Watson and not having to have the full offensive load for the TE on him right away. Giving Drew Brees even more weapons in the twilight of his career is always a nice move. This will also benefit whoever replaces him in the coming years.

Well I suppose I'll be accused of waiting too long to grab a RB and that's valid, given it's my mock, but remember if I had been making the picks I would have taken Michel in the second. So don't blame me. Blame the vibes Quinn's giving off, or blame his NFL upbringing, or blame the coaching change on the line, or the addition of O Line dudes. All of it adds up to us not drafting a RB in the first two rounds, and now there's not one here to draft. It is what it is, that's how Quinn's gonna roll if the value's not right. He won't be grabbing a RB at any cost. But then on top of that I'm having us grab a TE? Lions fans have a hate hate relationship with the TE position after the Ebron flop and the Pettigrew mini flop so we'll definitely be throwing stuff after this one. I think most of our fans would be fine not drafting one at all, or at least waiting until the fifth before taking a punt. And hey, I'm with you, Lions fans. Really, I'm not a huge fan of this pick (though I'm usually not a fan of Quinn's third
He's no Jordan Thomas

The Lions need a TE and I think a TE that can do it all and be on the field all 3 downs definitley would suit Patricias style. Hes my sleeper TE, he can block very well and is good enough in the passing game.

Another weapon for Jimmy G. He has Garcon and Goodwin but Garcon is suceptible to injuries and Goodwin only has one year of solid production. It wouldn't hurt to have a young wide receiver locked up at cheap money.

Aside from TE (which has already been covered by the selection of Goedert), quite a few Saints fans would have you believe WR is their biggest need. I don't necessarily agree with that point of view. We all know Michael Thomas is a stud, they've just signed Cameron Meredith (and if he can recapture his old Bears form, I think he could set the league on fire in New Orleans), Ted Ginn had a great year for them last year and only seems to be getting better with age, Brandon Coleman's still around to go up and snag the high balls, and technically Willie Snead's still on the roster too, though I expect him to be released now that the Bears declined to match Meredith's offer. And you have to consider Goedert part of the pass catching mix now too. To me, that doesn't scream need. Could they add some depth? Sure, absolutely, but it's not a position I'd be pining to fill too early. But, this is Sean Payton we're talking about (and Mickey Loomis too, but that's not as interesting to the rest of us). Since when has need been his main reason for drafting someone? He finds guys he loves and he goes and gets them. And I think he's gonna love Dante Pettis, and the Saints fans are gonna think he's filling a need when he's really going BPA. Pettis can even start to take over the return duties from Ginn to help keep him fresh, he might be the best return man in the draft. Certainly he's the most accomplished.
Tate is old, and can't return Punts forever. Their WR corps are notably bad. Why not fix both problems at the same time? Pettis does that, and does it very well.
He's a great punt returner, not so much as a WR

Pettis adds some good depth to the Ravens WR's. With the Ravens looking to be a fringe playoff team every little thing to get a win helps and Pettis return game is insane and brings another part of the Ravens game which can mean getting into the playoffs or not.

I'm trying to figure out why Leonard isn't going higher in the mocks I've read. Is it his small school background? I mean, competition level is always a concern and any team drafting him will have to get comfortable with it, but that hasn't stopped other small school guys from going high. Leonard was fantastic in the Senior Bowl against the big boys, and he basically single handedly stone walled Tarik Cohen last year (Cohen's worst collegiate game), one of the few NFL caliber players he faced off against. Maybe it's the fact that NFL.com mislabels his weight as being 213 (and that a lot of other sites seem to be taking their cue from nfl.com and mislabeling him too)? Everyone knows that's not right, right? A cursory search will reveal that he weighed in fine at 234. Not only that, but he checked in with 34 3/8 inch arms and a 82 1/8 wingspan. Those are basically Tremaine Edmunds numbers, but on a 6

Baltimore needs someone who can give CJ Mosley a hand in their Front 7 and Leonard is someone who can do it all, and do it well. They find an immediate upgrade to a defense in need of a spark to continue to carry their "Elite?" Offense

Jacksonville had a studded defense but needs to replace the recently retired Paul Posluszny. Darius Leonard, despite being a small-school guy, is a very sound LB who should be able to contribute right away. He has solid instincts and is very patient, and then shows the abilitiy to play downhill hard and attack the ball-carrier. He does a good job avoiding and shedding oncoming blockerers, and also shows good range on outside runs. There may be a learning curve with the big skill jump, but he can do a lot of what Poz did.

Trade details: See pick #11. Raekwon McMillan returning this year could help alleviate some of the struggles the Dolphins’ LB group had last year, but even then, reinforcements are need. Kiko Alonso just hasn’t been the player he once was the past couple of years.
Small school but solid value don't @ me
The Bills desperatley need LB help especially as Preston Brown is gone. Darius Leonard has good size and speed, he can play inside or outside LB and would be a good fit for the Bills.
