He has solid instincts and is very patient, and then shows the abilitiy to play downhill hard and attack the ball-carrier. He does a good job avoiding and shedding oncoming blockerers, and also shows good range on outside runs. There may be a learning curve with the big skill jump, but he can do a lot of what Poz did.

So Philly's loaded and can go BPA blah blah blah, you know the story, it's not a new one. But here's the main reason they should go BPA it's time to start preparing for life without a QB on a rookie contract. As early as next offseason you're gonna ink Wentz to one of the largest deals in NFL history and you're gonna have to start sloughing dudes left and right. You went for it while you had the QB on a rookie contract the equivalent of NFL gold and it worked, you won your Super Bowl. But pretty soon it won't, and you'll have to operate like most of the NFL teams who have their franchise QB. You're gonna have to make some tough decisions. Just look at what's happening to Seattle, the fallout of inking Russ to his contract. While he was on his rookie contract and playing for peanuts, they were stacked. Now, they aren't. You've already begun to do it, Eagles fans. Vets like Ngata and Bennett on short term deals, those guys won't be back once Wentz is signed. But that's not enough. We all know one of the main reasons for your success was your vaunted defensive line, well you're not gonna be able to keep the band together much longer. You can't have eight/nine great D
The Chargers need help in the middle of their defense and Payne is a great player to help with that. He will stuff the run and force double teams freeing Bosa up to win 1v1 battles on the outside

Most people think the Ravens need offensive playmakers, especially receiver or OL. Nay. Why do you need offense if your opponents can't score against your oppressive defense and your kicker can make a field goal from ~95 yards away? The Ravens get even better at the point of attack with Payne…bringing the pain. Also, Baltimore + Alabama players = happy Ozzie.

Los Angeles takes the top DL available in Payne, who has tremendous strength and has a great first punch that can take offensive linemen off their gameplan. He is one of the premier run-stuffers in the class, and should instantly improve a Chargers defense that gave up the second most rushing yards per game (131.1) in 2017.

Our 3rd Bama player in the Top 20 is Payne, who can immediately join the Chargers Front 7 and take them from a unit with above average pieces to an elite unit as a whole. The only thing he’s not good at is... well... not being Vea in my eyes.

Our 3rd Bama player in the Top 20 is Payne, who can immediately join the Chargers Front 7 and take them from a unit with above average pieces to an elite unit as a whole. The only thing he’s not good at is... well... not being Vea in my eyes.

Da'Ron Payne is a much needed player for the Chargers. They should be lucky to receive him here. Payne doesn't make a whole lot super plays, but he's consistent, and he always disorients the OL to some degree. This is much needed when it comes to helping out the other guys in the front 7 do what they need to do as a team.
Chargers could use a good 1 tech player which Payne excels at. Harrison Phillips was another option here for them, but Payne is a better fit, even with a lower level of production.

Not sure 1T is the biggest need here but unless the Cowboys are enamoured with one of the linebackers still available, Payne is the best value here. Receiver is also in play, but the signing of Hurns makes this a less urgent position.
Some great prospects have dropped but Redskins need to help their terrible run defense

While Grady Jarrett had himself a nice breakout season, Atlanta severely lacks talent at the defensive tackle position. Without a true 1T on their roster, Atlanta needs an immediately contributor, and Da'Ron Payne is exactly that. Payne is the model of consistency; constantly collapsing the pocket on passing downs and stuffing the run on running downs. He is a true two-gapper that you can build a front-7 around. He also displayed some pass-rusher upside in the College Football Playoffs. Perfect fit for Atlanta.

Moving up boards pretty fast, and a huge position of need for ATL. Also fairly close to home, so he doesn’t have to move but one state over. I think he comes in and immediately makes an impact for a team that funny enough; defense has been the evolving face of the team. They just haven't brought in any of the first round OL guys, so I'm really starting to think they're looking at RG in the 2nd or 3rd round.

With Dontari Poe exiting in free agency, Atlanta finds themselves looking to replace him with another difference-maker in the middle of their DL. Outside of Grady Jarrett, they don’t have much to talk about there. I like Payne’s fit here because of his ability to play either interior spot in a 4-3. He can do what Poe did as a 1-tech, but also possesses the athletic ability to play some 3-tech if Quinn/Manuel want to get creative. Atlanta won’t be missing Poe much after this pick.

Detriot swaps firsts and gives Baltimore their 3rd rounder to secure Da'Ron Payne. It's no secret that the Lions need help at DT, and word on the street is they covet Da'Ron Payne. By scooping one pick in front of the Chargers, they ensure they get their man at a relatively low price.

The Chargers biggest need is probably defensive tackle. They'll likely address offensive line at some point, and could address quarterback as well .Payne fits nicely inbetween pass-rushing specialists Melvin Ingram and Joey Bosa to give the Chargers a nice front seven to work with.
Lions see Payne falling and jump on it before someone else can.
The Lions need to generate more interior pressure and Payne is solid in both the run game and at pass rushing.
probably should go higher
Please pick some OL

The Lions grab Payne, the 3-tech tackle that looked like Aaron Donald in the playoff games in college.  He can join the number of Alabama interior lineman that have found success in the NFL, and looked every bit the part at times this season.
Pairing him up with Bosa and Ingram will give the team an almost complete defense.
Payne would come in and start at 1 tech day 1. He's got great run blocking skills and has the athleticism to add some pressure up the middle, adding Payne to Bosa and Ingram is a scary thought.
Great strength/athleticism to dominate the run. Improving vs the pass and has to the tools to be even better
Up to this point, the Cowboys have made zero noise in FA and look to have a lot of needs. I think they would be thrilled to land Payne here.

The Falcons fill a Dontari Poe size hole in their roster with Da'Ron Payne. He can immediately plug in and help with Atlanta's run defense, while contributing more than expected on passing downs. I doubt Atlanta could dream of a better player falling into their lap

Chargers are planning to bring the Payne! They need a big powerful disruptor on the D-line and he's that guy. If Payne continues to play at the level he was at in the playoffs, he could end up being one of the best picks in the draft.
DL1 comes off the board to strengthen the front 7 of the Falcons, where he will take the starting job from day 1.
The best player available at this position happens to also be a need for the cowboys so they rush up to the podium to take Payne, who could be a threat from day 1.

DT is probably the biggest need for the Chargers, and Payne is the best one available. Payne had a fantastic National Championship game and will add solidarity in the interior to an already stacked defensive line boasting Melvin Ingram and Joey Bosa. The Chargers fortify their defense and choose Payne.
The Chargers are building a dominant front 7 with Ingram and Bosa on the edges. Adding an athletic DT only makes it better

New Orleans revitalized their future by nailing the 2017 NFL Draft. The Saints enter the 2018 Draft with holes at TE and in the front seven. I could see an athletic TE like Mike Gesicki or Dallas Goedert here, but Payne would be a great pick that fills a need. As are most Alabama players, Payne would be ready to contribute from day one.
Versatility to play either NT or 3T in ATL's defense
Payne fits a need at NT for the Titans and adds a little pass rush ability to the position as well

The Saints could also really use a WR to help Brees out even more. But with their DB group playing like the best in the NFL, they need to complete this defense. Payne is a guy that probably should not have fallen this far, and he's will eat up the run at DT. The Saints need to keep adding guys like this and make this defense elite. Unfortunately the top 3 EDGE guys are off the board. A trade down could be nice, but idk who their trade parnter would be.
Colts fill another need and get great value here with Leonard.

After addressing their main need along the O line, the Vikings are situated to go BPA as much as they want. Hand is most often thought of as a 3 4 end (unsurprising since that's where he played in college), but at 6'4, 297 can easily shift into the middle of a 4 3. In fact I think he may be better off as a penetrating tackle, which is exactly how the Vikings would use him along their line (he was crushing it there at the Senior Bowl before he got hurt, pretty much the only guy who got the best of Isaiah Wynn). He's a good, quick athlete with good technique and a high footballing IQ (like most Bama guys), but he won't be pushed around in the run game. He gets labeled as a jack of all trades and master of none kind of guy (which explains his drop), but I think that's unfair. Like so many other Alabama guys, he sacrificed himself for the team somewhat, and was never given the chance to show out at his best position. Think of Da'Ron Payne. Before the playoffs he'd been pretty meh as a 0/1

Hand has been a little disappointing at Bama considering how he was ranked coming out of high school but he has still shown flashes of brilliance. He has the ability to play on the interior or exterior of the DL. With Watt and Clowney most people don't think this is a position of need for the Texans but Watt has had trouble staying healthy and Hand is the best player left on my board
I have no idea why Hand gets hype tbh

Here's Minny doubling up on the interior D Line, but Senat's a different kinda cat than Hand. He's your rock, your immovable object, your squatty little irritant. He's got strong, lightning hands and a motor that never stops. That shit's gonna appeal to Zimmer. He might never offer much going towards the passer, but then neither does Linval Joseph, there's a spot for him on the Vikes. This is a sheer value pick, he's a fit in Minny's D and he's a bargain. He might not play much as a rookie behind Joseph and Richardson, but he'll put in some minutes and he'll make Zimmer think twice about hanging onto Joseph any longer, whose cap hit plummets after this season. With the cash crunch the Vikings are in for, it's good to start planning for it now.

I know we've heard all the news about how the Bills are trying to trade up, and I think that's probably true. But let me reiterate, here's the vibe I've gotten from the Bills FO so far they have a set of parameters they're willing to work within, and anything outside of that they simply disregard. They won't panic or get ripped off, which is (one of the reasons) why we haven't seen any movement already. They're Belichickian that way, or at least they seem to be to me. So I don't know, call it a hunch, but I just can't see them overpaying to the extent the Dolphins did to trade up for a QB, especially when it was Rosen who fell (I imagine he'll be the least favorite of the Bills FO). I suppose this makes Buffalo the loser of the great QB rush (though I still wouldn't be shocked if they traded for Nick Foles later on), but I certainly expect them to draft a QB at some point. On the plus side, not having to grab one of the QBs means they can sit back and let one of the best players in the draft fall to them. CB's not Buffalo's biggest need, but at this point, he's too good a player to pass on. He might not have the length they'd prefer, but he doesn't have the length anyone prefers, technically, but you overlook that sort of thing with a guy this talented. He and White will give the AFC East nightmares for years to come.
I've seen Edmunds in this spot a ton and it isn't a bad choice. But look at what adding an elite CB did to the Saint's defense last year. Ward could be a game changer.
The Lions' biggest vulnerability is in its defensive backfield. Darrius Slay is particularly inept but the other CBs aren't special either. Denzel will reWARD the Lions with his play

Cleveland is able to trade down from 4 and still land the top pure cornerback prospect in the draft. Ward fills a need for the Browns and will be able to immediately upgrade a defense that already has a solid front seven anchored by last year’s No. 1 overall pick, Myles Garrett.
They’ve lacked any help next to PP for some time, and in the midst of a secondary overhaul, they find an incredible talent here who will help shut down receivers for a long foreseeable future.
They’ve lacked any help next to PP for some time, and in the midst of a secondary overhaul, they find an incredible talent here who will help shut down receivers for a long foreseeable future.

Packers have had CB issues for a while. They can finally shore that up with the best CB in the draft. They tried to bring in Kyle Fuller, but were unable to, so they'll have to resort to plan B.... drafting Denzel Ward.... which very well could be better than Plan A. Ward is a tad bit undersized, but those are quite honestly his only limitations, as he does everything else better than the other CBs in this draft.

It's no secret that Mariota was BAD last year, but maybe if they could get the ball to him more, he'd suck less. BOAT, Watson and Brissett (or Luck, if he's even out there anymore) are turnover machines.
I'm not as high on Ward as some others are, but Browns need some CB help. Ward offers that in spades. A bit of a fall a la Hooker last year but still a first rounder.

Not the biggest need for the Redskins, but thirteenth is a long way to fall for the top CB in the class. Not enamoured with the receiver options available, the Skins go BPA and take Ward. He is exceptional in coverage despite being a little grabby at times.
Huge suprise to see Ward still available and the packers have something else go their way (shocker) by getting a top 5 players and the top corner which is their most glaring weakness. Yuck

Chicago's presumable top target Quenton Nelson is off the board, so they could also look to simply add a top talent available. With the Eddie Jackson/Adrian Amos pairing at safety, Chicago could look to add DB talent in the form of CB Denzel Ward. Ward is an elite athlete who can play man and zone coverage concepts due to his fluidity in movement. He is excellent at playing the balling and countering a size mismatch with his jumping ability. Nabbing Ward would give Chicago a longterm pair of boundary CBs with the newly extended Kyle Fuller.

I think the 49ers are in prime position to change the outlook of the

in the NFC. Their secondary is still a weakness even with Sherman
being added to the team. Ward is undersized and can get pushed around
by bigger receivers, but he is a good cover corner who will pair nicely
with Sherman and elevate the defense to complement the Jimmy G
led offense.
Packers need secondary. Packers need secondary. Packers need secondary. And I think they have him and Derwin as their highest rated guys. I could see either, but OCB is a bit harder to fill.

Green Bay invested the 33rd pick in the 2017 draft in the intriguing Kevin King, but he needs a quality running mate as he’s the only potential long-term CB on the Packers’ roster. Their system is geared towards man corners, which is what Denzel Ward projects to be. This gives him the nod over Josh Jackson. With Ward on board and bringing back Tramon Williams, the Pack have a nice trio of corners unlike the atrocious group they fielded last year.

Best lockdown, man to man corner in the draft. Raiders need the help in the secondary, but after investing in safety twice the past two years, I see them taking the best pure CB in the draft in Ward.

With both Minkah Fitzpatrick and Derwin James off the board, the Packers turn to Denzel Ward to address their secondary. They need to address free safety, as they only have Josh Jones on roster, but they decide to do that later in the draft with both Fitzpatrick and James off the board. I could see them grabbing a receiver here, but their is value to be had later at that position to address Jordy Nelson's departure.
Ward can play oppposite Norman and adds elite speed and playmaking to the secondary that lost Kendall Fuller and Bashaud Breeland.
This pick is interesting. The Giants could go many ways here but they have so many top 100 picks now that they decide to go BPA and take Ward.
This was another tough choice between Ward and Minkah Fitzpatrick. Bucs already have some okay safeties, but really need a starting-caliber CB and they get that in Ward.
is good
He's...a pick
Can project as a slot or outside guy, fits a need and is BPA in my opinion.

Nelson would be another fit here but again I think Ward would be more impactful for the team as Grimes is only on a 1 year and Hargreaves dropped off slightly last year. Ward could easily come in and fill in CB1 or 2 at the worst.
Sticky press corner with athleticism to match. Only concern is size.
Kendall Fuller and Breeland have departed, making corner a big position of need. Redskins land the best true corner in the class.

The Bucs could go in a couple of different directions here after the top 3 on my board went (Chubb, Barkley, Nelson). Instead, I grab the best outside corner in the draft to replace the aging Brent Grimes. I nearly went safety here, but with the glut of free agent safeties still to be had on the cheap, I went with the more valuable postion here

Oakland gets the best lockdown corner in the draft. Ward mirrors receivers and is scrappy. He's also great in the run game. Some fans may think that CB isn't a need, but he is the best CB in the draft. They need secondary help, and getting Hurst here is a reach.

I really didn't know whether to go with a CB or a WR, but given that Ward is the #1 pure CB in the draft, I think the Cardinals will value that over Ridley, who is the best WR but not as stunning as #1 WRs of the past few years.
The Bears decide to go and get the best CB in the draft, an incredible talent who can help make this secondary one of the best in the league.

After the Gareon Conley pick didn't really go the way they planned, Oakland needs to improve their secondary the best they can this offseason, so they select the best corner in the draft in Denzel Ward. Coming off a good season with the Buckeyes, Ward is both fast and good in coverage, and he will provide clarity at the cornerback position for the Raiders. This is a great pick for the Raiders and I am incredibly high on Ward, I'm excited to see how he develops in the NFL.
A lot of people have them taking a LB, but I dont see it here. They have a lot of young front 7 pieces, RIchard Sherman, and Eric Reid is gone. They bring in a DB here

The Buccaneers will be hoping Saquon Barkley falls to this selection, but it doesn’t happen here. If Barkley doesn’t fall, expect them to address their woeful secondary which may be the worst in the NFL. They could go with a safety such as James or Fitzpatrick, or take a CB. They need upgrades everywhere here. I’ll have them taking Denzel Ward who has established himself as the best CB in the draft.

Ward is my BPA and fits a position of need for Tampa as Grimes is getting older and Hargreaves has disappointed. Only potential issue here is that TB runs a zone scheme and Ward is best in man but I think Ward is sufficiently scheme versatile. Plus, if I'm the GM I realize that this coaching staff could easily be gone next year and thus I shouldn't necessarily let their scheme influence my decisions enough to pass on the BPA.
The Bears further solidify a young, strong secondary with the top corner in the draft.

This was the second tough choice, because the 49ers could honestly go anywhere with this pick and I know they just signed Richard Sherman. But I think Denzel Ward is not only the best player available, he's also the best value. It really just does not make too much sense for them to be spending this #9 pick on a LB. EDGE I can see them taking, but ultimately they've spent like the last 3 1st rounders on DL. While EDGE is a need, I think they can get an Edge rusher in the 2nd/3rd round. So I think DB is the choice here, which leaves you to choose between Minkah and Ward. And while I love Minkah and think he can play CB, The 49ers just don't need someone that is more of a Safety. They Need a pure CB, and Denzel Ward is the best in this class.

I've seen GB get mocked so many DEs this year. People we get it they need. I think in this position Denzel Ward makes the most sense relating to both need and impact. A little undersized he's broken out as the top CB for a lot of people in this draft. If Green Bay does decide he's too small for there liking i think they also consider Mike Hughes strongly here. The best press man CB in this draft would fit right in with their defense. In the end i think they get over this "undersized" crap the NFL seems to love and go with the easy pick in Ward.

The Packers are in dire need of CBs. Ward dropping all the way to 14 for them is a dream come true. Adding Ward here and maybe Mikes Hughes in the 2nd would be huge for this teams secondary going into this season.

It's not often you find a guy with Cain's upside in the fourth round. He's got legit WR1 skills, but he's got some other shit too that causes him to drop, we all know what it is. Dropped too many passes (a concentration thing IMO, not a hands thing), he didn't show out when he took over as Clemson's #1, got frustrated a lot and his effort waned. We all thought he was in line to be a first round pick before this season, he has that kind of natural ability. Then the season happened, and here he is. Now for the good stuff, I don't think any of it will be too surprising. You watch the guy play and your first thought is, 'that guy's an NFL receiver.' He looks the part. He's fast, he breezes by coverage when his head's in it, he fights for the ball, he's great once he has it in his hands. He just looks like he belongs out there. There aren't too many guys you can watch where you can just glance up and catch a glimpse of one random play that makes you think to yourself, he's gonna crush the league. Cain does that, that's who he is. I hesitated to mock him to the Bears though, I keep reading where Pace has a thing against off the field stuff. But then it's just a nineteen year
Cain is a phenomenal athlete running in the low 4.4s at a height on 6'2. His biggest problem is consistency. He is a boom or bust pick but the Panthers need a playmaker at the WR position

Trade details: See pick #4. Cleveland has a ton of picks and already filled their other major needs via free agency and picks earlier in this draft. This is a value pick as they grab a high upside WR from a school with a reputation of producing quality receivers.
Building a winning offense
Cain is a developmental WR and with the Broncos WR situation may have to look like a choice between Sanders or Thomas, Cain could eventually become that No 2 guy.
Nnadi is a big dude who can play at 1- or possibly even 3- for ATL. He's still a bit undersized, but for a 3rd rounder, he's a good pickup for a team in need of positional help
D Line depth
A bit of a reach considering needs, but a decent fit for JAX
Nnadi would fit in at NT but probs would fit in more at 3-4 DE has a run stopper on the first 2 down.

I'm aware this pick is not going to be well liked by Raiders fans, not with James, McGlinchey, Hurst, Roquan, Payne, any number of WRs on the board. But this isn't an exercise in need filling, it's an exercise in attempting to approximate a real draft. And that means there's going to be surprises. And a lot of those surprises come from teams with new coaches, and I expect that's especially true of a new coach with the power of Gruden. So I thought to myself as I was doing this, who most strikes me as a Gruden style player? OK, old guys with experience, I get it. But who's the most Gruden style player in the draft? Because there's no way Gruden's not running this thing. McKenzie's done a pretty good job over the years but he just got usurped. Mark Davis wanted Gruden and handed him the keys to the kingdom, what Gruden says goes, no matter what kinda smile McKenzie puts on his face or what they say to the media. So, is it gonna be a guy like James? Maybe. But safety's not really a need, and the extra pick allows Oakland to really hammer BPA here, and my inclination is that Gruden's going to really love Guice, and Guice is gonna love playing for Oakland, with the guy he's most often compared to in Marshawn Lynch. But I see this pick as a tone

The Eagles may have traded for Ajayi in the middle of the season but he isn't good enough to be a bell cow back. Guice is a stud and the Eagles will get the best years of his career with a 5 year deal in the first round. He will help take pressure off of Carson Wentz

No team is more hungry for adequate RB play than the Saints. Neither Ingram nor Kamara are starters in this league. Guice will finally be the complement needed for Drew Brees to be an effective passer.

The Jaguars have a couple of options here players like Will Hernandez and Billy Price available, but the Jags trade down with the Giants, who hold the second pick in the 2nd round at 34 and look to jump the Browns for the 2nd best RB in the draft. Guice is a powerful back out of LSU and possesses an exceptional balance of speed, power, and balance as the top interior rusher in the draft. After taking Rosen 2nd overall, the Giants add Guice who, combined with Odell Beckham Jr., create a very exciting offense for the future.

The Buccs need a feature back still, as Doug Martin hasn't been that guy in quite some time and he's officially gone. Guice can step in and be an immediate threat from the get go and make Jameis' life much easier

Did they sign Hyde? Sure. Is Duke still on roster? Yep. But they still may be looking for a feature back, and what an immense value at 22 in Guice. A cold as ice RB who can change their whole running game, and make Darnold's job much easier

Lions need something with the run game they have. Derrius Guice is a perfect fit for them. He can't do everything, but he does more than most other RBs in this draft. The Lions really ned to establish their run gam so that they can get their offense kickstarted.
I don't love the Eagles RB corps, and Guice adds to it as a RB who can house it. Like the Jaguars, they don't have a lot of needs, and Guice is a top 20 player for me.

Giants miss out on a generational talent in Barkley by trading down but Guice would be the cream of the crop in many other classes, getting Davenport and likely an additional 2nd-3rd round pick next year helps too

Isaiah Crowell failed to meet expectations last season, and Duke Johnson was rather underutilized last season. While I do expect a Todd Haley offense to use Duke more, Cleveland needs a true feature back to keep up in the AFC North. Enter Derrius Guice, who many believe to be the best pure runner in this class. Guice is a smooth, downhill runner who runs with good balance and hits the holes hard. Behind Cleveland's strong IOL front, Guice should be able to carve out big gains to get Cleveland's offense going.

I've heard a lot of Lions fans not sure what they want to do with their
running back room. I think the Lions should and will address it with
a running back who can transform an entire offense. I think they could
go defensive line hear but Pairing Guice with Stafford and 
sharing carries with Blount and maybe Abdullah can maybe perhaps 
finally have his breakout year....I guess?

This one is less about what I think or don't think of Guice. I think of him very highly for what it's worth, and don't see him as much of a downgrade from Barkley. That aside, the Redskins have brought him in for a private visit, a workout, and visited his Pro Day. There is something to be said for that intrigue, and I just can't foresee this much effort into a smokescreen nobody is falling for. They've also mentioned that an RB will be brought in early this year. I'm convinced they're pulling the trigger, and I don't hate it.
This is a value pick. The Bills can use Guice is tandem with Chris Ivory behind Shady McCoy in the short-term and save him up for a big debut in a couple years.

This is essentially a best player available pick. The Eagles don't have many obvious holes. I could see them addressing wide receiver here as well as offensive line, tight end, and cornerback. But the Eagles decide to address their running back depth as they only have Jay Ajayi and Wendell Smallwood on roster. Guice is likely the best pure runner in this class and is the second best back due to Barkley's pass catching abilities. Enjoy the rest of the offseason, Eagles fans!
Marlon Mack is probably not the solution to Indy's RB woes. Guice is an immediate upgrade and provides an excellent RBBC with Mack for the Colts to lean on in the coming years.
CLE trades 2018 2nd and 5th for MIN 2018 1st
Giants get RB2 and hopefully their future RB for the next few years.
I have Guice very high on my board and he fails all the way to the Skins. Guice can really elevate an offense and will succeed behind the Redskins' line.
finally.
A RB who can HOUSE IT

I can count 14 million reasons why Guice makes sense here. Pittsburgh can have Guice produce at a great level for pennies compared to Bell's contract. Even if it's a downgrade the money saved is worth it.

Patriots always trade back if they don't value someone at their spot, and I don't think there is. The Colts and Patriots have a nice peace trade which gives the Colts a guy to take the load off a recovering Andrew Luck and the Patriots get their 2nd and a 4th.

Isaiah Crowell failed to meet expectations last season, and Duke Johnson was rather underutilized last season. While I do expect a Todd Haley offense to use Duke more, Cleveland needs a true feature back to keep up in the AFC North. Enter Derrius Guice, who many believe to be the best pure runner in this class. Guice is a smooth, downhill runner who runs with good balance and hits the holes hard. Behind Cleveland's strong IOL front, Guice should be able to carve out big gains to get Cleveland's offense going.

Before the Sly Williams signing, I would have picked a DT here. But that signing combined with Guice sitting here at 20 made the decision easy. Guice has been overshadowed by Barkley this draft cycle, but he is a complete power back who should take on the lead role in the backfield immediately

*TRADE: Giants trade their 2nd (#34), 4th (#108) and 5th(#139) for Steelers 1st* Giants got their new LT in FA, their new QB with their second, and now they want a RB that will do some damage to help out too. I don't think the Odell talk is legit. They may be trying to send him a message that he needs to get his sh*t together. Guice can do it all and gets outshined by Saquon, but is definitely a superstar in his own right.
Lions call upon Guice to break their streak of not having a 100 yard rusher, and he can definitely make it happen.
Guice is a very good player who falls due to the large depth at the RB position, but the Browns don't miss the opportunity to draft him.

I could see the Redskins secretly being tempted to pull the trigger on Josh Allen here, but that is pure speculation on my end. Washington has a huge need at RB, and Guice is one of my favorite players in the draft. I don’t think he’s too far behind Barkley. Guice would give Washington’s offense a workhorse back to pair with Alex Smith.
A top 10 player on my board who fell due to positional value. Guice is a franchise RB in his own right being overshadowed by the presence of Barkley.

Philly has no real holes and adding Guice will make an already terrifying offense even scarier. If the attitude problems with Guice end up being real Sutton could also be a pick here. Either way Philadelphia will be ready for a run at another Super Bowl.

The Cowboys overpay on the trade value chart to play keepaway from their division rival Redskins. Well, also because James is a great player and a really good fit for Dallas at a position of need. But you can bet your ass Jerry's chuckling to himself after leapfrogging his buddy Dan Dan and snatching the player he (and everyone else) will assume the Redskins were zeroed in on. When I started this, James was one of the guys where I said to myself "he's gonna go a little higher than everyone thinks". Then I dug in, and well, he didn't. I considered mocking him to Oakland, but he's not really a fit and the trade down won out. Then I considered sending him to Buffalo, but I never expected a talent like Ward to fall to them, and given a roughly similar grade, CB > S more often than not. Then I thought well surely the Redskins will take him, right? But then they got the offer from the Chargers and decided recouping their lost third rounder sounded pretty good to them. Then the Packers and Raiders (again) went different directions, and here we are. It's not shocking, I suppose. Safeties tend to fall, and James is coming off a pretty crap year, by his standards. But that won't stop Jerry from stumping for him, and I expect it'll be a pretty big hit with the home crowd. So I did this all before Dez got released (and if I may toot my own horn just a little, like I predicted back in February in my mock and caught so much shit over), but I still think the first round plays out this way, even after the fact. James should be waaaaay higher on everyone's boards than any of the WRs, and there's good depth in this draft at WR, so the Cowboys can afford to wait.
After cutting the Honeybadger the Cardinals could use an upgrade in their secondary. James is the BPA on my board and is a huge steal for the Cardinals at 15

The Packers have needs in their pass rush and their secondary, so they go BPA here with Derwin James, who, like Fitzpatrick, falls due to the rush on QBs in the top 10 picks. James is the top strong safety in the draft and is a great playmaker with elite athleticism who has drawn player comparisons to Kam Chancellor. He can be used in a hybrid role near the line of scrimmage, but needs to work on his ability to diagnose plays at the next level.
This is the most easy to mock move in the draft. Tampa loves the hometown kid, Derwin fills a need and upgrade their secondary. It's Cake.

A slide due to positional value and needs of teams, Packers happily land a major game changer on defense to help turn their unit into something which can help Rodgers, instead of being another thing for him to carry.

BPA pick right here. The Dolphins don't necessarily need SS here, but Derwin is still too good of a value to pass up on. His versatility on defense along can make the Dolphins pull the trigger. Put him in the box, make him cover deep, he can do both well.
LOB II. Derwin James edition. He's a scary player and one of my favs in the draft. Hard to have him this low but I kinda love this fit.
The loss of Morgan Burnett makes the Packers safety corps a little thin Derwin James automatically enhances that from day one. One of the most pro-ready prospets in the draft. BPA at this pick.

This is a bad situation for the Bucs. They miss out on their top three targets in the last three picks, and instead opt for James. James doesn't fill as urgent a need, but he is an upgrade over Ward and Conte, and will slot nicely next to Evans.
In this scenario Giants take EDGE after trading down, Davenport will try to fill in the gap after JPP's departure

In a BPA pick of sorts, Washington nabs the talented Derwin James to hopefully become a key playmaker on their defense. Washington has a solid safety in DJ Swearinger, but lacks a big playmaker at SS and really outside of Kerrigan on their defense. Derwin is a super versatile DB with excellent range, quality coverage skills, and a willingness to go and make plays all over the field. If he can round back into his freshman year form, which he showed evidence of doing this past season, Washington now has an amazing player to use in multiple roles.

Derwin James is another prospect I could see soaring up draft boards
in most drafts, but again with so many QBs on the board he will probably
slide down to this range. I think James has loads of potential and could 
become a pro bowl safety with the right tutelage and coaching. The
Redskins appear to be trying to contend as Jay Gruden is sort of
coaching for his job at this point. Derwin could help this defense
really take steps forward along with a healthy Jonathan Allen back.
Dallas needs safety help. FS and SS. 19 to 15 is close enough to where they give up one of their 3rds and get a guy who is falling that could reshape their entire secondary.

Trade details: DAL trades picks #19 and 50 | MIA trades pick #11 Dallas has greatly missed Barry Church, and James is a guy who can fill that role. Given that James is in the running with NYJ’s Jamal Adams for best SS since Eric Berry, it’s actually fair to say he may even end up being better than Church. Dallas found good young corners last year (Lewis, Awuzie, and Woods) and a quality free safety two years ago (Jones). Now, they grab their thumper to complete the revamping of a secondary that was not looking good a couple short years ago. Dallas now has one of the top young secondaries in the league.

With Chubb, Nelson, and Barkley all gone, the Bucs decide to address their secondary with Derwin James. James can run a legit 4.40 40 yard dash and can hit like a truck. His combination of speed and physicality makes me believe that he can play a safety/linebacker hyybrid role and should server as a jack-of-all-trade defensive back that the Bucs need. While they'd love for Barkley, Chubb, or Nelson to fall, they are just as happy selecting James and continuing the FSU to Tampa Bay pipeline. They'll address running back later, as it is a deep class, as well as address cornerback later.

Dallas swaps #19, and gives up their 81st and 193rd to secure Derwin James. Since Dallas is hosting the event, there is almost now way owner Jerry Jones won't move up and make a splash. If Derwin falls this far, expect Jerry to be on the horn to make this deal happen. This works for Arizona as well as they want to pick up a QB, but 15th is too soon to draft either Miller or Rudolph.
Athletically elite play making safety. Get him on the field and he will improve this defense. James is dynamic and versatile.
Jerry has his guys trade up for the most talented S in the class who could be an instant difference maker.
The Chargers get a good one in James and their defense becomes even scarier.
good fuckin snag boys
A safety that can HOUSE IT
Green Bay really needs a corner, but they can’t pass up the safety James.  He has all-pro potential at either safety position, and can lock down the backfield with Ha-Ha.
A Swiss army knife defender is somehting the Bucs could use dearly. James is athletic as all hell and has great instincts to boot
Not the biggest need, James is a top 10 prospect and the Packers need secondary help. Sometimes all a team needs is a leader and I think he can sort their secondary out.
Ideal size, athleticism, leadership. Jamal Adams 2.0
A dream scenario for Green Bay. Safety might not be the biggest need for GB, but Derwin is a fringe blue-chip player and would upgrade their defense immediately.

The Chargers are jumping with joy when their pick comes around. It's not a huge need, but with Tre Boston's asking price as a free agent, the Chargers could move on for much cheaper and take the standout of the 2018 NFL Combine, Derwin James.

(Originally Minkah Fitzpatrick) The Packers need all kinds of secondary help, and this is a great way to start. They get the best SS in the draft. He's an athletic freak of nature, and he will do big things in Green Bay.
After trading down with the Bills, Bucs still land the guy of their dreams.
The Broncos can't pass up the chance to draft a potential superstar here in Derwin James, locking up the best player available and a huge help to a defense that was once extremely feared.

After a disappointing season, the Bucs will look to bounce back and fill one of the many holes they have. After missing out on Chubb, Barkley, and Nelson, they trade down with Buffalo to acquire more picks. Then, they use the first pick of the haul to the most talented safety in this year's draft in Derwin James. I'm really high on James and I think he's a top-5 talent. Although this last season was not his best for Florida State, he possesses raw talent that, if developed correctly, can make him a beast in the NFL.
The Pack have a lot of needs right now. I was back and forth between S, CB, and WR for them here. Ultimately I settled on the BPA of the three positions

The Raiders and new head coach Jon Gruden could seek to add an offensive playmaker such as Derrius Guice with this pick. That would be a bit of a reach in the top ten though. James is a hard-hitting safety that will give the Raiders secondary a sorely needed identity.
BPA and fills a position of need. Derwin is a versatile defender who can play in the box at SS or LB, cover TEs and slot WRs, and potentially play back in a deep zone
James fills an immediate strong safety hole on a weak secondary

Derwin is one of the most versatile players in this draft. Dude played everywhere for FSU. He's an athletic freak. He fills a major position of need for the Buccaneers. I can definitely see them going Minkah or Ward here too. But Justin Evans at FS and Derwin at SS with the ability to roam all over the defense is too enticing. Definitely a tough call here though.

I hate this pick. I hate it so much. Derwin James has the potential to be an perrenial All-Pro Safety in the league. The idea of him being in a Washington jersey upsets me greatly but you just can't get a better player here. I think he'll be the last of consensus blue chippers to go.

Derwin James won't fall this far. I know i have him falling here in this draft but i just can't foresee 15 teams passing on someone like him. The perfect LB/SS blend in todays NFL who might also be a top 2 athlete in the draft. If he somehow does fall to the Chargers the card will fly in.
Fits nicely next to Collins
Elliot is one of my favorite players in the class. Good pick for Arizona here.
While I think Jesse Bates would be a great fit here, unfortunatly hes off the board and instead Elliot is a very solid FS that has very good coverage skills and could start day 1.
I have a 1st round grade on Elliot and he can play either SS or FS

The Saints are in the enviable position of drafting almost solely for depth at this point. Sure, maybe they're linebacker corps could use an upgrade Anzalone's a walking injury waiting to happen, Klein and Davis are both solid in the run game but not so great against the pass but the value's not right at LB here, and the fourth round (really the whole of the third day) is for grabbing value, not reaching to fill needs when no one expects a fourth rounder to contribute much anyway. With Vonn Bell, Marcus Williams and Kurt Coleman the Saints have some depth at safety, but Bell is only average in coverage IMO (and OK against the run) and Coleman turns 30 this summer. It certainly wouldn't hurt them to have a guy like Elliott waiting in the wings, who some people have mocked as high as the second round. And as a bonus, he played plenty of downs at UT lined up as a linebacker, so if Klein and Davis aren't up for the job of coverage, maybe Elliott can flex into the hybrid role from time to time. He's strong enough against the run to hold up. Maybe he'll thrive enough to make the switch permanent.

Kansas City needs a true lockdown compliment to Berry, and Elliot can step in Day 1 and be just that. He's always in position to make a play and can absolutely make a QB think twice about throwing in his direction

Adding to the secondary should be a priority for Carolina, and with a CB already selected, they should look towards the best safety available. Texas safety Deshon Elliott fits that bill, with his incredibly aggressive coverage and willingness to play downhill. Elliott plays physical with receivers, and attacks the ball at it's high point. He's a smart player, and will come down to the box multiple times a game. He could be better athletically, but he does a great job to make up with that with early breaks on the ball.
He always falls so is he really good? :thinking:
