They need a FS to replace Boston, and Elliot is a playmaker who can instantly come in and compliment the Addae revival in the Chargers Safety corps

So who are the jewels of day 3? There's usually around 5 10 guys that most of the drafting world had graded as top 3 round picks who fall here (not counting the 3rd 4th guys), and sometimes the team picking first can get a windfall. So let's see... Mark Andrews maybe? Tyquan Lewis? Maybe Chukwuma Okorafor and Kyle Lauletta too. And of course Shaquem the dream the feel good story is still around. I wonder if he's still sitting in the green room? Man I hope not. My hunch is anyone wanting to trade with Cleveland during the Friday Saturday overnight is gonna have to blow them away, most likely with future picks. They've still got plenty of picks coming up, what good does it do them to, for example, drop ten spots and swap with the Rams for two extra sixth round picks? For some teams I think that would work, but for the Browns, I doubt it. And I'm not sure any of the guys left are worth tossing a future third at. I'm sure plenty of NFL might think otherwise, but I can't see it right now. So I've got the Browns staying put and drafting Harrison, throw him into the mix at OT. Or more like, sit him for awhile and teach him up and hope you don't have to throw him into the mix at OT. He's raw as sushi, only ever played games against Jucos and little tiny schools, but man, what a unit. We all saw what he did at the combine, set it on fire then he stoked the flames. He's got some off

LaAdrian Waddle will probably be the Patriots starter at LT entering the 2018, but it’s likely Bill B will look for a long-term option early in the draft. Desmond Harrison has LT potential but also his fair share of character concerns. Belichick isn’t one to shy away from concerns of this nature, so I think he’s a realistic option for the Patriots. From what I’ve heard, it’s still in the air whether or not Dante Scarnecchia returns. His return would only help Harrison, but I like his upside regardless.
Broncos need to start sorting out they O line, Harrison is freakishly atheletic and could compete for RT this year.

This pick's gonna roll around and a lotta Colts fans are gonna be screaming for an O lineman, and I think one would have been in consideration had Chark not been available. But they're gonna look up at all the offensive linemen still on the board and they'll know that they've got another pick coming up at 49 and instead they're gonna go for what some people might think is the last of the first round receivers. We all know Chark has the potential to be special, like A.J. Green style. 6'4 guys shouldn't be able to run like he runs, and in the Indy offense with him on one side and Hilton wreaking havoc on the other, if Luck's shoulder is healthy, he's gonna have a lot of fun throwing to these guys. All that speed is gonna open up the running game too, and let's be honest Indy fans... I think Ryan Grant's been underappreciated too, but he's not a guy who stops you from upgrading a position. He came into last season as like the fourth option on the Redskins, and it's not like they had Desean Jackson and Pierre Garcon ahead of him anymore. I doubt I'm reinventing the wheel here by saying you need to improve at WR, but you need to improve at WR.

Odell Beckham has been on the trading block. Even if you think he doesn't get traded this season, he could be tageed and traded after the season. I just don't see OBJ wanting to sign a long term deal with the Giants at this point. Enter DJ Chark another freak WR from LSU. He can develop next to OBJ and start to develop chemistry with Rosen now

The Bengals need speed at WR. Literally nobody on their squad has top-end speed. Their OL can block forever but what good is that when their WRs can't get open? With Chark on the roster, the Bengals will have a charkboard full of new plays.

First, let me start by saying I am not a huge Chark fan. He reminds me of a more athletic Sammie Coates. I'm giving him to Pitt due to the fact that Eli Rogers is a low impact player, Martavis may be gone, and DHB is getting older by the year. Chark can come in Day 1 for 4WR sets and give an absolute nightmare for DBs faced with defending AB, JuJu, Bryant, and Chark, with Bell in the backfield.

The Saints are another team that need a WR. Brandin Cooks leaving hurt their passing game a bit, and Coby Fleener doesn't look like the receiving option they wanted him to be. DJ Chark surprised some people in the combine, and I'm thinking that he will be a great speedster that is opposite of Michael Thomas.

Trade details: See pick #58. After grabbing Da’Ron Payne, the Falcons are in the position of not really having a glaring need, and this allows them to go for value. Mohamed Sanu is a solid #2 WR, but I believe D.J. Chark can surpass him and provide an even better complement to Julio Jones. At absolute worst, he replaces the skill set Atlanta lost when Taylor Gabriel left in free agency.
HOUSTON
Deep Threat to compliment Hilton... makes a great trio at WR for Luck
Fast. Speed kills. He can get to point a to point b with quickness
Panthers add a deep threat to complement Funchess. I could definatley see Chark going higher becuase of his 40 time and people like to jump on the bandwagon of fast WR's.
The 49ers get another athletic target for Jimmy Garoppolo to throw to.

I think we can all assume Landry's gonna be there for a long time, but Josh Gordon's Josh Gordon, and he might do a lot of Josh Gordon things. It seems short sighted to not have a contingency plan. And I don't know what to think of Corey Coleman at this point, I have a hunch the narrative on him right now is worse than his actual performance (a big time drop will do that for you), but it's got to be a consideration as well. A lot of people have Moore atop their boards at WR and while some might argue he's a bit superfluous with Landry already aboard, I disagree. I see Moore as an outside receiver in the Steve Smith mold, and him, Gordon and Landry make for one of the best receiver corps in the league. I have to say as I'm doing this I'm somewhat baffled by all the talent that appears to be on the Browns roster. I could easy see a Jags style leap in their immediate future, I think they might have more sheer talent than any other team in the AFC North. Of course winning takes a lot more than talent, and the Browns do have the issue of Hee

With Taylor Gabriel heading to the Chicago Bears thr Falcons have a need at WR. Moore has the speed to outrun corners on the outside and the quickness and experience to run shorter routes underneath. If teams want to double team Julio Jones the Falcons will be happy with Moore as a second option

The first WR off the board is not Ridley, but Moore, for the Cowboys. Dez Bryant is still on the roster, and with the addition of Allen Hurns, Moore is the best fit for the Cowboys in the slot. He has a good blend of size and quickness and is great after the catch.
The Pats no longer have a WR1. Or WR3 really. Or Punt Returner. So they get all of the above in DJ Moore who when paired up with Tom Brady is absolutely disgusting to think about.

It was tough between Wynn and Moore, but I'm betting they all some dynamic talent to their offense here, and Moore fits the bill. Despite playing with terrible QBs, he's put up great numbers and has elite athleticism. A perfect compliment to Julio.

Dez Bryant isn't the Dez we once knew. Allen Hurns and Deonte Thompson aren't true WR1s, so this is where DJ Moore can come in and be a WR1. DJ Moore took the combine and curb-stomped it. With that and his Pro Day performance, he is WR1 in this draft.
Colts WR corps is thin as of now and with the addition of the electric DJ Moore, it gives Luck another weapon to ease him back after injury.
With talk of previous 1st round pick Byron Jones moving to corner the BPA fills his hole at S nicely.

Baltimore's offensive, specifically their receiving corp, has been a hot mess since Steve Smith retired. Breshad Perriman and Jeremy Maclin were huge letdowns, leaving Baltimore to rely on the now-departed Mike Wallace as their only playmaker. Signing Michael Crabtree gives them a great redzone threat, but drafting a guy like DJ Moore gives them an every down playmaker that they desperately need. The Maryland product is a truly amazing athlete who works well in space and can make plays at each level of the field. Most importantly, DJ Moore brings consistency to the receiving game which could go a long way for Baltimore's offense.

D.J. Moore leapfrogs Courtland Sutton due to his freak combine. 
Moore is a quality receiver who should help the Panther offense after they
traded away Kelvin Benjamin last season. Moore could spread the 
field for Cam Newton and allow the offense to have a less one 
dimensional approach without Shula and let McCaffery run lose.

The prodigal son returns home with the Eagles picking Moore to star at WR opposite of Alston, and allowing Algohlar to remain in the slot. Moore is a philly original and provides a different enough look to keep defenses unbalanced
The Ravens fill arguably their biggest need here with my WR1.
Solid choice with high upside
D.J. Moore lands at 27 to the loaded Saints.  He’s speedy, a great route-runner, and could lock down the receiver position across from Michael Thomas in a Stefon Diggs like role for Brees.
While this wouldnt be my pick, every year WR get taken higher than expected. I dont think the Cowboys are going to expect either Dez or Hurns to be the longer term No.1 so they get their guy.
Underrated WR with good size/speed. Fantastic after catch, productive (1000+ yards, 8TDs) despite 4 different QBs, punt returner.

Really surprised to see two WRs go in the top 15, but Baltimore is still able to nab my top target in D.J. Moore. The star of the combine not only measured in taller/bigger than expected, but tested as an elite athlete in every catagory. Moore carried the passing game single-handedly in College Park, and will be asked to do the same one hour down the road in Baltimore.

DJ Moore gives the Dolphins the opportunity to replace Jarvis Landry. They already addressed LB, which leaves their primary needs to be TE or C... I don't see much value in drafting a C here, and all the top TEs are gone.
I'm still not convinced the Jaguars are happy with their recieving core, after letting both Robinson and Hurns go, and Moore gives this Bortles another talent to throw to.

Wide receiver was one of the Cowboys' biggest holes to fill this offseason, and that hole just got much larger with Dez Bryant's departure, so they choose DJ Moore out of Maryland. From what I have heard, some teams have Moore as the number one receiver ahead of Calvin Ridley. They're pretty similar as prospects, too. While Moore is on the smaller side, he is a jack-of-all-trades type receiver who will be a big impact for the team that drafts him.

After releasing Dez Bryant, the Cowboys have a huge need at WR (they did sign Allen Hurns however.) Speculation still points to them adding a receiver early, and in this scenario they could have their choice of any in the draft. Moore is rising up draft boards, he would give Prescott an exciting young weapon to throw to.
IND needs to give Luck more help

Ravens probably mad that th Cowboys swooped Minkah, but it doesn't matter because they need to focuse on offense. They absolutely need to get some Weapons. I know they signed Crabtree, Snead, and John Brown. But Perriman has been a bust, Crabtree is old and not very good anymore. They are missing that #1 WR that they desperately need. DJ Moore is that guys - and he's local too. Moore is the best WR in this draft and finally gets the Ravens a top passing weapon, even if Flacco isn't around too much longer.

I've been on the DJ Moore train since well before draft season began much like i was Stefon Diggs. Watching him move up the draft boards as honestly been a wonder. After his pro day it wouldn't surprise me if he's the first WR off the board. In this scenario Carolina grabs a guy whos main comparison is Steve Smith. DJ Moore will be a top 5 WR is 3-4 year and this will be a great investment for the Panthers.

Much like Vea earlier DJ Moore is another one of my favorite players in this draft. Growing up 10 minutes from the Maryland campus has earned me a life time of misery from Maryland football. DJ Moore is a rare exception. He's extremely talented and he's immediately going to make an impact in this league. Not only is he already extremely talented he also an elite athlete and very young giving him more time to get even better. He'll be a Top 10 Receiver in this league in no time.

I have an inclination the Giants didn't tend to address CB this soon, given the projected rounds of most of the guys they've visited with, but the draft is a fluid thing and when a guy like Jackson falls to you, you adjust. And Gettleman will adjust, he's renowned throughout the league as a BPA guy (as such, I would expect a few picks that don't fill your biggest needs, Giants fans. That's a Gettleman draft for you. I mean, you guys have so many needs anyway I'm sure he'll hit them no matter who he drafts). Eli Apple might have been brought back, but can you really trust him, Giants fans? How soon before he and Collins are fist fighting after a tough loss in the locker room? Even if they manage to make it through the season together, who's the NB next to Apple and Jenkins? All I can see on the roster right now are a bunch of FAs and low round picks. Jackson's got first round measurables and I've been looking for a place to put him for a round now, but the teams where I thought he might fit either like their CBs in the Seattle style (tall and long

I wanted to cheat and put Brian O'Neil here and just take Isaiah Oliver at 43 but I don't think O'Neil would fall this far. I thought about Hayden Hurst but if he is supposed to be a "Gronk Replacement" he isn't a good enough blocker. Ultimately Jackson is a similar build to Butler but he is a better athlete.
San Fran also wants to continue to develop their CB corps, even with the Sherman signing. Donte Jackson is very athletic and can develop to being a very reliable player with the right coaching

Minnesota is in the market for a slot defender, and this is a great spot for Jackson’s athletic upside to get him drafted. This could end up being a steal is Jackson learns to harness his raw athleticism and speed into more consistency in coverage.
Speed kills, in this case at CB. The secondary is one of the few areas that could use upgrading for the Vikings in this draft
Very fast undersized corner, can play slot and perimeter.
Pats get help at DB and arguably the best athlete in the class.
He's super raw to me idk I don't love him here
Jackson can play Nickel Corner or outside corner. He has very good speed and fits in the Falcons fast secondary.
Replaces Taylor Gabriel. Instantly boosts their return game.

No matter what you think of Shane Ray as the starter opposite Von Miller, Denver could use some depth on the edge. Armstrong's an intriguing guy who might have gone a lot higher than this if he'd been in last year's draft, but falls due to a subpar 2017. But it's starting to look like we should take those 2017 numbers with a grain of salt. He was shifted into a different role on the Kansas defense, tasked with stopping the run before attacking the pass. That's not his strength (though perhaps the experience will benefit him). If you want to get the most out of Armstrong, you put him on the edge to attack. He didn't test as well as some thought he would, but he's plenty athletic on his game tape. Denver's had a lot of luck with Jayhawk alums recently (Talib, Harris), why not go back to the well? We know they've met with him, and as I’ve said, that means something to Denver.

EDGE help is needed now more than ever for the Giants, and Dorance has an immense amount of talent and can contribute Day 1 rotating in. He'll be a stud for this time, and put all 10 fingers in action on every play.
Armstrong doesn't have the production you would want from a person with his skillset, but the mix of power and and speed is going to help him a lot at the next level.

I’m not as big on Armstrong as some others, but this is a really good risk/reward value for a team in desperate need of an edge rusher. This pick has the potential to pay off big, and if it doesn’t, the Jets don’t lose a ton of value long-term.
Armstrong is a tough evaluation. Has some big potential though
Kony Ealy replacement
While not the most athletic LB, O'Daniel is good in coverage and I very reliable. He can defo compete for starting roles and is also an amazing special teams player.
While Armstrong didn't have much production last year he definatley has potential to go good. This could be one of those draft steals in years to come.

The Broncos have done a good job during the offseason of turning their needs from 'OMG we're dead if we don't draft a edge guy' into something more along the lines of 'maybe we got it covered now?', but in no universe is Tramaine Brock a legitimate replacement for Aqib Talib. I guess technically Bradley Roby's the replacement for Aqib Talib, but have we decided whether he's actually any good or not, Broncos fans? Maybe? Well either way you gotta throw another body into the mix and here's one, Duke Dawson's. He's predominantly a nickel back but he's one of the best, sticky like sticky rice, first team All SEC baby! Those are some bona fides. Great in press, great tackler, smart fella and fundamentally sound like a smart fella tends to be. You don't want to line him up against one of those groots on the outside, and he's gonna get smoked now and again by the track guys, but everyone else is a rock and he's paper. And isn't everyone in nickel all the time anyway nowadays?
Dawson is undersized but he has good speed and quickness to make up for it. He should be able to contribute right away. Best used as a nickel corner but could be a matchup play on the outside as well

With Rhodes having and amazing year and Tre Waynes stepping up, the only hole left is Nickle corner to take over from the ancient Terrance Newman. Dawson is a scrappy slot corner that would instantly make this secondary even better.

Philly's only got one pick over the past three rounds, so this trade down makes sense for them. This makes for the third round in a row Green Bay has traded up, it's a good strategy with a lot of picks, sit back and strike. It's really too bad Ejiofor couldn't participate in any of the pre draft process. I would have liked to see if he tested as more athletic than he looked on tape, like Sam Hubbard and Marcell Frazier. We all know it happens, sometimes athleticism shows up in sneaky ways, a guy who makes a ton of plays might actually be making them cause he's got the sneaky explosion to drive at a QB or RB at the last moment, even though he might not have looked so explosive getting there. Or sometimes what looks like a lumbering step is actually a long, faster one. We see it all the time with RBs and WRs, they don't look like they're going fast, yet they're blowing by everyone. Maybe Ejiofor's like that too, I wish we knew. Because now we're left to look at the tape, and while I think he's pretty advanced as a collegiate DE with his hand usage and his moves and counters, it's hard to say he looks like anything more than an average athlete. Too bad. He's been one of my favorite guys throughout the process (I even mocked him to my Lions in the second round back in February), but I always questioned his athleticism and hoped I'd get answers. I didn't, and the league won't, so I imagine he'll fall. I don't know if he's athletic enough to play on the edge in Green Bay's defense, but it's not like Nick Perry or Clay Matthews are Sparq monsters (or Vince Bieber, for that matter), Ejiofor seems like he'd be close to those guys as athletes, and he's got a lot of other things to offer in attack. And if it doesn't work out, he can put on a few pounds and shift inside.

Ejiofor is average atheltically for his position but he is a technically sound pass rusher and strong against the run. Ejiofor is a high effort player and is the type of player Bowles should be targeting at this point in the draft. The Jets aren't very good and need dedicated football players to start getting better
Seattle has holes everywhere now, so it's BPA for them. Duke can work in Pete's defense and can help make a difference on a team which looks like it's actively rebuilding
After going ILB in the first, they grab an impact EDGE in the 2nd and can rest easy knowing they're two most needed spots for help are taken care of before they skip their 3rd round with the trade up
EDGE help. Lots of upside
Ejiofor is a solid edge player and will instantly improve their pass rush. He definatley has potential to get 5-10 sacks a season.

The Packers have a ton of picks to play around with, so it's no surprise to see them moving up in each of the past two rounds. Here they move for a guy who'll fit seamlessly into their receiver corps in St. Brown. There are some who think he might wind up the best receiver in the class. I don't know about that, but there's no doubt you can basically throw 2017 out the window. Notre Dame morphed into a poor QB'd running team and St. Brown didn't have much of a chance to show what he could do. Go back to 2016 though, and it makes you think those people who say he could be the best in the class might be right. With Adams on one side and Cobb slicing and dicing through the middle, they could use a tall gazelle to open up the other side (Geronimo Allison doesn't count). And he shouldn't have any problems adapting to the pros. It's not that big of an adjustment going from Wimbush to Rodgers. It's like catching passes from the same guy.

Allen Robinson went to the Bears leaving the Jags with a need for a red zone target. Brown didn't get a ton of looks at ND due to poor QB play but his measurables are tantilizing and he has a ton of potential.

It's not a WR's job to teach other WRs, by the idea of ESB learning fro Larry Fitz makes me happy to think about. He needs to learn to give 100% and play harder, so there's not no better mentor in the league than Larry Fitz for that in my eyes. Who knows - he may end up his successor.

Some Eagles fans will get mad at me for this, but I like ESB to them. The Eagles still have to shore up a few problems with their receiving corp, but ESB is a very solid guy to them for a couple reason. Alshon Jeffery + Equanimeous St. Brown can be a downright nasty combo. Alshon Jeffery a 6'3 possession guy, and Equanimeous St. Brown, a 6'5 receiver who ran a 4.48, which is faster than Christian Kirk and Courtland Sutton. Basically with this pick, they have 2 receivers that can be matchup nightmares against smaller AND/OR slower DBs.

Pierre Garcon and Marquise Goodwin proved to be solid WR’s this past season, but I wouldn’t feel comfortable with them as my two best options long-term. St. Brown has #1 upside and could benefit from working in a secondary role for a year or two. The biggest reason for this pick is the value-to-upside ratio he could provide the Niners with in the future.

St. Brown is an intelligent WR that sees like too good of a fit for the Pats to not go here, especially after trading away Brandin Cooks. This pick is tricky though as the Pats typically don't draft WR and never this high.
BUF trades 2018 2nd, 4th, and JAX 5th for WAS 2018 2nd and 7th
Big bodied and strong handed

The 49ers should look to add a WR 1, Equanimeous St. Brown has massive potential to fill in that hole. He's 6'5 and ran a 4.48 at the combine. He needs keep adding a little weight but other than that he has the potential to be their No 1 reciever.
A bit of an overdraft, but a perfect successor to Poz. Day 1 starter

I like Ragnow as a fit in San Francisco cause I think he'll make a better guard than center (and the Niners just signed Richburg to play center). A lot of people disagree with me and that's fine, but I thought the most alarming part of Ragnow's game was his delayed response to stunts and twists. It popped off the screen to me (perhaps cause I look for it) and while he was able to recover for the most part, I immediately thought of the potential crushing my QB might take if I drafted him in the NFL. At guard, that's not such an issue. Richburg can identify those things ahead of time and ready his linemates to take action. I much prefer the idea of Ragnow shifting to center only in a pinch, and given Richburg's concussion history, it's good to have a capable backup around. I also didn't think Ragnow was the greatest athlete at guard, but otherwise I really like him. He's a nasty dawg for one I think that's why he's such a favorite of the drafting community, we always love the dawgs and despite his delayed response to stunts, he never gave up a sack in the SEC. That's impressive. I also think he's one of the best interior linemen in the class at reaching the second level (behind only Daniels), and he's got a knack once he's there for keeping his balance and securing the block. I expect a long career from him, as long as he's used the right way.

The Broncos need to add depth on the OL especially with a rookie QB. Ragnow is a center but he is taller than most at his position. It hasn't been an issue for him to this point but he could certainly fill in at guard as well

Different Center, Same Need. Ragnow (assuming he's healthy) is an immediate improvement on this line. Their defense is coming together on its own, but they need to fix their Offense ASAP to stay competitive in the AFCN

As much as I want to double dip on Wide Receivers here, I'll play it safe and go with Ragnow to provide them flexibility on their line with Jensen gone. Ragnow could move to Guard or Center depending on what Harbaugh likes, so it'll be a big asset for the teams future
He's definitely got the coolest name in the draft. It just sounds strong. And Ragnow is strong. They end the run of OL players.
Bodine is very bad and should not be the starting center. Ragnow can come in and form a relationship with whoever ends up winning the QB job, McCarron or Allen.

The Redskins are set at LT, RT, and RG, but there are question surrounding the LG and C. Chase Roullier flashed some potential last year and seems destined to get a shot to fill one of those holes. Frank Ragnow can fill the other.
Ragnow is a beast despite missing half of the season due to a lower leg injury. He can play either G or C and plug some holes in the Dolphins O-Line. Not a bad pick up at all at 42.
I really like this pick for the Cowboys. Ragnow gives them options on the OL.
Good value. I'm not the highest on him but he's solid af
The Chiefs currently need a guard, Ragnow is a versatile inside lineman. I think Ragnow would be better off starting at guard and I think he only falls to late 2nd because of some injuries.
After losing both Eric Wood and Richie Incognito to retirement, the Bills go with the best IOL left on the board.

This is a really hard pick to figure out. We've reached the point of the draft where it's gonna start moving further and further away from what we think of as chalk and more into WTF territory. Or maybe it's not as dramatic as WTF, maybe it's more subdued like 'hmmm, that's interesting' or 'didn't see that coming' or something like that. The point is, strange stuff's about to start happening. Our valuations are gonna start to differ drastically from the NFL's valuations, and it's really hard to tell who they're going to evaluate as better players than we do, cause it's gonna vary on a team by team basis. Honestly, just take a look at the receivers who are left. The narrative probably says Washington or Miller is the next to come off the board, maybe St. Brown. But I expect NFL boards will be all over the place. Some will have Pettis ranked highest remaining, some Deon Cain, some Gallup, some even DaeSean Hamilton or Antonio Callaway. It could literally be almost anyone of like, twenty guys. So it's in that vein of thinking that I'm giving the 49ers Warner here. Throughout the draft process he's answered most of the questions people had about him
Warner is a fast athletic LB that fits the mold of the Jags current core. Posluzny has retired and there is an a need for a LB on the Jags
Oakland needs LB help, and Fred Warner is the cure. He's incredibly talented and can immediately step in on Day 1 in my eyes. He's a steal here, and one that the Raiders desperately needed to find

Trade details: See pick #56. Jerrell Freeman had a bad time in Chicago after facing a significant injury and PED suspension. It’s not surprise the Bears decided to move on this offseason. They do, however, have to find a starting backer to replace Freeman, and Fred Warner is an athletic playmaker.
I like Fred but not this early
Warner is a solid tackler and decent in coverage, he can come in and add some competition to the cowboys LB's.

The Chargers are perilously thin at LB outside of Denzel Perryman, not that I think Avery can step in and fill one of the holes that's not something you count on from a fourth rounder, it's something you hope for. And at this point it doesn't hurt to throw bodies at the problem, especially a body like Avery's. One of the best things about Avery is how scheme and position versatile he is. He can play inside or outside, he can rush the passer, he can cover backs and tight ends (a work in progress, he's much better right now against the run which just so happens to be a weakness of the Chargers). He's built like a tank and strong as an ox (state champion power
Buffalo needs to improve their LB corps during this draft, and find Avery waiting for them at the top of Rd 3. He's freaky fast with a lot of potential and will fit in well here
The Cowboys need a SAM LB after losing Anthony Hitchens to the Chiefs, and Avery projects as a good fit for the role. His athletic upside means he could become a special backer, too.
Avery doesn't have much pass rush ability so I think he would be better suited at ILB, hes very strong and a good tackler, exactly what the Colts need.

The roster fix is a long term one for the Jets, so they can afford to draft a guy with whom they'll have to be patient. If it takes Christian a year or two to come good, well that's right with the timeline. He played in one of those janky college schemes but has three years of starting experience. He's got a perfect LT frame and long arms, but he needs time to fill out. He's a great athlete for the position as a former basketball player and he rarely gets beat inside something I imagine the Jets and their rookie QB will really like about him. Still, he's far more of an athlete than a technician, he has problems staying strong at the point of attack and gets walked into the backfield by powerful defenders, and he can often seem a step slow not because of his athleticism, but because he doesn't have confidence in what he sees. He might be a superstar in three years, but the Jets will hope he takes to coaching quicker than that. But I'm not shocking anyone here by mocking the Jets an offensive tackle, everyone knows they need one, they might even need two. To find a guy with this kind of upside in the third is a draft victory.
Keep re-building that line
Christian is a developmental tackle with a lot of potential, hes entered the draft a little early. However ho could probably start at RT because of how bad their current RT is.
While Senat didn't have the combine I was hoping for, he still is a strong OT, I think he could come in and start at RT.

So I think it's Landry vs. Edmunds, and when you decide Landry's underrated while Edmunds is slightly overrated (as I have), this is a more even decision than you'd think. The Niner D is crying out for a guy like Landry to plug into their LEO spot, or even maybe at SAM, so it's pretty damn convenient that the value matches up here (the way I see it anyway, and the way I imagine the Niners see it too). Landry's got Von Miller potential if he can reach his ceiling, and there's not a lot of dudes you can say that about. Now I will say, Landry's got some bad tape, especially in 2017, which makes him sort of an odd evaluation. Because it's more of a projection more than an evaluation. You're looking at that 2016 tape when he shredded everyone and you're justifying his subpar 2017 by saying he was injured. Well, maybe. But you better be right. FWIW, I believe they are.
While I have some concerns about Landry in the run game against NFL OTs, there is no questioning he is an elite pass rusher and could be a nightmare for Wilson and Goff for the next decade

The 49ers are able to trade back with Arizona and still land the second best edge prospect in the draft in Harold Landry. He has great pursuit against the run and is a fluid athlete with good twitch. He is also a fit for the Niner’s 4-3 defensive scheme.

Chicago can grab a top CB here, or Top LB, but I feel like the EDGE premier rushers are slim pickens so they grab someone who can line up opposite Floyd and put some real damage down on teams, and in turn, make their CBs lives MUCH easier
A dynamic EDGE rusher who should be able to fill the SAM spot in Miami’s D very well, and make Raekwon’s return much easier and Kiko less of a liability

Harold Landry is a big on the small end, but he's got energy and a load of pass rush ability. Solomon Thomas is good as a run stopper, but isn't the greatest pass rusher and Arik Armstead is inconsistent. Harold Landry would be a great addition and fit on the team as a pass rusher
The rich get richer. The Eagles defensive line just gets deeper and deeper. Landry is a talent.
Landry is the best EDGE prospect aside from Chubb and the Niners OLB/EDGE position is weak compared to days of years past.
He may be a bit undersized for a 4-3 DE but Landry may be the best pure pass rusher in this class. The Giants have a JPP sized hole at d-line, Landry would see a lot of playing time immediately.
Patricia builds his defense with an edge rusher

Harold Landry is a seamless fit in Green Bay's 3-4 defense, for placing him in a 3-4 OLB role allows his talents to flourish. Landry has elite bend and overall athleticism coupled with a nasty first step that makes him a problem for opposing OTs. He battled through injuries in 2017, but there's a reason he led the entire country in sacks in 2016. His explosiveness and fluidity as a pass rusher makes him a sought after commodity in the NFL. He needs to work on his run defense, but Green Bay could use him in more of a pure pass rushing role at least to start out.

The Saints are a few pieces away from winning the Super Bowl
and will do whatever they need to get Brees his second ring before
he decided to hang it up. Their defense and overall draft class last year
was way past expectations and adding Landry could honestly put them
in great contention for a top 10 defense after being so bad for so long. 
Landry is a great pass rusher who has dealt with injuries but should 
bounce back and show promise in the NFL.
The 49ers get a guy I believe they may be considering around 9th overall anyways, and now with extra draft capital. Landry is the edge that they need and love.

Boy, what a crazy season the 49ers had. A simple trade for Jimmy Garoppolo turned the short-term aspirations of that franchise around. The team still isn’t without its holes, but finding a franchise QB has the Niners undoubtedly trending up. One of the glaring holes on SF’s roster in at edge rusher. The Niners drafted Solomon Thomas #3 overall in 2017, but he’s more suited for the Michael Bennett role in their 4-3 (LEO). SF is still looking for that quick burst and bend off the edge, and that’s where Landry comes in.
BRONCOS FROM BILLS

EDGE is arguably the biggest hole on the 49ers roster. They ranked 26th in sacks, and Landry, along with Thomas, Buckner, and Armstead could go a long way to fix that ranking. However, Rueben Foster's ugly legal situation could cause them to go linebacker with this pick. Based on how a pass-rusher can be so valuable, I think they go Haroldl Landry and take a linebacker later in the draft.

Landry is a beast, and after trading away JPP, the G-Men cannot rely on Vernon alone. Gettleman is known for taking his big guys up front first and adding Landry at EDGE is a perfect marriage. I love this pick as I think Landry will be the better prospect of all EDGE defenders, including Chubb.

An edge rusher opposite Khalil Mack will be very helpful. Mack commands a lot of attention and Landry should be able to take advantage of that and be a productive rusher off the edge. I almost took Roquan Smith but I felt that adding an edge rusher was more important.
Some will agree that Landry is a bit of a reach here but I like the pick for the Bears. Pass rush might be their biggest need now.
has less bend then a piece of wood
he cant bend lol

The 49ers trade back up after already trading down to grab Harold Landry, the talented pass-rusher from Boston College.  Landry was hurt most of this year, but looked like a top-5 pick the year before, and still managed double digit sacks. The 49ers finally grab a legit pass rusher.
This connection makes sense when you consider that there's a need for an edge rusher and his former coach is in Detroit.
Landry will probs have to start off as a 3rd down rusher but I think give him some time and he'll be able to replace the aging Orakpo in his last season in his contract.
Best pure pass rusher in the draft.
Landry is climbing back up draft boards after the combine, and I think that teams will look at his 2016 tape and combine and decide to look past his struggles in 2017.

I fielded a few trade offers here before deciding to stay and pick the Packers next great edge rusher. Landry's size and athleticism certainly fits better in Mike Pettine's 3-4 scheme, but can put his hand in the dirt with he decides to show a 4 man front. Bonus: he gets to learn from a great player in Clay Matthews

San Fran got Thomas last year, and they get another monster in Landry to put opposite of him on the line. They plan to bring the heat this year. They also get some additional draft capital to help their rebuild. While they may typically go pure BPA, they can't miss out on stacking their d-line.
I wasn't sure whether to go with Landry or Vander Esch, but ultimately I felt like Landry had more value here.
The Titans see Harold Landry available and take him to help this defense keep getting stronger giving up a 3rd that seattle desperately needs as well as a future pick.

The 49ers use their first pick of the draft to fill their biggest hole at defensive end with Harold Landry out of Boston College. Landry is a pretty solid EDGE rusher who has been flying up mock drafts in the past few weeks. Although he isn't the best against the run, Landry is very fast and good at pressuring the quarterback. First of all, I think there's a very high probability the Pats trade Gronk (it may have already happened by the time I get around to posting this). Belichick is renowned for getting rid of guys a year early, not a year late. Hell, he might have already waited too long. But whether they trade him or not I think they'll be drafting a TE this year, and I think they'll be drafting one early. Now, one thing about the Pats over the years, it's usually possible to get an idea what position they'll go, but we almost always get the player wrong. And that's because they value different things than we do as a drafting community. Sometimes it works (Logan Mankins, Jimmy Garoppolo, Jamie Collins), sometimes it doesn't (Ras I Dowling, Chad Jackson, Aaron Dobson), but they stick with the way they do things, and can you blame them? Look at all those trophies. So while most of the drafting community will have both Gesicki and maybe Hurst rated above Thomas, my hunch is the Pats value a TE's blocking ability more than most (see Gronkowski, Rob). Thomas is still raw as both a blocker and a route runner, but man, what a piece of clay to mold. He's humble, he works hard, he's taken to the coaching at Indiana and improved drastically over his time there. He actually reminds me somewhat of David Njoku, though I'd argue he might have a higher upside. He's got the athletic ability and the size to be a multi tool TE, which I think the Pats will value over the one

Answer me this, Vikings fans... when has Spielman ever done what you wanted him to do? That's the vibe I got after I did my first mock, and that vibe was only strengthened as I perused your boards in preparation for this one. He frequently makes you guys angry with his picks. So it can't be shocking that in a draft so deep at the interior of the offensive line (and with only one having come off the board so far), that he'd nab one of the draft fallers at a more premium position and choose to address the interior of the line in the 2nd/3rd round (FWIW, I think Williams is an interior guy too, the only OT worth a first rounder has already come off the board). In his whole history with you guys, he's only drafted an offensive lineman twice in the first two rounds. He's drafted that many CBs in the first round alone (and one of them happens to have a contract that expires at the end of the year). Now I know there are probably lots of linemen you love here, but I'm trying to make this as realistic as possible, and I really think if one of the elite CBs or DTs (or McGlinchey) falls here, he'd nab them over an interior lineman, that's just how he operates. Failing that I think he'd trade down. So when not one not two but three potential first round CBs are staring him in the face, I don't think he can resist. The question, then, is does Spielman prefer a guy who can take over for Alexander in the slot this year (as he's looking more and more like a bust) before potentially flexing outside if Waynes leaves (Mike Hughes, for example, or Jaire Alexander), or does he prefer one of the longer CBs that they use on the outside (Oliver), who'll most likely sit for a year. The Vikings don't appear to have a "type" of CB they like the way Seattle does (Rhodes, Waynes and Mackensie Alexander have very different measurables), I expect if you can cover and hit and listen to coaching, you'll be an option for Zimmer. For me the BPA among those three guys is Jaire Alexander (I have him as 1b to Ward's 1a, in fact he's my CB draft crush), and I highly doubt I'm alone. I see him going higher than Hughes and Oliver on most mocks, so I don't expect it to be much of a surprise. He's got almost everything you want in a corner except height and length, and he makes up for it with bravado, toughness, instincts, ball skills, and well... tick off everything else you're looking for in a CB, cause he's got it. I hate that he falls to the Vikings, of all teams.

Every once in awhile the narrative we've all created together takes over and the delineation between prospects becomes too black and white. I blame the combine, mostly. Take the OT class for instance. If you watch the tape, there's no way you put a guy like Brian O'Neill (who I like, FWIW) ahead of Jones. Yes, he's got some physical traits that are enticing and he's got lots of upside as a guy who hasn't played the position long, but where's his floor? It's basically in the basement. And yet he shows out at the combine and all of a sudden he's a borderline first rounder. Same with Kolton Miller (who actually has better tape than O'Neill). Those guys may or may not turn out to be better pros, but are they really that different as prospects than Jones? No way. Sure, Jones might not have their ceilings, but he's got a higher floor than both of them, and there's something to be said for guys with high floors. It's like fantasy football the most important thing in the first couple of rounds is not busting. The NFL draft isn't quite so rigid in its approach to adding talent (they have more than one year for things to pan out), but it's also prone to guys exceeding their ceilings (or plummeting past their floors). So I don't know if Jones is ever gonna make any pro bowls, but I'm pretty sure he's gonna have a long, productive career, and I think he's great value this late. And given the Texans' tackle needs, this feels like a perfect marriage. Which is why they had to pay something of a premium to get up here. The mantra in Indianapolis is to get faster on defense, and after watching Baker slide towards the end of the third, they decide it's worth it to go up and get him. It costs them a fourth, fifth and sixth to do it, but they've added other picks through the trades they've made throughout the draft, so they can stomach it. Some teams are gonna have as high as a second round grade on Baker, I expect, and Indy strikes me as one who might, given how much they intend to value speed at LB (and Atlanta doesn't have a fifth rounder, and given that Indy's picks are at the top of each round, it's kinda like they're a round higher). Of course they're not the only team valuing speed at LB, so Baker's slight fall is somewhat surprising. Well here's what I was thinking most of the teams looking for speed at LB want a guy who can cover backs and TEs. Baker's one of the fastest LBs, but he really, really struggled covering backs and TEs this past year. Now, maybe that was because he was asked to do something different within the Ohio State scheme, because in 2016 he looked fine. I wouldn't call him lockdown, but he was certainly better in 2016 than 2017. So what happened? Lots of Ohio State fans I've spoken with contend he was asked to do something different within the scheme, but that's not a consensus. And besides, pro teams are gonna ask him to do something different too, it's no reason to go from decent at something to terrible. That combined with questions about his instincts causes him to fall. But we all know Indy wants the fast guys, and they'll give Baker plenty of time to learn a new scheme and adjust to the pro game. He and Edmunds are gonna cover a ton of ground.

Baker is a rangy LB who can run the field, tackle well, and cover RBs and TEs. Sounds like a first round pick. The problem is he hasn't been able to contribute consistently. Hopefully NFL coaching will help him reach his full potential

And thus far at least, Brown hasn't translated that production into regular season performance, averaging just 3.6 YPC on 85 career carries. That doesn't seem like the kind of guy you ride into the season with as your main backup. Kelly's a guy a lot of people love, and it's hard not to watching his smash mouth tape. He doesn't seem like a great athlete (and he didn't really test like one either), but he's got that little sideways glide that looks like it might play in the league, he's a good pass catcher so the Rams wouldn't have to adjust their offense too much with him in, and toughness like his is always welcome. But he's a 205 pound grinder, and there's not a lot of guys like him in the league, he'll have to buck some history to find success (and Phillip Lindsay as a 190 pound grinder will *really have to buck that history, but that doesn't really have anything to do with this pick, I just wanted to mention it).
