Something something darkest timeline, but as I much as I dislike this pick if I am the Jets, his talent (albeit entirely situational) is evident. He'll work with great mentor McCown and sturdy bridge BH2O, he could be in a great situation here

Look, I don't like Allen that much. The production and skill set doesn't match at all, and it's worrisome. At the same time John Elway is the type of guy that thinks he can coach up any QB. I mean, look at Paxton Lynch and Brock Osweiler. They were shit, but Elway is the type of guy that will take a chance on a guy and try to turn him into a diamond. If there's any guy that's worth taking early, but is a project that can be turned into something great, it's Josh Allen (although I hate to admit it). In short, I think Elway is absolute garbage at evaluating QBs, but at the same time, this pick will make sense in his mind.

Another trade into the top 5, this time Miami move up to secure polarizing passer Josh Allen. He can make the throws to wow people, and the existence of Tannehill allows him a bit more time to become more consistent. I like Allen, but he needs time to sit and learn to become a bit more Wentz and a bit less Bortles.
Bills trade up and get the most polarizing QB in the draft. Has a chance to duke it out with AJ McCarron for the starting role in his first year.

I see Allen going much earlier than this, but Allen's raw-ness could put off some teams. His electric arm talent has impressed analysts and scouts, and its not hard to see why. Maybe not pro-ready, but certainly worth the investment.
After John Dorsey's comments about hand size and general interest in Allen's arm strength I think they make the wrong pick and go with Josh Allen number 1.

I'll preface this by saying that I strongly disagree with this pick, but the indication I'm getting is that this will be the pick. Recent reports have narrowed Darnold and Allen down as the 'finalists', and to me I think it's looking more like Josh Allen comes out on top. Cleveland is in desperate need of a franchise QB, but with Tyrod Taylor in the fold, they have the oppurtuntiy to bank on Josh Allen's boom or bust potential and let him develop for a bit. He has a historically strong arm, and if a coach can iron out his accuracy issues, the upside is there for the taking.

The Broncos got Keenum as a stop gap just as the Browns traded for
Tyrod as a stop gap. They are both QBs that probably won't lose you 
games, but won't win you too many. Allen would go to a less than ideal 
situation in Denver as their OL is still under construction and their 
defense is getting older with a less than spectacular offense to speak of. 
I do think it will be good for Allen to sit a few games or even all of the 
season until he understands the grasp concepts of NFL defenses. His
floor is extremely low, but his ceiling is one of the highest in the draft 
and teams that like him should not be afraid to jump on him as long
as they have done their homework.

Originally it was Darnold. Darnold is the absolute right choice to me. There is literally no reason to take anyone but Darnold here. I just think the writing is on the wall at this point, as we're seeing more and more links to Allen. I'm scared the Browns are going to make a mistake here.

Trade details: DEN trades picks #5 and 71 AND a 2019 3rd-round pick | CLE trades pick #4 Denver misses out on Kirk Cousins despite being considered the early favorite by the media, but they really aren’t too upset about it. Case Keenum will make for a fine bridge QB, while Josh Allen develops on the bench. Allen will have solid weapons when he takes over the job, and hopefully, the Broncos will have put the necessary resources into improving their OL by the time he takes over. Allen has only helped himself this offseason. He looked great in the second half of the Senior Bowl, and he followed that by flashing his big arm and interviewing well at the Combine. He’s still raw, and I think it’s fair to say he’s not currently the 5th-best player in this class; however, his upside is undeniable. It makes sense for any team with a decent bridge QB to invest in him potential. I know some will hate the trade, but Denver had to make a compelling enough offer to keep Buffalo from being able to jump all the way up here. Cleveland ultimately favored dropping 1 spot for a couple day 2 picks over dropping 8 spots.
BRONCOS

After not being drafted by Denver, Allen continues to plummet as no teams are willing to trade up to take a chance on him. He falls to Miami where he can sit a year behind Ryan Tannehill before the decide to cut Tannehill loose at the end of the season. Tannehill, who just turned 30, is set to make too much money in the following years so the Dolphins will cut him in an effort to free up some cap space after this season.

I don't like Josh Allen. In my opinion, a 56% career accuracy doesn't suddenly translate to 60%+ in the next level. Yes, you could argue that Josh Allen's supporting cast was garbage and didn't help him out, but then you'd have to make the same argument for Josh Rosen who had significantly better numbers with a poor offensive line and cast as well. He obviously has a cannon for an arm, but we've all seen that having a huge arm doesn't translate to immediate success if you aren't accurate. I could very easily be wrong here, but I just don't understand the Josh Allen hype at all.
Josh Allen is more talented than Darnold. Allen is more raw than darnold and he is a project but the Darnold is not far enough ahead to justify taking him over Allen.
A lot of people hate Allen which is understandable but I could certainly see Elway wanting this guy.
While Allen is my QB4 of this draft (him and Mayfield are very close), I feel like he is the best fit for the Bills and could potentially start Day 1.
unfortunately wont be able to wear shorts in those cold new jersey winters.
Someone had to do it

I think quarterback has to be the pick here, but it’s Allen who gets called.  Eli is still around for this year, and possibly another, which means that whoever Gettleman picks here won’t be seeing the field for awhile.  While Rosen is a more polished passer, he’s ready to step in right away. I bet, if given a year to sit behind Eli, Allen, with his top-3 arm talent, will be a better QB than Rosen.
This is a move you bet your career on but it's one I think needs to be made, Allen's raw but give him time and who knows how good he can become.

Bills panic trade up and get Allen to sit behind McCarron until he is ready to start. I think it would be better value for the Browns to recieve 2 of this years first rounds picks and a next years 1st than take Chubb here.
Ideal measurables. Teams believe NFL-level coaches/teammates can make him the best QB in the draft.
Buffalo trades picks #12, 22, 53, 56, future 3rd to Cleveland for pick #4

The most controversial selection of the draft. Nervous that a team in the early 2nd was going to trade up, the Saints give up a 4th to hop up a few spots and pick their next franchise QB who has fallen for too long. Sure it's a luxury, but Allen most likely gets 2 years of NFL coaching as the understudy to one of the greatest quarterbacks of the past few decades before he takes over a much more prepared player. A pick like this doesn't immediately help the team, but it worked out for Green Bay with Aaron Rodgers.

The Broncos are in a great position, but also a very tough one. The positional value of quarterback far outweighs running back, but this also isn't just any running back. Elway figures that Allen will have just enough time behind Keenum to develop into the star he sees him to be. I hope he's right because I wouldn't want to be the one making that decision.
Broncos have a stopgap QB in Keenum, and have time to let Allen develop. Allen is the prototypical Elway QB, too.

As much as I'm not a fan of Josh Allen, and before you stop reading, he does have the highest ceiling and is the guy i think the browns like. With Tyrod Taylor and Drew Stanton they can afford to take a slightly more developmental guy if it results in the better final result.

After trading Tyrod Taylor to Cleveland and acquiring the 12th pick from Cincinnati, Buffalo made their intentions to trade up for a QB very clear. They do just that to choose the best quarterback available in Josh Allen. *HOT TAKE ALERT* I do not like Josh Allen as a prospect *END OF HOT TAKE*. This may be because, as a Jets fan, I know what it's like to see a team overvalue a project QB with a good arm and accuracy problems (see: Christian Hackenberg). However, looking at Allen's tape, I can see why GM's love him as much as they do, not to mention the fact that he has had a great offseason (good Senior Bowl, good combine, and good pro day) and is rising up team's boards incredibly rapidly. He often produces amazing throws, and I don't know if I've ever seen a QB prospect with a better arm coming out of college. If coached correctly, Allen could truly become a superstar in the NFL.
A big draft slide for Josh Allen due to how much development he needs. Get him behind Big Ben for a couple and see what he can do

Josh Allen’s slide stops here. I could see him being taken much earlier than this or I could see him falling even past this spot. I’m beginning to really get curious about how much teams really like Allen. However, you can’t deny that the traits are there.The Cardinals could really use a franchise QB, and some say Allen’s skill set is comparable to Cam Newton (Steve Wilks was the DC in Carolina). Allen’s ceiling might be too tough for Arizona to pass on here given the need at the position. The Cardinals could spend a few seasons developing Allen behind Sam Bradford.

I have a 2nd Round grade on Allen but the positional value makes him a good pick here. McDermott coached with Cam Newton and he can install a similar kind of offense with Josh Allen built around his mobility and strong arm while limiting the exposure to his accuracy issues. Build a run first offense with big targets at WR.
Bills fans might not like it, but the NFL seems super high on Allen and his upside.

The Bills are going to trade up with somebody. The question is just who is their trade partner going to be? I can see them trading with any of the Giants, Browns, or Colts. But ultimately I think moving up to 2 would be too costly. 4/6 is the sweet spot where they wont have to sacrifce their future picks to move up and secure their qb. And while I don't like Josh Allen, you can't deny his physical abilities. And He's the perfect QB type for the conditions in Buffalo. Bills are hoping they get the next Favre with this pick.

Like Darnold earlier, my view on this QB differs from a lot of people. While Josh Allen isn't my #1 or even #2 QB in this draft I believe he has the potential to be far and away the best QB. It wouldn't shock me to see Cleveland go with him at #1 either for the same reasons i see them taking Darnold. Josh Allens tape is so divisive. Some of the throws he's able to make are just breath taking. It's like watching Aaron Rodgers and DeShone Kizer in one QB. I don't think he's Denvers first choice in this draft but i think they take him and hope to develop him behind Keenum.

Lots of Whispers about this one. It seems like draft professionals and draft fans are really split down the middle on Allen. I like Allen more than Darnold but less than Rosen. No matter what the Browns do here it's gonna lead to jokes about them. Allen really reminds me of Mahomes last season who Dorsey drafted so he takes Allen here as well.

I actually have high hopes for both Bradberry and Cockrell, now that they're back in a scheme they're more comfortable with, and who knows, maybe they'll bring back Worley now that it looks like the Eagles might cut him (I doubt it). So when I see all these mocks sending a CB to the Panthers in the first, I'm usually like, I don't think so. Not only do I think their need is less than most people think it is, but the Panthers don't have a long history of drafting corners in the first (twice in their history, the last time in 2004). But then most of those CBs being mocked to the Panthers weren't Josh Jackson. Because you have to admit, Panthers fans, that whether or not corner is your biggest need, it could still use some addressing. I just don't think you'd do it in the first unless the guy you picked was BPA. Well to me, and I expect to a lot of FOs, Jackson will be BPA here. I mentioned earlier how I think FOs are gonna be a little higher on him than we are cause he's a DB that makes plays. That's important. You hear how coaching staffs are always harping on turnovers, turnovers, turnovers. Well Jackson is probably the best defensive playmaker in the draft. He reminds me of Marcus Peters that way (except he's not a chump). He baits, he attacks the ball, he makes, ahem, educated guesses. He plays the position like a receiver. He's not the athlete Peters is, but he allayed a lot of fears that he was a bad one with his testing. And we know the Panthers have met with him. Sure, maybe they have more glaring needs at safety (though they've never drafted a safety in the first) and along the interior OL, but both of those classes are deep. After the first seven or so CBs come off the board, the dropoff is palpable.
I have a first round grade on Jackson but I just saw better fits for most teams at the end of the first round. Cleveland gets a steal here.

the Jaguars defense is laughably bad, especially at cornerback. Bouye and Ramsey are on the hot seat. Defensive line is an option as well but Jackson is the Man in the Mirror and is a Thriller whose talent is not Black or White; he is anything but Bad.

New England takes one of the top CB prospects in the draft in Josh Jackson, who saw his stock dip slightly because of a slow 40 time at the combine. Regardless, Jackson has elite ball skills after finishing 2017 with 27 passes defended and eight interceptions.

The Packers go BPA and grab a phenomenal player here in Josh Jackson. He's only played CB for one year but showed incredible poise and potential. He'll start Day 1 and provide an immediate upgrade for their DB Corps

They find a true CB1 which will help take the pressure off their defense in all kinds of ways, and Jackson is my CB1 so... foot meet shoe. Simple fix, and they've been without a true CB1 for some time now
Highest upside of any CB in the draft. Elite ball hawking ability and just like Richard Sherman, he is a converted WR. Sherman leaves a hole, Jackson fills it.
After Breelands failed offer sheet Carolina will be keen to take the former All-American who they have met with twice. I'm intrigued by Oliver's length but Jackson goes here

The Patriots let Malcolm Butler walk to Tennessee, and could seek
to improve their secondary with Jackson to go along with Gilmore and 
now Jason McCourty. Josh Jackson is a fringe prospect who some
think may be overrated due to his one great performance against OSU, 
but others see a consistent force to reckon with if you throw 
against him. The Patriots could upgrade their pass rush or linebackers, 
but I think they would be happy to see Jackson still on the board.
A better fit for Indy, who really needs to focus on their defense. It’s been awful for too long. Josh Jackson will make his presence felt.

The Cardinals would love to grab a QB in the first, but it didn’t work out for them in this scenario. It’s not all bad as they did sign Sam Bradford in the offseason, so I don’t think they need to get super desperate at this junction. There will be an intriguing QB prospect available at their 2nd-round selection. This lead me to fill Arizona’s second biggest need, cornerback. This organization has longed for a quality corner opposite Pat Pete for a while now, but they’ve never been able to find more than a short-term stopgap. I think that stops here with Josh Jackson. Steve Wilks is going to bring his zone coverage scheme from Carolina over to Arizona, and that’s the absolute perfect system for a CB with Jackson’s skillset. He’s the best pure zone corner in this class.
Josh Jackson is the top playmaking corner in the draft. (He had the most interceptions + pass deflections). He can likely start as a rookie and will play on the perimeter opposite of Kevin King.
I think Jackson is a great fit in Carolina and he's arguably BPA at 24
quits basketball to play for a team that went 0-16
I like this pick, he's a good player.

The Cardinals trade back with the Patriots to get Jackson, a turnover machine at outside cornerback and the best zone cover guy in the draft.  Jackson can lock down the other half of the field across from Peterson, freeing up Arizona’s pass rushers with blitzes and time to rush.
Not the most athletic specimen but he's the best ball hawk of this class.
Tall ball-hawk best suited for zone coverage due to stiffness
Who does Seattle have at corner these days? Shaq Griffin and maybe Byron Maxwell? They need some players to step in right away.

(Originally Jaire Alexander) The Cardinals miss out on the QB parade, but they're okay with that. They have some faith in Bradford holding them steady for a year, so they focus on building other parts of their team. Jackson is a legit ball hawk, his hands have glue and he always puts himself in the right position to make a big play. Giving PP some much needed help and a PIC is awesome. I hope this works out for them and they will most likely try to grab a QB later in the draft or next year.
Fills a need and Panthers get a top CB in the class.

The Panthers need to upgrade their defense any way possible. After Breshaud Breeland failed his physical, the Pathers are still looking for improvements in their secondary. They get just that by selecting Josh Jackson. Jackson is one of my favorite corners in this year's draft. He's incredibly exciting to watch – just look at his game against Ohio State – and will be a great pickup for any team that drafts him.
I debated WR or RB for them here as well. With the departure of Sherman and uncertainty of other DBs, they need to hop on Jackson here

The Panthers are my favorite team so I follow them the closest. Yesterday a Panthers beat writer said he feels as if Josh Jackson, DJ Moore and Justin Reid are the current favorites for the pick. I prefer Jackson in that scenario, and I have Moore off the board anyways. Jackson is an ideal fit for Carolina’s secondary, and could finally provide the team with a shut down presence that has been missing since Josh Norman left.
according to my research IND is running a zone based scheme so Jackson is a good fit
Seattle lost Sherman but they get a big, physical, ball hawk cornerback at 19 who can play outside corner from day 1

Little bit of a run of DBs here. Josh Jackson is Marcus Peters. No DB is better at playing the ball in the air then him in this draft. I have trouble envisioning anything but a CB here for the Cardinals. Maybe Ridley? I just don't see it when you can get a player like Jackson. He'll be a quick fan favorite across from Peterson.

Josh Jackson will have big shoes to fill coming in and replacing one of the best CBs of the last decade. That being said he's the best in this class at playing off the ball in the air and he should slide right in no problem in this Seattle defense.

And now we come to the coach who got the most out of Cutler the dick QB. Adam Gase might be the best coach for Rosen. As much as that whole Jim Mora thing got blown out of proportion, I think he's right about Rosen needing to be challenged. I think the same was true of Cutler. And I think Gase might like being challenged too, he's like the millennial version of a coach who's not really a millennial but he's young and hip so whatever, he might as well be. I doubt too many of you Dolphins fans will like this (and probably you Bills fans either), but no fanbase likes it when they give up a lot of draft capital to move up and take their guy, I mean, not most of them anyway. Chiefs fans were pretty pissed last year when it happened, and while your everyday Texans fan was probably a little happier given their need and Watson's name recognition, on here at least fire was shooting out of their eyes. Now, both fanbases are pretty happy about it. I have a hunch Baker is the Dolphins guy but Rosen is probably right there with him, and he's a good fit. I expect the Colts will have been looking at Barkley and Chubb, and with both of those guys gone, trading down makes sense. And I expect the Dolphins to give them the best offer. They just seem like a FO that's more willing to overpay than the Bills to me. The Cardinals might kick the tires too, but trading with the Dolphins drops the Colts down the least amount of spots, and I imagine with the next batch of guys they're considering, that's important.
2nd best QB on the board. I'm not doing trades and you gotta take a QB if you're not trading. He gets one year to learn under Eli and then the job is his

The Raiders are talented but fell apart without a keystone at the QB position. As the Eagles demonstrated, a talented backup QB is vital. Plus Rosen's the only worthy QB in the draft who played in California and, as Marshawn Lynch can attest, Oakland fans love to keep their boys home.

With Darnold off the board, the Giants take who many believe is the top QB in the draft. Rosen has poise in the pocket and the best combination of footwork and throwing mechanics of any quarterback in the draft. Rosen is the heir-apparent of Eli Manning for the G-Men.

Forget Bridges. Browns go all-in on a Win Now QB who can start Day 1 and Rosen is the man with a plan, and the power to rally the Browns to win a game. He's the best pure passer in the draft, and will be a step up over bridge-turned-backup Tyrod Taylor

Rosen and the NY market is a match made in heaven, and whether he likes it or not, he'll be Eli’s successor. With cap clearing out the yin yang, he’s poised to be the new face of the NYG with OBJ as his star receiver.

With the Browns making the offseason moves they've made so far, I doubt that the Browns will waste this chance not to draft the best QB available in the draft. Without a doubt I believe it's Josh Rosen. Ever since high school, he's been "The Man"... The biggest problem Rosen has had is his injury history. The Browns are in a great position to take advantage of this pick and minimize Rosen's problems. Have Tyrod start for most of the year, and making Rosen sit for a bit, making him go through strength and flexibility training, and then have him become a competitor later on in the season.
Leapfrogged by the Bills, they see the best passer in the draft fall to their laps. Rosen is the best passer to come out of the draft in a long, long time. He's primed for a long career.
Josh Rosen is a perfect fit for the Giants in my eyes. In my opinion, the best QB in the draft and the successor to Eli Manning.

I firmly believe that the Bills will trade up, and if they do, they will not wait around to see who falls, they woll get as high as they can to get their guy. Rosen is the most pro ready QB in the class and the Bills have the most urgent need for a QB in the league.

Buffalo did'nt stockpile picks to sit and wait for their QB at 12, With Rosen making it out of the top 5 they will be worried teams like the dolphins and cards will jump them. Bucs also get a great haul after losing a 3rd to aquire JPP

Buffalo seems determined to trade up into the top 5 for their future QB, and trading with Cleveland at 4 to jump Denver seems logical. Many believe that Josh Rosen has the highest floor and is the most polished mechanically out of the bunch, which I tend to agree with. He is a smooth, natural thrower who is used to making multiple reads. While not mobile per say, he has a good feel for the pocket around him. The risks with Rosen are his personality and concussion history, but the value of an immediate contributor at QB is too great to pass.

The Giants will keep the smokescreens going for who they will pick 
up until they are on the clock. We've heard everything from Rosen to 
Bradley Chubb, with most picks being Barkley in this spot. As much as
I love Barkley, the Giants will likely not be in this position to grab a 
franchise QB for another 5 years. Eli Manning is still a functioning QB
and he will most likely start a few games but don't be surprised to see him
shipped out before the trade deadline in favor of Rosen. Speaking of
Rosen, he is one of the most mechanically sound quarterbacks to come 
out of the draft in the past 5-10 years. His footwork and throwing motion
is nearly flawless which puts him ahead of any other QB in this draft 
class. This makes me believe he has the highest floor and he will succeed
as long as the environment is not completely ruined.

The general consensus is Buffalo trades to 4, which I can absolutely see. That would end up being Josh Rosen, and Cleveland likely goes after Connor Williams at 12. I also wouldn't be surprised if Cleveland wants to stay in the top few picks though. They're not willing to do a trade back to 12, but if Buffalo can go to 6, and then go to 4, Cleveland is more willing. We keep saying Cleveland is definitely going to want to trade with Buffalo, but they need top talent, because they're missing on a lot of later talent. Josh Rosen is the end of the QB rush, and one that Buffalo desperately needs after this offseason, but it's going to take the farm. The Bills don't miss this chance.

The Giants have a good enough roster, when healthy, to make it unlikely for them to have a chance this good to grab a QB prospect of this caliber again. At least, without having to go into a full rebuild. I’d totally understand trading down for a massive haul. I think it’s a good move, but I think having a high-end QB prospect ready to go when Eli calls it quits is the better option. This could be a Favre-Rodgers-type of transition all over again.

There's so many smokescreens regarding the Giants, that I am just keeping it simple here. If they truly don't like Rosen, and the Browns take Darnold, then they would trade back with the Bills. Josh Rosen, in my opinion, probably has the best overall arm in this class. He is a quintessential pocket passer that just feels like the perfect heir to Eli Manning. He can handle the New York media, and could be the future for the Giants. A franchise never yearns to be picking in the top five multiple times, so if you have the chance to select your quarterback of the future, you have to jump on it.
NY didn't trade up for a RB. The Jets find their signal caller of the future and the face of the franchise for years to come. Rosen is equipped to handle the bright lights of NY and their media.

The Bills give both of their firsts and probably more to move up ahead of the Broncos and select a quarterback. Rosen can likely play right away but if not, McCarron should be able to start a few games in the beginning of the season. Rosen will have ups and downs throughout his seasons but if he gets a season with more ups he could eventually lead the Bills further into the playoffs than they got with Tyrod. The Bills will need to add offensive weapons throughout the rest of this draft, may be difficult if this trade came to fruition and they had to give away both firsts and a second or third, if that is the case, Rosen could struggle as a rookie similar to Trubisky last season.
Buffalo uses a big portion of it's draft capital to trade up to #2 and get their franchise QB for the next decade (hopefully)
This choice was really between Rosen and Mayfield for me. I went with Rosen simply because he is higher on my board and is less of a risk.
The Bills pay a kings ransom to move ahead of their division rivals and take Rosen.
QB1: elite, unstoppable

The Jets traded up to 3 to grab a QB, and they end up with Rosen, who can contend to start right away on this Jets team.  Rosen is the franchise QB they missed out on in FA and haven’t had in a long time.
Having Rosen learn football while Eli plays out his career allows Rosen to iron out the few issues in his game.
Giants should either get QB or trade out, I think the Bills would have to give a fortune to get to the No.2 spot and the Giants get their QB for the next 10 years.
The top passer. Concerns about concussions/personality could make Darnold the pick
There's been talk the Giants trade down or don't pick a QB here, but as long as they stay at 2 I think they gotta grab a QB.

After seeing the Browns take Darnold and the Giants electing to not take a QB, the Jets decision became much easier. They traded up for a reason and now they get to take their guy. Rosen can come in and compete for the job with Bridgewater while also learning from a veteran in Josh McCown

This is a controversial pick, but at the end of the day, the Giants go with their guy in Rosen. He's smart, got the best accuracy and footwork, and is ready to step in day 1. The Giants don't let one of the best QB prospects in recent history go by them because they're rarely in the position they are in now.
Bills trade up and get a franchise QB in exchange for both 1sts and a future 2nd.
My favourite QB in this class falls into the jets lap, and they are extremely happy to take him and hopefully finally have their guy at the position.

(Let me preface this by saying that I don't buy into the rumor that the Giants only like Darnold with the number 2 spot and will pick a non-QB if he's not there.) This pick is the most intruiging in the entire draft. The Giants could select Saquon Barkley (an amazing talent), Quenton Nelson (another amazing talent who fills a huge hole), they could trade down with Buffalo and acquire a metric fuckton of picks, or they can select a franchise QB to succeed Eli Manning. I'm going to be honest, I have no idea what they'll do, but I think it would benefit them the most to select their quarterback of the future. They look to find just that in Josh Rosen. Rosen is my favorite quarterback in this year's draft; he is an accurate, intelligent, pro-ready quarterback who will have an immediate impact on any team that picks him. Watching his tape, I don't know why Rosen isn't the consensus number 1 pick. Rosen goes to New York and will be chosen to sit for a while until groomed into the Giants' franchise guy.
TRADE: The Bills trade #12, #22, 2019 1st, and additional picks in this years draft to move up for their future QB.

Trade details: Buffalo sends #6, #53 and a 2019 third round pick to NYG for #2. I still think Buffalo will work their way into the top 5. My guess is that they trade up again with Indianapolis, then trade from that pick to #2. The Giants probably don’t want to trade directly from #2 to #12, but they might be comfortable to settle in at #6 with Darnold off the board. If Buffalo works their way into this spot, the question becomes which QB they’ll take. Allen? Rosen? Mayfield? There are no clues regarding who they would lean towards here, but Buffalo needs someone who can come in and start right away. Allen is more of a project where Rosen is already a polished passer. Rosen would be my pick for ROTY in this scenario.

I have Rosen as the only blue chip QB prospect in this class and he would be the clear cut choice for me here. Excellent arm strength, accuracey, intelligence, and the ability to stand strong in the pocket. Plus, his upside is being undersold as he has had to play with a different offensive coordinator every year at UCLA. I have no idea why it seems like he's not being considered by the Browns in real life. I have to assume that teams are hearing really bad stuff about his personality but without being privy to that information I need to select him here.
Best pure passer in the draft goes 3rd. The Jets get a steal and ignore the "mindset" questions that keep popping up about Rosen

Josh Rosen is the best QB in this draft. If not Rosen its gotta be Darnold. Otherwise the Browns are making a mistake. QB is the only option here, so this is an easy one. Hue Jackson does like those big armed qbs, but remember he also prefered Goff over Wentz. Plus Hue was always a huge Palmer fan. This is the type of QB Hue Jackson wants.

This pick is so valuable that there's no good reason for the Giants not to trade it. They're clearly in win now mode and trading this pick would allow them to still get a very good player this season while also setting themselves up for a rich future draft. If they do decide to stay then there's no doubt it will be for a QB. Rosen is my #1 QB in this draft and I think he's significantly better than anyone left. Bills fans should hope they can pry this pick from The Giants.

I originally didn't have Denver taking a QB with this pick when i started doing this mock. Josh Rosen is just too good to pass on though. Not only do they take him I would bet he replaces Keenum by the half way point. Josh Rosen could take this Denver team to special places and quickly.

Remember when I said in the intro to this thing how most fanbases were gonna like half their picks and hate half their picks? That's how most of us feel after the draft (until we talk ourselves into all of them) and I'm thinking by the end of this thing, the Cowboys are gonna be the example I use. I may even go back and amend it. The reason everyone was so surprised when the Cowboys took Taco Charlton last year was that he wasn't a fit as a RDE in their system. That position had traditionally been manned by a smaller, speedier guy; Charlton, at 6'6 275 pounds, was anything but. There was the thought that maybe they'd changed the way they do things by playing Jack Crawford at RDE some in 2016, but I'm thinking they may want to take a mulligan (not necessarily on the Charlton pick, but on the style). You can never have enough guys who get pressure, and outside of Lawrence, Dallas doesn't have enough of them. Now though the Cowboys don't have a traditional RDE on their roster and though we don't know how the Lawrence saga is gonna play out long term, they're pretty deep at end (and not so deep at ILB, OT/OG, DT, etc...). So I'm sure you Cowboys fans just like the fans of every team who's picked since Price went want me to plug Ragnow in here. (Edit or now that Dez is gone, a receiver) And you guys actually have a legitimate argument. Ragnow and Jerry are Razorback bros, and Jerry's shown no hesitation in drafting an interior lineman high (to great success too, I might add). In fact I thought it made so much sense, I put it in, then I started writing this explanation, then I started having second thoughts. I don't know, maybe I rate Cameron Fleming more so than you guys, but I actually think he's pretty good. And he'll allow Collins to flex back to guard where he should be playing anyway. And that right there is the best offensive line in the league. Now I'll give you, your depth is bad, and it was that bad depth that ruined your season last year, and if you guys were maybe one player away, maybe addressing that depth in the second round would make sense. But you're not one player away, you're like four players away (which is still much closer than most), and in a draft that's deep in linemen, I can't in good conscious believe Jerry won't be talked out of Ragnow by his people for a higher profile, harder

Pats Find a physical freak to rotate in on their Pass Rush with Josh Sweat, who saw his value skyrocket form a downtrending threat to a monster thanks to the Combine. He'll make Bill smile... maybe. That seems generally impossible.

Browns find a physical freak to rotate in on their Pass Rush with Josh Sweat, who saw his value skyrocket form a downtrending threat to a monster thanks to the Combine. He'll make Williams a happy coordinator.

Make no mistake, Josh Sweat is a freak athlete. He blew up the combine and looks the part of the ideal pass rusher. However, after suffering from a freak injury his Senior year of High School, I still worry about his capabilities going forward. He doesn't exhibit much bend on film, and instead tries to win with strength. It's still a long road back to gaining back his confidence in his knee, but if he does then watch out. San Francisco lacks a true LEO pass rusher, and Sweat has the athleticism to pull it off. He is also an immediate contributor agaisnt the run, as well an excellent edge setter.

Tennessee is a good fit for Sweat, because they can afford to wait on his play to match his raw talent. With Brian Orakpo and Derrick Morgan currently starting, Sweat can work as the third pass rusher in 2018 and move into a starting role in 2019. Head coach Mike Vrabel specializes in LB’s, so he’s a good as candidate as any to develop Sweat.

Brian Orakpo is on the wrong side of 30 and can't be trusted to stay healthy throughout a season. If not for Sweat's gruesome leg injury he would have been a consensus first round pick. As it goes, everyone else's fears is the Titans gain.
Haha he will make the opposing OL sweat
With the Panthers DL getting older they need to add an explosive pass rusher, while Sweat is very raw, he is a crazy athlete and adds some great speed rush potential.

Make no mistake, Josh Sweat is a freak athlete. He blew up the combine and looks the part of the ideal pass rusher. However, after suffering from a freak injury his Senior year of High School, I still worry about his capabilities going forward. He doesn't exhibit much bend on film, and instead tries to win with strength. It's still a long road back to gaining back his confidence in his knee, but if he does then watch out. San Francisco lacks a true LEO pass rusher, and Sweat has the athleticism to pull it off. He is also an immediate contributor agaisnt the run, as well an excellent edge setter.
Josh Sweat had a strong enough combine for someone in the 2nd round to pull the trigger and with a need at edge the Panthers are the team that does.

Panthers need a real cornerback here, and Josh Jackson is a great pick. I imagine a lot of people will wonder why I have Jackson all the way down here at 24. Josh Jackson is a real ball-hawk with rare size at the position. Even on defense, he sometimes looks like a better wide receiver than whoever he's going against. There's been a noticeable hole in the secondary ever since Norman left, but that can easily be filled by Jackson.

The Chargers have built a solid front seven, but their secondary still has some holes. Jackson has a very high ceiling and his coverage is clean. Jackson may not be ideal to start immediately, but he has a very bright future.

Best case scenario pick here for Carolina; top zone coverage CB falls to one of the most zone-heavy teams in the league. Josh Jackson exploded onto the scene with a huge season for Iowa, racking up multiple picks and key pass-defenses. He is excellent in zone coverage, a scheme that allows him to utilize his skills of reading the play and making breaks on the ball to creat turnovers. Bradberry took a step back this season, and the Bashaud Breeland signing fell through due to a failed physical, so adding CB talent is an absolute must for Carolina.

The Panther must address wide receiver and safety at some point in the draft. They would do well to address edge rusher as well since Julius Peppers will eventually retire. Joshua Jackson is a nice value pick adding to an otherwise uninspiring group of James Bradberry, Kevon Seymour, and Captain Munnerlyn among others.

First slightly controversial pick, Jackson is a great scheme fit and corners that get turnovers are worth alot. Him and Sherman would be a deadly duo in the secondary and he can learn from one of the best.

The Legion of Boom is crumbling and in need of an injection of fresh young talent. Jackson brings to the table the best ball skills in the entire draft class and an impressive resume from Iowa. Though there were some concerns at the combine when he struggled in DB drills Pete Carroll's defense is flexible enough to put Jackson in position to win early while he cleans up his technique.

The Panthers have had a hole at corner back ever since Josh Norman left, so they snap up the chance to take Josh Jackson who falls due to only being very strong in zone coverage, not being quick enough for man.

I know Dolphins fans consider the DT position to be a team weakness, but I actually think they've got a little something cooking. I thought Godchaux had a great rookie season and Vincent Taylor flashed too. Phillips has been so so overall, I admit, but he did improve quite a bit in 2017 and I think his best is still to come. But they are thin and inexperienced and it would do them some good to add another body to the mix. Enter Justin Jones, who I think is one of the underrated gems of the class, and the only reason he's available this late, IMO, is that he doesn't wow you with any one thing. His hands are active and strong but not vicious, his technique is sound but not stellar, he gets good leverage and plays with a strong base most of the time, his spin move is solid when he's rushing the passer, but not elite. He's just a solid player in every aspect, and that's an underrated trait in a fourth rounder, to find a floor as high as Jones's. He also plays with a high motor and is willing to do the dirty work for his teammates, namely against double teams, which he has a knack for splitting. Those are the kinds of guys you need on your team, if you want it to be a winning team.

This is one of those where, when they announce the trade, the media machine is gonna barf out a quick narrative about how the Redskins traded up for their guy, foregone conclusion Payne this, Payne that, and then shocker! It happens all the time, but the best example was when the Dolphins hopped into the top 5 back in 2013 and the cognoscenti started running video of Lane Johnson and he’s the pick and he has to be, and then he wasn’t, it was Dion Jordan (it turns out the Dolphins should have listened to the cognoscenti). Washington needs a DT to stuff the run, and if you’re drafting Payne to stuff the run, you’re not drafting him for the right reasons. That was his role with Alabama for most of the season, and for most of the season, he looked like a mid rounder. It wasn’t until Saban cut him loose in the playoffs that we got an idea what he could really do, but that's not the guy the Redskins need. They’ve got that guy, a few of them,  starting with Payne’s former teammate Jonathan Allen. So the move up’s not for Payne, it’s for draft darling Justin Reid. The Redskins added third and fifth round picks from their trade haul with the Chargers in the first round, so they don't mind giving up their fourth to move up seven spots to grab one of the draft's surprise fallers. I think going into the draft their plan was probably to snag a RB in the first two rounds, but you have to adjust to the board as it falls, and it fell kinda weird for them. Guice went before they thought he would in the first, Reid falls further than they thought he would in the second. So they go up and grab him. It makes the loss of Derwin James and the decision to pass on Minkah more palatable. From the Colts perspective, they recoup a pick they used to go up and get Maurice Hurst. Now I know some of you Redskins fans are gonna be hammering me for coming out of the first two rounds with a DE and S and no DT, RB or interior lineman, but my belief is when elite talent's available, you take it, especially when it's at a position that's not stacked. It's why they (and you) were so willing to grab Minkah or James in the first. They stood out above the talent around them, and I think the same's true of Reid in the second. And there's always the two third round picks coming up.
Tre Boston hasn't signed anywhere yet but it doesn't look like he will return to LA leaving the Chargers with a hole at safety. Justin Reid is a phenomenal athlete who can start on day one
Keanu Neal had a low ceiling as a prospect and unfortunately the Falcons need to target the safety position again in 2018. Reid can read the offense while Neal kneels on the sideline.

Opting to stay put rather than trade down, the reigning Super Bowl champions take Justin Reid, the best safety prospect available. Reid will add depth for the safety position and eventually replace Corey Graham, who will be 33 when the season starts and is a free agent following 2018.

An athletic freak, Justin Reid will immediately help end the Safety woes the Panthers have had, and make their whole Secondary more dangerous. He can slot in at FS or SS depending on what they need as well

An athletic freak, Justin Reid will immediately help end the Safety woes the Panthers have had, and make their whole Secondary more dangerous. He can slot in at FS or SS depending on what they need as well
Panthers need a lot of help in the secondary, and Reid is the BPA at the position with Ward coming off of the board.

Without a worthwhile LB on the board, the Steelers could look to adding a true free safety for their secondary, something they've lacked for some time. Morgan Burnett was an excellent addition that slots in right at SS, but Sean Davis is more of a versatile piece than a true FS. Justin Reid has amazing athleticism and excellent range to fit right in up top. He is aggressive in both tackling and coverage, which allows him to create many turnover chances. His short-range acceleration is his best trait, and that's something Pittsburgh lacks in the secondary.

T.J. Ward played one year for the Bucs as a stopgap option at SS, but they’re looking for a long-term starter now. Reid has the potential to grow into one of the most complete safeties in the league. He’s athletic enough to cover, while still being willing to get rough and make plays in the box. Reid also has the football IQ to be a leader on the field if required.

After trading away Brandin Cooks, the Pats land one spot ahead of Reid’s other potential suitor in Carolina. Reid is a classic Patriots player, smart, versatile and consistent. Can be used at safety or to cover the slot. Has potential to grow and get better every year.

With the top linebackers on the board gone, the Steelers decide to address Mike Mitchell's departure. Sean Reid and Morgan Burnett are solid, but Justin Reid could add a playmaking quality to that secondary.
The Steelers FS woes are over with the best FS in the class.
To finish out round one the Eagles solidify their secondary. Reid has his flaws, but overall, he is a solid, well-rounded player.
Related to Eric Reid but not Ed Reed

The other first round selection for the Browns from the Bills trade, the Browns select Reid, the rangy safety who can start at multiple positions.  He’s already a more polished safety than Peppers I’d argue, and an upgrade over Damarious Randall as well.
While releasing Tyrann Mathieu who mainly played in the slot leaves a hole there. Reid would be a steal here and I see him falling because hes more of a slot corner than a traditional FS.
The Steelers have two main needs, ILB and FS. Reid has been rising recently and it is looking like he will end up going in the late first round.

I like to call Justin Reid a "chameleon player." He can line up deep or close to the LOS, play man or zone coverage, and is reliable in the run game. This scheme versatility makes Reid one of the safest prospects in this draft class and a great fit to an already solid roster in Pittsburgh.
The Steelers have a big need at safety and Reid is one of those guys whose fastly becoming seen as a first round prospect.
This is a good, safe pick here for Pittsburgh. Reid can start immediately and place good enough to hold the spot. His instincts alone will keep him on the field with tons of room to improve.
This is a safe pick for Carolina. Reid is a fantastic athlete with great instincts for the position. He should be able to make a big impact right away on the Carolina defense.

You don't find a lot of athletes like Turay in the late third round. Of course, the first thing you gotta ask yourself then, is what gives? Well I'll tell you what gives despite his freaky athleticism, Turay didn't produce. It's the classic story of the third rounder, the guy with all the gifts and none of the output (not to be confused with the story of another kind of third rounder, the guy with all of the output and none of the gifts). I've talked to a couple of Rutgers fans who are genuinely angry with Turay. They can't fathom how a guy like that

Turay is a pass rush specialist. He is a little inconsistent which let him fall to the third round but he has all the tools. Like a lot of guys at this point in the draft he needs to be coached up to his potential

Carolina needs to find a long term solution at EDGE that doesn't involve convincing Peppers not to retire. Turay is a beast and his personal pro day numbers proved that he's got the athleticism to match his tape. Great value here.

I love this fit for both the player and team. Green Bay isn’t looking for an immediate impact edge rusher, but they are in major need of a developmental guy behind Clay Matthews. Turay has a ton of upside, and he gets the benefit of playing with quality vets and working with a great defensive mind in Mike Pettine.
Super raw player. Pure athlete with good bend. High upside pick
Norton fills a NT need for the Cowboys, would start day 1.

Oh, this one breaks my heart Giants fans. I was so hoping he'd fall to the Lions pick in the third. It's literally hard for me to write this. Kerryon's my #1 draft crush, he's the guy I think we'll be looking back on and wondering 'man, why didn't he go higher?' Well, a few reasons. His injury history plays a part, for sure, and his long speed's not the greatest, but what he does well he does as well as anyone in the draft. I think he's the best goal line back you can get. He's not built like the best goal line back (though he's not a small guy, either), he just has that knack for finding the end zone. The way Marcus Allen did back in the day, or Tomlinson or Charles more recently. You don't have to be the biggest guy in the world to slither through creases and understand the most likely ways to fall forward a yard. It's an intuitive thing, and I think Johnson has it. I also think he's one of the best pass catching backs in the draft, and we all know how the league wants their back to catch passes now. And just look at his production in the SEC. He was going against NFL talent week in and week out and succeeding enough that he was named offensive player of the year. Don't tell me doesn't have what it takes for the pros, that's ridiculous. He literally passed the best test a RB can get from the college ranks with flying colors. And it's gonna keep happening. Congrats Giants fans, you've crushed me. I'm sure some of you might prefer Nick Chubb, and all I can say to those of you thinking that way is, you're wrong. I mean, probably. Maybe. I do think NFL FOs are higher on Kerryon than most of us are, you can see it when you look at the ratings of former scouts. Which is why, alas, I can't see him falling to our pick.

It seems like it has been a long time since the Giants had a strong RB. Johnson has drawn comparisons ranging from Tevin Coleman to Jordan Howard to Le'Veon Bell. He is supremely talented but he has durability concerns
Patient runner like Le'Veon Bell, not as high as him as the selection implies, but I think he fits the Colts system more than other RBs in this range.

I’d be tired of giving Ameer Abdullah chances if I was Detroit. At this point, Kerryon Johnson is more intriguing. He has a better chance of becoming a feature back than Abdullah, and I like this value for him.
He's good but I have major health concerns for him
Johnson would make a good team with McCoy and coulv eventually take the No1 role over.

Toliver's gonna go higher than you think. He's got that LSU CB pedigree, and while his time at Baton Rouge wasn't as successful as evaluators would have liked, he did show some improvement in 2017, and he's got the freaky size and athleticism teams can't get enough of. If his play ever matches his talent, watch out! He's no nickel back, but Fuller can shift inside easy enough while this tree lines up outside. And the Chiefs gotta get somebody else for the outside, they just gotta. Otherwise it's Amerson and Keith Reaser and (shudder) Steve Nelson lining up next to Fuller, and that's a recipe for a lot of shootouts. Gonna have to grab Mahomie in fantasy this year, I think. Toliver falls mostly because of his up and down play, but also because he's a bit of a punk, apparently. But if NFL teams avoided 20 23 year old punks, they wouldn't be able to fill out their rosters. Guys mature. And if he is a punk, I like the chances of the guys on your D straightening him out and getting him to channel that punkitude into usefulness. Harness it, don't squelch it. Some of the best players in the league came into it as punks, and KC's never been afraid of them (sometimes it works out, sometimes it doesn't).
Toliver is a big lanky corner that teams covet but his tape is somewhat lacking. He needs a year or two to develop but he has all the tools to be a starting corner in the league
Bills

I expect Colts fans would have liked to address the OL before now, and I tried a couple of times, truly, the board just didn't fall the right way. Still, given how high I've seen Miller going in some of these mocks recently, this has to feel like a pretty good get at this point. I wouldn't be shocked if, by the end of the draft, the Colts have added two more offensive linemen, they have to keep Andrew Luck healthy. There's still great value left in the interior, but the tackle spot is starting to thin out a little bit, and Miller represents one of the last guys you might be able to plug in this year. I'm actually a little higher on some of the other guys' upside but there's no doubt Miller has the higher floor, and if he has a career like Solder, the guy he's most often compared with, I think the Colts would be pretty damn happy about it. And I don't think there's that much difference anymore between left and right tackles, either. So drafting Miller to plug in on the right is no problem, or if it is you just flip them. It's about getting the two best guys on the field.
The Vikings spent big bucks to bring in Kirk Cousins. Now they need to protect him. Miller is probably the best rated OT on the board.

Controversial prospect, yes, but Houston needs a stud and he definitely has that potential. Their OL must improve to protect Watson and open up holes for D'onta Foreman. Miller has some skills which may work Day 1, but his long term potential is where he can shine

Kolton Miller is a good OT to the Jaguars here. Cam Robinson has shown his ability to play LT and they can keep him there. But perhaps Millers athleticism will allow him to play LT as well. The nice thing about this pick is that between Robinson and Miller, their skillsets are translatable to both right and left tackle.
As I mentioned before, the Jaguars do not have a lot of needs. They can afford to take a high-upside, athletically gifted OT like Kolton Miller in the last second round.

I do not believe in drafting o-linemen based purely off physical potential, but given the Eagles stacked roster and veteran presence at O-line, this is a tactical pick for the defending champs. Miller can sit for a season behind Peters and improve his technique

The Patriots have brought this guy in for a private visit and with Guice, Davenport, Oliver, off the board, along with Williams and McGlinchey I think they make sure they get a guy they're eyeing before chancing it to 11.

Trade details: OAK trades picks #41, 110, and 159 | PHI trades pick #32 The Raiders had a need at RT, even with Marshall Newhouse, so losing him means they literally have no one you could comfortably project for a starting role. That ends with Kolton Miller. Miller needs to add a little more weight to his frame to play RT in a man blocking scheme, but all that comes down to is coaching. If Miller develops nicely, there’s even a chance he’s the long-term answer to Donald Penn at LT, which would feel two needs with one guy for the Raiders. Giving up to day 3 picks is worth it to grab a player with Miller’s upside.

Losing Nate Solder and Cameron Fleming means that the Pats have to fill a hole at LT. Miller is basically Nate Solder lite, and was impressive in his athleticism at the combine. He will have some growing pains, especially if he doesn’t get any stronger.
Miller is a bit of a project but is uber athletic and has a ton of potential.
another mammoth, needs some work
No
The other pick from the Patriots trade, the 49ers get the last first-round worthy tackle, the athletic Miller who can play both tackle positions very athletically.
With no LB being worth it here I think the Eagle go for a developmental LT to replace Jason Peters when needed.

Miller has started to rise because of his fantastic showing at the combine. His tape is not great and he needs a ton of work, but he wouldn't have to start right away and would have some time to learn and improve.

Miller's has outstanding length and great balance/movement for a guy of his height, he'll be a reliable addition to any line he goes to. However, I am now aware that OG is actually the Jags biggest need on the offensive line despite adding Norwell in FA. Chalk this up as me being misinformed; just pretend that y'all grabbed Isaiah Wynn here and move along.
The giants take this chance to further strengthen their offensive line which was absolutely terrible last year
Hunting on the Nate Solder replacement. Garcia was drafted last year but who knows about his health

This is probably a pick that a lot will not like. But the Colts need OT's, and Kolton Miller has an incredibly high upside. This is a really risky pick, but with Lucks recent injuries, they absolutely need to address the OL early in this draft. Theres a lot of smoke that Kolton Miller could be the first OT off the board, so the Colts gettin him 3rd here isn't too bad. This is why the Colts need to trade down. They added the best Pass rusher in the draft and a top OT to protect their Franchise QB, and still have four 2nd rounders to go.
Is Kolton Miller the "Josh Allen" of OTs? Maybe. He's mostly size at this point and will probably be overdrafted because of it. If there's anyone i trust to help him succeed it's NE.

OK, maybe this is cheating a little to get Lauletta to Denver in a spot where I can talk about it. I do expect him to come off the board really soon, and I expect Denver will have to trade up to get him, and I think they will. That said, if Tennessee was offered this trade, I very much think they'd take it, it works out quite a bit in their favor, but you know what they say, you have to pay a premium to move up for a QB. I think the Broncos really like Lauletta. I think they like him (and Falk) enough to pass on QB with their first round pick in hopes they can get him, though I doubt they like him enough to draft him before this. QBs, once we move past the first grouping of them, tend to go a little later than we think. Remember all the mocks that had Brad Kaaya going in the 2 4th last year? He lasted until the very end of the sixth. We were all sure Vernon Adams was the next Russ, he went undrafted. Tyler Bray went undrafted. Lots of people posited that Josh Dobbs would be the best QB in last year's class and had him going in the second. He went around here, towards the end of the fourth. Dak went around here. It's a hot spot for QBs. I think Lauletta's lack of arm strength is gonna cap his draft position, it's a legit worry for any team drafting him. He's got the intangibles we all love he's kind of the anti Rosen, actually

You can never take Flacco's SB win away from him but he hasn't lived up to his contract since then. If he doens't improve the Ravens could cut him after the 2019 season and put in Lauletta who has soared up the draft boards after an excellent senior bowl week. He needs a couple years of development anyway.

Bill is gonna need a QB with a longer contract to avoid the whole Jimmy G issue, so he's going to get his guy at the tail end of the 1st to lock it in. Lauletta just feels like a Pats pick and he would be much more talked about if he put up those numbers and had that tape, he'd be in the first almost guaranteed.
Originally one of my late-round loves, he's found himself at pick 15 and no one can believe it. Sam Bradford is a walking sicknote and Lauletta is a nice insurance policy.

This is a token pick, but sometimes picks become token picks due to making a ton of sense. That’s the case here for me. The Patriots absolutely need to find a developmental QB behind Tom Brady, and Kyle Lauletta has intriguing upside. He’s really not all that different from Jimmy G when he entered the draft.

I think Lauletta vaults over Mason Rudolph and enters 1st round consideration here. The reason is really three simple words; 5th year option. The Giants can have Webb and Lauletta battle it out for QB of the future. One of them will eventually shake out, especially under Shurmer's tutelage (the man made Case Keenum look good).
Panthers were tough to pick for here. I went with the very talented Lauletta who will provide some QB competition for Bortles and Kessler.
I love Lauletta here, and he's a great fit for NE
Patriots get their future QB once Brady retires in 5-10 years time.

White's a guy who was talked about as a borderline first round pick early in the process, but his inability to go through all the testing has him slipping a little, much to Cincy's benefit. This is the kind of hard hitting safety every fanbase loves, he flies around with little regard for his own well being and hits and hits and hits. It's no surprise then that he's better in the box, and in fact some think he's well on his way to transitioning into that hybrid role that's become all the rage, safety some of the time, linebacker some of the time, blankets tight ends and running backs, really quick at recognizing play action. He's a great blitzer too, I'm worried he's gonna kill a QB one day. He lets 'em know he's been there, sheesh. I suppose that means he might also get some roughing the passer penalties, but that's the sort of risk you run when you attack the QB the way he does. He was West Virginia's captain too, and I would have high hopes, if I were you Bengals fans, of your new defensive coordinator Teryl Austin turning him into something. The guy does really good work with DBs.
Bengals need some safety help, and the versatility of White shown in College shows that he can make an incredible impact in the NFL. The spur safety role should translate well in the Bengals defense
White has very good size and would add good competition and depth. He has good playmaking skills and could become a very nice defensive weapon.

My hunch is the Cardinals would prefer to make this trade with the Colts, but I think the Colts would ask for the moon to trade down yet again. As it is the Cardinals first and second round picks are already an overpay, they don't want to give any more than that. So they buzz Gruden & Co. to assess their willingness to trade down, and find themselves pleasantly surprised by their response. Because if you look at the Raiders most glaring needs OT, DT, MLB, maybe a WR (unless they sign Dez, don't rule it out)... those can all be had further down the board. In fact most of them would be a reach here. I have a hunch Gruden would love a guy like Vea, but Vea's off the board, so there's not as much reason to stick around. Minkah will give them pause, especially since Alabama's former DB coach now has the same position with the Raiders, but I can't imagine them having much problem adding a second round pick to drop down five spots. As for the pick, so here's the thing about Jackson 75% of the league may have him as a guy they wouldn't touch until late, or even someone that should switch positions. But we've all heard it said there only has to be one team that believes in his ability to take him, and my hunch is there'll be more than one team. You can see it in the sub. For every ten people who trash Jackson's game, there's two or three who defend him. I think roughly the same ratio will play out league wide. Because if Jackson can put it all together, he could absolutely set the league on fire, I don't think anyone's really debating that. The debate rages on whether or not he'll actually put it all together. But remember last year, with Watson and Mahomes? We didn't think they'd go this high, but they did, and right around here too. My hunch is Arizona and Wilks especially like what they see in Jackson. He comes from Carolina, where Cam and the Panthers success was based more on what he could do physically than his pinpoint passing. I know, I know, Cardinals offensive coordinator Mike McCoy likes his QBs big, stationary, and prototypical, but I think that actually works in favor of this pick. In Arizona, he's guaranteed to be able to sit, if not behind the oft injured Bradford then behind Glennon. In that time, he can go to McCoy prototypical QB school and iron out some of his kinks while McCoy plays around with Bradford and Glennon. I do think he could set the league on fire if they played him, but at the cost of his development. He can still set the league on fire in a couple of years.

I know people love to mock the Bills trading up to 4 but that's too complicated for me. As this stands the Bills didn't trade up to not take a QB. Jackson should be a better version of Taylor so this is a good fit

The 49ers don't have many holes on their roster except QB. The draft board falls perfectly for them as Jackson is an immediate improvement in all facets of the game, particularly with his innate ability to throw darts into narrow windows. Jackson will also instill confidence in 49ers fans based on his winning record, unlike other quarterbacks on the roster.

Arizona trades up with San Francisco to grab Lamar Jackson, who besides Josh Allen, is the most controversial QB prospect in this draft. Jackson has elite athleticism and a strong arm, and with Sam Bradford now in Arizona on a one year deal, Jackson can sit for a season and develop before taking over for the Cardinals

Buffalo sees a QB dropping, and they bust a last minute deal to get him. Lamar Jackson gets a lot of shit because he's handled himself less-than-ideally during this offseason with lack of true representation and poor reports coming from the Combine, but I feel like has has the tools to become an EXCELLENT passer and a very good runner. He comes to Buffalo here, and they keep their future and later picks

Trade details: BUF trades picks #12 and 56 | CHI trades pick #8 The Bills give up a little more than chart value to get up here, because there are several teams interested in acquiring this pick. However, Buffalo can easily outbid them by overpaying a bit due to their excess of draft picks. They still have another first, one second, and two thirds after this move, so they aren’t hurting their chances of filling other holes by making this trade, like other teams would be. Moving on to Lamar Jackson, he’s fairly unrefined, but that’s more so in a mental capacity than in a physical one. He already improved significantly as a passer this past season at Louisville. For that reason, I think it’s fair to say an NFL team can get even more out of him. At least, enough to where they can build a successful offense that suits his skill set. The area Jackson has the most work to do in is the mental aspects of reading defenses. Due to not making pro-level reads in college, Jackson isn’t a guy I’d feel comfortable starting right away, but the Bills have already signed their contingency plan in A.J. McCarron. They’re in a great position to groom the potential star QB.

Call it a hunch, but I think Quinn and Patricia are pretty high on Carter. We've met with him twice, and he brings the kind of versatility they're gonna look for in a front seven guy. With Carter you don't have to worry about him dropping into coverage (the way you would, say, Landry), he did it a lot at Georgia, he has a lot of experience doing linebackery things. And he's strong as an ox for his frame, he'll have no problem setting the edge. He just doesn't put up the flashy sack numbers, but he didn't have nearly as much opportunity as some of the other edge guys, either. Maybe there's room for growth? He's certainly got the freaky athleticism for it. He could even flex inside now and again as a Tremaine Edmunds style ILB. I think he's a defensive weapon, a matchup nightmare, and I think he's just the sort of guy Quinn and Patricia are looking for. Now I expect some of my fellow Lions fans will be pretty peeved about me passing on Payne, but I think he's in for something of an A'Shawn Robinson style draft day tumble. We're one of the teams that could end it (I think he fits better with us than most), and I think we might have, had Carter not been available. But I also think Quinn and Patricia like our DTs better than we do. I know that's borderline sacrilege, but it's the way I see it. Patricia squeezed more out of less in New England than he had any right to, and while I don't think we intend to go exactly that route, I think they believe in themselves to find guys later on that will work. Guys like the guys we have now. I don't think they'd keep us from upgrading if the right guy was around Vea, for example

Sidebar Here's reason #767 why I think Belichick's a genius I think he uses the bargains he can get with young/rookie defensive linemen the same way other teams use the bargains they can get with a rookie QB. I'll explain. What are the NFL's highest paid positions? QB, obviously, then I'd say DE, LT and CB, on the whole. There are outliers at other positions, but for the most part if you have good players at QB, DE, LT and CB, you're paying them a lot. Unless they're on rookie contracts. So I'm sure you've all noticed how the Rams have been able to stack their roster during the offseason, just like the Eagles stacked theirs too. They can only do that cause their QBs are on rookie contracts. That's shit's like NFL gold. But, and here's the dilemma, once Goff and Wentz get paid, the Rams and Eagles are gonna have to start cutting guys left and right. As an obvious example, look at what's happened to the Seahawks. You remember how loaded their roster was during their Super Bowl run and shortly thereafter. Wilson was making peanuts, so they could afford to bring in FAs like Avril and Bennett and Chris Clemons and Red Bryant and pay Lynch and Baldwin and Chancellor and Wright and Sherman. Until Wilson's rookie contract was up and they had to pay him instead. Now look what's happening to them. That same fate will befall the Rams and Eagles soon enough. There's no avoiding paying a QB once you get a good one. But what if you could find a bargain somewhere else? OK, so the Patriots have to pay Brady, there's no way around it. But what if they chinced at DE? It wouldn't give them the same kind of savings they'd get at QB, but it would still be a lot. So how would you go about doing it? Well, just like at QB, you get guys on rookie contracts, they're the best bargains in the league. And you hope they play their asses off. Then, if they become one of the best DEs in the league, instead of signing them to a long contract the way you'd have to sign a QB, you ship them off for good draft picks and start the process over again. Or, see Chandler Jones (and to a lesser extent Jamie Collins, who was more of a LB with edge qualities). It's a much more repeatable thing at DE, because you can afford to throw so many more numbers at it. Take this draft alone, here I have them drafting Ejiofor after already drafting Sweat. You'd never draft two QBs at the same spots, for a whole buncha reasons, one of the main ones being they couldn't both see the field. As for the other expensive positions, Belichick has clearly decided CB has more value as he's willing to pay those, but he tends to keep it manageable at LT too. So there's your value. It's not a QB on a rookie contract. It's DE's on rookie contracts (or vets on reasonable ones), and a LT on a rookie/reasonable contract. That's why the turnover is so great on the NE D Line. He can't get out from under paying Brady, so he finds some other way to do it. Sorry for the digression, I just wanted to get that off my chest. In an earlier version of this thing I had the Pats nabbing a DE and wrote that then, when it would have made much more sense, but I liked it and wanted to share it, so I crammed it in here. Anyway, everyone's all hung up on how Lauletta's a Pats style QB (he even played lacrosse!), or how Belichick loves Mike White (warning, if you hear Belichick loves someone before the draft, do not believe it) and Mason Rudolph. When I hear all that stuff, my inclination is to think 'OK, who's the guy we're *not hearing about?' To me, that guy is much more likely to be Belichick's target. And this year, that guy is Luke Falk. So you have to ask yourself then, does Falk seem like the kind of guy the Patriots would like? Let's see... accurate, smart, quick release, stands tall and has good feel in the pocket, uses his eyes well to manipulate DBs, good timing on throws, above average arm strength... It's like he was crafted for Belichick in a lab, I don't understand why it's not coming up more often. If you were drafting Falk after his sophomore year, you'd call this a steal than you'd cuss the Patriots for catching all the breaks. Of course that's not how it works, and Falk's work since then leaves a lot to be desired (he even got benched in 2017). The biggest concern is he got so beat up in that janky offense and behind that subpar offensive line that he's got happy feet, that his poise suffered, that he's a real injury risk. It's as if we're evaluating two different guys, and fair enough, those are legitimate concerns. But Belichick's the kinda guy who's gonna see past that, to the guy who looked very poised in the past and know that he can get that guy back, cause he can address the issues that caused the latest version of Falk to appear in the first place. But mostly, and here's this word again, he's gonna see in Falk great value. The kind of guy you wouldn't be able to grab in the fourth if it weren't for extenuating circumstances. And that makes him a Pats kind of pick, current narrative be damned.

Might be a small reach in the third round but the Pats don't pick again until the 6th round and I expect the QB pickings to be slim at that point. I'm on record as not being the biggest fan of Jefferson's game, but I can admit he did improve drastically this year under Tom Herman. He looked like he was on his way to bustville until Herman showed up and shifted Jefferson's responsibilities away from the middle and more towards the outside, where he could simply attack rather than think. If it's a sign of things to come this could be a real steal. He's got everything you want athletically from a LB, and with Thomas Davis's pending supension and retirement, Carolina has a hole opening up in their corps. Whether they simply plug Jefferson into Davis's spot on the weak side (what I would recommend) or shift Thompson to the weak side and play Jefferson on the strong side, the Panthers will have to be patient. But keep his responsibilities to a minimum and let him attack and you might get more out of him sooner than you think. He's also some sort of saint off the field, working with kids and foundations and charities and ingratiating himself into whatever community he calls home. Panthers fans will love him, at least until he misses his third or fourth assignment. But he's worth the risk at this point.

He is incredibly athletic and has the size and strength to match. When he gets going, he can take over games and shut down the run both inside and out. His instincts, however, are sorely lacking. I do think a lot of it is coachable, and the Steelers have good ILB coaching. He was still highly productive at Texas and was a key playmaker at many big moments.

The whole world is sleeping on Marcell Frazier. Here's a guy, battled through a quadriceps injury this season, but recovered enough towards the end of the year to post 5.5 sacks in his last seven games. Still, we're all like 'below average athlete who uses his smarts, good technique and a plus motor to create pressure'. OK, we might not all have been like that, but a lot of people were, that's ripped straight from a scouting report. He contended that he still wasn't 100%, but he didn't get an invite to the combine. So his pro day rolls around and he rips off a 4.6 forty at 6'5, 256 pounds. 34 inch vert. Faster 3 cone than Davenport, Key, Armstrong and Chubb. OK, so maybe he's not a below average athlete, maybe he really was hurt, then what? Then you've got a potential star on your hands. Cause if he's not just a try

The idea when they traded down was to recoup the third rounder, add a fifth rounder, and nab one of James, Davenport, Jackson or Guice (who I think they really, really love, and wouldn't be shocked if they took him at 13). One of them would still be available, and it just so happens there's two. And I know, I know Redskins fans, you want me to include Roquan Smith in that list, but I can't. He's too similar to Zach Brown, he's still a small, chase linebacker who struggles to get off blocks, drafting a guy like that this high just isn't in most GMs DNA, which is why I have him falling. He's not a 0/1 tech the way he's been portrayed, and that's really what you guys need (though maybe you'll sign Hankins, I think that's still in play. Or maybe Phil Taylor can finally stay healthy). If you're drafting Payne to stop the run, you're not gonna get the best out of him, just like Alabama didn't for most of the season. Jackson's a guy I think teams are gonna be a little higher on than we are because of his playmaking skills, but I'm guessing a guy like Davenport's gonna prove irresistible. He's definitely a riskier pick, a high ceiling/low floor guy, but how often can you get a guy with the physical traits to be the best defensive end in the league this low? The Seashawks need to replace Michael Bennett who was a staple on their DL for years. Davenport is a raw prospect but is insanely athletic and has the potential to bring Seattle's defense back to glory

The Cardinals lack talent and depth up and down the Defensive Line but the biggest need is at Edge. Haasan Reddick isn't athletic and Chandler Jones was released from the Patriots for a reason. Davenport is an immediate upgrade.

Davenport, the best available edge prospect, displayed elite rushing ability for UTSA. He can set the edge and drives through his target. Tennessee likes the upside of Davenport, who they did not believe would be available at 25th overall, but need to work on refining his pass rush moves, as he will not be able to use the same bull rush techniques he used against tackles in the Conference-USA.

With Patricia at the helm, the Lions play to their strengths and grab a great (if not raw) pass rusher in Marcus Davenport. He could be a real game changer for their Front 7, and at minimum, gives them more flexibility in what to do with Ansah next year
