Michael Bennett was traded to Philadelphia, and Cliff Avril may be headed to retirement due to a neck injury, leaving Seattle with only their rotational pass-rusher Frank Clark. They badly need every-down starters on the defensive line, and I think they're a team that might fall in love with Marcus Davenport's potential. Davenport is an excellent size-athleticism combo who makes his money as a pass-rusher with a nasty bullrush. He is still developing his pass-rush moves and overall technique, as evidenced by the Senior Bowl, but he has the traits you want in a pass-rusher. He should contribute immediately against the run, and with good coaching he can become an excellent pass-rusher across from Frank Clark.

Even with the signing of Mo Wilkerson, I think the Packers will

improve with this pick and sets them up for the future with the eventual

Okay the Raiders added a lot of draft picks. I'd probably have them trade some of those 4th/5th/6th rounders since they don't need 13 draft picks, but I'm only doing trades in the 1st, so it is what it is. But the Raiders trading back makes so much sense because as long as they stay in the top 20 they can still get a potentially elite guy. After all their moving around the Colts have a paucity of late round picks, so they have no problem taking a sixth from the Eagles to drop down four spots. As for the Eagles... is TE their #1 need? Nope, not even close. But they're so stacked they're in the enviable position of going mostly BPA, especially when a guy like Andrews falls this far. Now let me be clear, I think he falls this far cause he's a little bit of a JAG at the TE position. Well, JAG's probably a little harsh. It's just I think the things he does well are the same things that guys like Jack Doyle and Cameron Brate do well, and those types of player can be found later in the draft (i.e. Doyle UDFA; Brate UDFA). He's not fast, he doesn't block well, there's no fire to his game, plus he's got the diabetes thing going on (that last one's not necessarily a knock, but it does raise more questions... does the medication make him more lethargic, for example, that sort of thing). He *does appear to have a knack for finding the holes in a defense, but even that might be a product of the offense he played in (and again, you can find guys later with this skill). That said, it's hard to discount his production. He's got good hands and a knack for scoring TDs and he's good at coming down with the ball even when he's covered. The Eagles lost Trey Burton to the Bears in free agency and they released Brent Celek, leaving a good sized hole on their roster behind Zach Ertz. Sure they just added Richard Rodgers, but given Ertz, Celek and Burton all played a lot last year, there's room for another (and that's provided Rodgers gives them anything, he's been pretty quiet as a receiver for the past couple of seasons).

Atlanta was tough for me to pick for this whole mock. They get a guy who many think is TE1 (not me though).

Like Crosby, I have a sneaking suspicion teams are higher on Rankin than we think. A lot of that has to do with his visit list, which is vast and expansive. It seems every team wants a piece of him, and I expect that's due to the versatility he brings. How many other guys can play every position along the line? Crosby probably. Williams, maybe? Nelson? Wynn? Notice something they all have in common? Yeah, they've been drafted already. The Bengals are one of the teams that brought Rankin in for a visit, and if there's a couple of things I've learned about the way they do things from perusing their forums and subs, it's 1) they tend to draft guys they've met with, 2) they lean towards better athletes, no more plodders, and 3) they often draft the hype prospects cause they've got a small scouting department. Rankin's got the first two covered but fails at the third hurdle, but I expect if he's hype enough to be brought to HQ, that's good enough. If I'm completely honest, I wanted to have the Bengals trade up to nab Price or Crosby or whoever, but when I looked up GM tendencies... you guys don't trade up very often, do you Cincy fans? I saw a few trade downs sprinkled in, but only four times in the last half century have they ever traded up. That boggles my mind. And most of those were for mid low round picks. Granted one of those times was last year, but it was also only a ten spot move in the sixth round. Anyway, I think it's pretty safe to say Cincy won't be moving up, so they'll have to stay here and grab whoever falls. And we all know adding one more body to the offensive line isn't enough. The Bengals had a true offensive line last year I took offense to it. I expect any self

Improving the OL remains the name of the game, and after grabbing Price in the first, I have them nabbing a tackle. Cordy Glenn was a nice addition, but the right side of their line is still a bit of a mess. Rankin I feel projects very well as a RT, as he operates from a very strong base and has strong vice-grip hands to lock up pass-rushers. Considering his strength, he is a very strong run-blocker, which is something Joe Mixon would probably appreciate. He tends to struggle with speed, but if he can get his hands on pass-rushers, it's usally game over. With Price, Rankin, and Glenn, Cincinnati's OL may go from a big weakness to a strength just like that.

I doubt the Rams will have too much problem with dropping six spots to recoup one of the sixth round picks they lost in an earlier trade, especially since it's a very slight overpay from the Redskins. Washington has a clear hole at OG (and maybe center), and while I usually don't think NFL teams try to fill their holes in the 4th round, that's not necessarily true of the interior OL. Many of the league's starters came from the 3rd and 4th rounds, so you can draft one here with more than blind hope he might offer something in his rookie season. And Cole's seen his fair share of big games, so he has the experience to step in right away. That's what he did at Michigan, starting as a true freshman at left tackle, so he's used to stepping up quick. The Redskins would have been watching the board and seeing Tennessee coming up soon with a similar need, so they jumped them. Of course it means they're coming out of the first four rounds without filling what many Washington fans think is their primary need at DT, but you're still in the game for Hankins, and of course there's still Phil Taylor, there's always Phil Taylor. I'm sure the Redskins would like to address it but that's not how the board fell, and while there are a few guys available here who are interesting (Folorunso Fatukasi, Kendrick Norton, Derrick Nnadi, Andrew Brown, Bilal Nichols), it's rare for a team to fill a DT need at the end of the fourth round. These guys are mostly depth. Except at OG (and sometimes RB).

I feel a bit like a Mason Cole apologist for having him so high, but he's versatile, talented, and can easily plug the IOL holes here for the Skins. Doing that will improve their loose run game and protect Alex Smith for the future

Bills fans have argued the pros and cons of Mason Rudolph until they're blue in the face, so I doubt if I need to get into them here. I do think the Bills FO would like to wait on him, I don't think Rudolph is worth this high of a pick (and I'm an Oklahoma State fan), and I generally don't think the Bills FO is one that exceeds whatever valuation they strap to a guy. But the Pats moves before the draft have to spook them, especially since it's, you know, the hated division rival Pats. New England traded away their first round picks but they still pick again before the Bills do, and if I was the Bills, and knowing Belichick (which I totally don't), I'd be very suspicious of the fact they've shown interest in Rudolph, given they picked right after them when the draft started and have picks before the Bills pick again. Is he being too obvious? Is it a smokescreen for his real intentions, trying to get the Bills to take Rudolph so someone else drops? Or perhaps he's trying to hide his interest in another QB? But then, maybe Belichick knows that the Bills would find his interest in Rudolph suspicious, which means maybe he really IS interested in Rudolph, and only wants the Bills to think he's not. So they can clearly not choose the wine in front of him. And that's not even taking into account whatever interest the Steelers, Jaguars or Chargers might have in him. The only safe play, if they're in fact interested in Rudolph, is to take him now, though I expect they'll have quite a bit of interest in Calvin Ridley and D.J. Moore as well. But QB trumps everything else, we've seen it a thousand times, and unless the Bills are certain they can trade for Foles (which they won't be by the time the draft rolls around), I think they almost have to pull the trigger. I don't know what kind of QB Rudolph's gonna be, but I think he's got a chance, and it has nothing to do with his arm talent (average) or his poise in the pocket or the gimmicky offense OSU ran or any of that stuff. If he makes it as an NFL QB, it's gonna be because of his smarts. He's basically been calling plays at the line for OSU for the past two years, he's Payton esque in his study habits, and I don't think he'll have any problem adjusting to a different offense. It would be best if he had a little time to do so, and in Buffalo I don't know that McCarron will afford him that time, so we'll see. The good thing is I also think he's mentally tough, so even if he struggles during his rookie season, he ought to be able to bounce back.

Andy Dalton isn't getting any better. While his cap hit isn't too bad he wouldn't be a costly cut as he doesn't have much dead money left. Rudolph puts the pressure on Dalton to be a playoff winning QB or get cut. If Dalton's play picks up Rudolph probably won't lose much stock if they want to trade him down the road.

The Bucs like big-bodied QBs and while Jameis Winston fits the bill size-wise, his play leaves something to be desired. Rudolph is the big man the Bucs covet and he'll do more than guide the sleigh when Tampa's weather gets rough.

QBs have been linked to New England following the Brandin Cooks trade with Los Angeles; Mason Rudolph being among them. His arm strength and play outside Oklahoma State's system are both big questions, but learning behind Brady could help him develop into a true pro-style offense.

Patriots use there second pick to shock every body and take Tom Bradys potential replacement. Not only does this give BB time to develop his next guy it potentially gives Brady another 5 years before Rudolph gets traded away for another second round pick.

For the first time in as long as I can remember, I think the Saints will trade down to recoup some of their lost picks. They don't do it often, only three times since Loomis has been around, and all of those more than a decade ago. But it just makes too much sense this year, I think a lot of the guys they're eyeballing will be there in the second, and they really need to add picks this year, since they've already used so many of them in trades and the like. And at least two of the three trades they've made were in the second round, so it's not out of the ordinary for it to come at this range (some teams will trade down freely in the later rounds, but not at the top). And it has to be said that one of the best drafts the Saints ever had, IMO, was in 2006, when they traded down twice. They walked out of that one with Reggie Bush, Roman Harper, Jahri Evans, Rob Ninkovich, Zach Strief and Marques Colston. Man, what a haul. Why not try and do that again? And since the Colts have so many picks to play around with (and even more so thanks to the second trade down I have them pulling off), I could definitely see them trading back up, especially with so many guys they're gonna be interested in still on the board. So they flip New Orleans one of their many second rounders and their third (a slight overpay from the Colts). It's really difficult to pin down where Hurst is gonna go. A lot of people see him plummeting like into the third round due to his heart thing, and I imagine maybe he's off a lot of teams boards But to those teams that still have him on their board, he's becoming better and better value as more picks go by. Before the combine I thought he was a top 15 lock, and I thought there was a decent chance he'd move up even higher than that as the Aaron Donald comparisons grew heavier and heavier. And he has been cleared by doctors, let's not forget that. He's not a ticking time bomb health wise. I'd say Rueben Foster and Jonathan Allen had more long
Consider me someone who isn't concerned about Hurst's medical red flags. He is a near perfect 4-3 DT and will be chasing down NFC East QBs for years to come
Detroit gets Maurice Hurst with the 20th overall pick. Hurst is a disruptive interior lineman who has great initial quickness and is a great pass rusher from inside.

A steal in the 2nd, he's a beast at DT and his medical issues are clearing up. He'll be able to slot in the line right away, and his college time shows that he's flexible. He'll add a lot more dynamite to an already developing and strong F7

High production DT from Michigan and fills a hole along the DL left by Dontari Poe.
Health concerns aside, Hurst is the best 4-3 DT in this class. Lacking serious roster weaknesses, the Titans trade up to secure their one serious roster hole.

In one of my favorite team-player fits in this draft, Detroit should nab the in-state talent Maurice Hurst. Detroit's interior defensive line, and defensive line as a hole, is lacking pass rushing capabilities. They have run stuffers like A'Shawn Robinson, but adding Hurst's elite interior penetration would add a new dimension to their line. Hurst has the quickest getoff from the interior, providing consistent disruption to plays right from the snap. Detroit needs a 3T, and Hurst fits that bill perfectly.

He could go so many different directions. That said, Detroit has an absolutely dire need for DT, and Hurst could really end up being special. His motor and his habits of taking a play off here and there concern me, but he's already a hometown favorite for Michigan, and fills a huge need. I think you take that risk.
Size-to-athleticism and health concerns push Hurst down the board some, but I like the value-to-need ratio here for Detroit.
Big Mo falls a bit because some teams are scared off by his heart problems. LA isn’t afraid though as they add the top DT to their already impressive line.

It was very tempting to put Derrius Guice here. However, Ziggy Ansah was only franchise tagged, so his future is uncertain. Maurice Hurst, prior to his heart condition (thankfully cleared), was a guaranteed top fifteen selection. He still easily could be, I just think teams will be a little weary, and as a result, the Lions will end up with a steal.
The Dolphins get sniped. Would have liked to grab Jackson but Hurst will help fill the void left by Suh. I take hurst over Vea because Hurst is a superior pass rusher.
Again, not much to say. Hurst is great value at 26 and fills a need.
This pick was sort of hard as there were a couple routes to go. Hurst has the potential to be the best DT in the draft and will bolster the Pats' D-line.
bad heart boi
Good first step and all that

I’m super high on Hurst, and I think he’s got insane pass-rushing potential from the DT spot.  A pass-rushing trio of Hurst, Bosa, and Ingram on the line could be tantamount to the best pass-rushing force in the league.
He fits their defensive mindset of "speed kills". Now that his medical evaluation checked out I think he's primed to go in the first.

They traded Shelton becuase he wasn't really a fit anymore so I think they are looking for someone that could apply a bit more presure up the middle. Hurst is a steal at this point considering he drops due to his heart condition.
Very disruptive DL with great quickness. Medical red flag could drop him lower.
With Dontari Poe's departure to Carolina, DT becomes a huge need for the Falcons defense. I think Hurst would slide nicely into their 4-3, assuming his medical checks out.

Injury scare aside, I cannot for the life of me see how this guy isn't a consensus top-15 guy on everybody's board. I see a guy with rare explosiveness, first-step quickness and the ability to consistently disrupt plays behind the line of scrimmage. There is no doubt in my mind that he's going to be an every down defender in the NFL, and the possibilty of him lasting to pick 22 was a key reason in my decision to trade down

(Originally Marcus Davenport) Detroit has the opportunity to take Davenport and even with the value of the EDGE position, Hurst is just too good to pass up. After watching more tape on him, it's easy to see that he's one of the nastiest players in the draft. He is relentless and uses amazing technique and explosiveness to get to the QB. Watch out A-Rod, Kirk, and Trubisky
Even though there may be some worries with his heart condition, the Lions can't resist taking a guy who could help strengthen a defensive line in need of help since Suh left.

Detroit should look to strengthen their defensive line this offseason, since it is one of their weakest assets. Though a bit lacking in size for a DT, Hurst is fast, quick on his feet, and a good improviser. I don't think the heart condition will hurt his draft stock at all, and there's no denying he's a first-round talent. Hurst stays in Michigan to begin his NFL career in Detroit.
Buffalo gets the 3 Tech needed to make their defense work
The Saints went defense heavy in 17 and it worked great. They continue that trend and improve their DLine with Hurst

I think all the smoke about Hurst falling far in the draft is a bunch of BS. He's the best 3tDT in this draft for sure. He's a top 15 talent, and he was cleared of the medical problems. The Lions would love to get Hurst here. Pair him next to A'shawn Robinson and hopefully Ansah, and they got the makings of a good DL that can actually get some pressure for a change. Add one more EDGE in the 2nd/3rd and they're golden. I know LB and CB are needs as well, but getting that penetrating 3tDT is more important.

The Titans lost Avery Williamson this offseason, but I think Kiser's got a real shot to be even better. He has much higher upside in coverage (not saying a lot), though that'll never be his main strength, and he's been a long time starter on an ACC team. He went into the combine with more at stake than most, then he nailed it. I always like to see guys rise to the occasion like that, kicking ass when everyone's watching, when it matters. Says a lot about character. He tested as more athletic than we thought he might be. He ran virtually just as fast as Fred Warner, Leighton Vander Esch, Dorian O'Daniel and other linebackers considered to be the 'fast guys', and faster than Tegray Scales and Darius Leonard. He doesn't look as fast as those guys on tape, but the league's littered with guys who look like they're not moving fast at all when you watch them, but they're making plays left and right. My hunch is Kiser's one of those guys. Right now the Titans have a pretty goddamn gaping hole at ILB, Woodyard's probably certain to start at one spot but the other's up for grabs, so an ILB makes sense. It woulda made sense with their first two picks too.

For Raiders fans upset about passing on Edmunds and Smith (c'mon you got Minkah!) Kiser is a solid substitute. He lacks good lateral quickness but he is awesome agaisnt the run and is a great blitzer. An excellent person and student as well, winner of the William V. Campbell trophy aka the academic Heisman.

Poz retired after many years in the league, and Jacksonville will look to fill his role. Kiser is good for this role as he has similar weaknesses to Poz in terms of range and coverage ability. He just needs to plug the middle of the field while Smith and Jack make plays, and he’s perfect for that role.

Hahaha, that's right! A punter in the fourth round. Suck it if you don't like it. Or don't, whatever. I'm not pressuring you. I said earlier how the Eagles didn't have any needs, well that's not exactly true. Their punter Donnie Jones retired after the Super Bowl victory, and now they've got no one. Nada, bubkus. Or, that's not right, they've got some guy named Cameron Johnston, or maybe it's Johnston Cameron, it's hard to say. It doesn't matter anyway. Because Cameron Johnston Cameron is no Michael Dickson. I'm not sure there's ever been a Michael Dickson before, not as a punting prospect. You know all those shows you watch, Path to the Draft and First Draft and whatever the hell CBS calls theirs (give it up for Houston Nutt), how they're always going on about safest player in the draft, or the player most likely to be a star in ten years, and they always say Nelson or Barkley and a few of them say Chubb but mostly it's those guys... well my answer would be Michael Dickson. (Of course after I wrote this I noticed the post on the sub about this very thing, so kudos, u/TTrevor11, for stealing my damn Dickson thunder). I can't see any way he's not a twenty year fixture at the Pro Bowl. Move over Ray Guy, Michael Dickson's coming for your yellow jacket. And since Philly's roster is loaded they can roll the dice on a punter in the fourth round. Why not? Fix the position for twenty years, no one's gonna remember when he got drafted.
YEET. They could probs get him in round 5 but I wanted to put a punter in my mock draft.

(Note written way back before Dez was released). Here's a fact about the Dallas roster in two years, Dez, Terrence Williams, and Cole Beasley won't be on it. OK maybe that's not a fact, but it's a widely held opinion, and if it turns out to be true that leaves, what, Allen Hurns and Ryan Switzer? Anyone else? That's pretty damn thin. Sure, they could wait and maybe add another guy next year, but receivers are notoriously slow to adapt to the NFL, recent years notwithstanding. Is that how we think the Cowboys are gonna treat Dak? I have my doubts. And what a steal to get a guy like Gallup this late, he's in the top five of my personal board, but like Washington, I understand some of the knocks against him. His effort when he's not involved with the play is a bad look. He gives little more than an offhanded shove when he's run blocking, and sometimes not even as much as that. His routes become lazy, he gets frustrated and his effort dips when he's not getting the ball or when he's being shut down. He also doesn't help his QB out much on throws that aren't perfect. But then I've probably just described 50% of the receivers in the league, and what Gallup does offer more than offsets the things he doesn't (I mean, at least enough to make him a third rounder). He's gonna make Dak's numbers look really good when he takes those slants and screens and turns them into long gains, he's one of the better receivers in the class once the ball's in his hands. He's also got that intuitive knack on the back shoulder fades, and he's another guy who, like Washington, would benefit from a metric that was able to discern 'play strength' and 'play speed'. It's no surprise that he was the second
Gallup absolutely dominated the MWC and he is expected to at least have a floor of a reliable receiver which is something that the Saints don't really have outside of Mike Thomas.
Colts WR corps is not pretty in the slightest. Adding an elite WR like Gallup will make TY Hilton's life much easier, and give Luck a chance to get the ball downfield
Gallup is a jack of all trades, master of none. He is the most solid WR in the draft, in my opinion, but doesn't wow me with any of his traits.

Sticking with adding offensive weapons, the Browns could look for a boundary WR to play opposite Josh Gordon with Michael Gallup. Jarvis Landry slides right into the slot, but their receiving corp behind the often unreliable Josh Gordon is pretty barren. Michael Gallup is a receiver with a big frame, solid route running, and jump ball ability. He won't particularly blow you away, but Gallup is a 'total' package WR who Cleveland's QB should enjoy throwing to.

Arizona tries to yet again to find a nice weapon opposite, and potential long-term replacement to, Larry Fitzgerald. Gallup is a steal here in terms of value, so this pick was easy after already filling the Cardinals’ other two major needs.
Indy let Moncrief go in the offseason. The signing of Ryan Grant won't be enough for providing Luck with targets. Gallup is a sure fire WR 2 with upside.
I was looking at Edge here for the Panthers but didn't think there was one that wasn't a reach. Gallup is my WR2 and can help that Offense.
Gallup is my WR1, either I cant scout or he fell. Or both
Although the Jags have a lot of recievers, none of them stand out to be the No 1 guy. Give Gallup and year or 2 and I fully expect him to break out and be their No 1.

Sticking with adding offensive weapons, the Browns could look for a boundary WR to play opposite Josh Gordon with Michael Gallup. Jarvis Landry slides right into the slot, but their receiving corp behind the often unreliable Josh Gordon is pretty barren. Michael Gallup is a receiver with a big frame, solid route running, and jump ball ability. He won't particularly blow you away, but Gallup is a 'total' package WR who Cleveland's QB should enjoy throwing to.
Kiser is a tackling machine and could defo start next year. Just the guy the Chargers need.

I expect Ravens fans would be shitting themselves if they were able to come out of this draft with Courtland Sutton, Christian Kirk and Mike Gesicki. The only question here was whether to go Gesicki or Hurst. I actually like Hurst better as a prospect myself, but I imagine a lot of teams will have him lower on their boards due to his age. But he's a much better blocker than Gesicki and maybe that sways Ozzie, Gesicki blew up the combine the way very few TEs have before him, and the only reason he's lasted this long is because not too many tight ends have gone, and he's a terrible blocker. But being a bad blocker didn't stop Evan Engram from going in the first round, so maybe some team will value Gesicki higher than this, I just have a real problem with his blocking, it's a turn off, and I expect it'll be a turn off to a lot of NFL FOs too. But Ozzie's drafting Gesicki as a weapon for Flacco, and in that role, I'm not sure there's a better fit. And they'd be looking up at the Jets and Dolphins about to pick and thinking to themselves, we need to get in front of them. It costs the Ravens their late fourth, but I think they'll be fine with that if they can come out of the draft with these three guys.

The Dolphins have been victimized by Gronk for nearly a decade. Gesicki isn't the blocker Gronk is but he enjoyed immense success as a red zone target at Penn State and could be a headache and matchup nightmare for other AFCE temas
The Bears need a mis-match at the TE position, especially with a sure-fire QB on the roster. Gesicki will jump to TE1 immediately

Miami needs a tight end, Miami finds a tight end. Mike Gesicki in my eyes is nothing but a big athletic player who can catch a pass. He's more a jumbo WR (not an exceptional one, mind you) than TE and would have a hard time blocking a wet napkin. But, he is athletic, so he's worth a third

Gesicki roundly impressed at the combine, and with the defensive line talent available the Panthers decide to instead draft Greg Olson's heir. The Panthers could use more pass catchers right away as well.

A reliable pass-catching tight end is a young QBs best friend. While I don't have the Broncos selecting a QB early, both Case Keenum and their eventual future QB would definitely enjoy Gesicki's capabilities in the receiving game. Gesicki is a stud athlete and an amazing jump-ball receiver, thanks a lot in part due to his volleyball background, and he is a true downfield threat. He is basically the quintessential modern day 'flex' TE, with no blocking skills to speak of but legitimate receiving skills that makes him a big WR. Size-athleticism combos like him are a huge mismatch in the NFL, and a team like Denver who hasn't had much at TE since Julius Thomas could definitely use him.

I don’t really see it, but Jaguars fans insist they are still in the running to draft a TE early. They know better than me, so I’m not going to argue. Gesicki’s receiving ability provides great upside here. His blocking stills major improvement, though.

Coby Fleener hasn't been the seam stretcher that they'd hope he could be. The Saints like running twin tight end sets and utilizing the tight end a lot. Gesicki is a vertical threat and can be a good route runner, but offers no run blocking. The Saints could address receiver, offensive line or edge rusher, but decide that Gesicki is the best value at this point.
Can you trust Tyler Eifert to stay healthy for 16 games? Me neither
Back-to-back tight ends off the board. Gesicki is player, who like Hurst, can really elevate an offense. Bortles should be estastic with this pick.
Fast.
Philly generally takes BPA, and here that coincides with Gesicki, who actually fills a need as well. He's the most athletic TE in this class and figures to be a force for Wentz

Although TE is more of a luxuary pick, getting Gesicki certianly is a special guy. Adding Gesicki who blew up the combine would create mismatches and really complete this offense to be the best in the NFL.

A reliable pass-catching tight end is a young QBs best friend. While I don't have the Broncos selecting a QB early, both Case Keenum and their eventual future QB would definitely enjoy Gesicki's capabilities in the receiving game. Gesicki is a stud athlete and an amazing jump-ball receiver, thanks a lot in part due to his volleyball background, and he is a true downfield threat. He is basically the quintessential modern day 'flex' TE, with no blocking skills to speak of but legitimate receiving skills that makes him a big WR. Size-athleticism combos like him are a huge mismatch in the NFL, and a team like Denver who hasn't had much at TE since Julius Thomas could definitely use him.

Ridley again could be the pick, though like I said for the Cardinals, he's not as flashy as WRs of years' past. Gesicki is the most athletic and versatile TE of the draft, and can come in and be a day 1 starter.
Eifert is only on a one year deal and seems injury prone, so they get an extremely physically gifted TE as a complement/future replacement

The Saints biggest need this offseason was linebacker, but they filled that in free agency by signing Demario Davis from the Jets. They now look to fill their next biggest hole and find Drew Brees a solid receiver. Gesicki is fast for a TE and very athletic. An important stat to note is that he had zero drops over the past two seasons with Penn State. Gesicki is a very solid tight end who will unlock his full potential with Brees throwing to him.
The Eagles don't have a lot of holes so they add BPA. Gesicki fills in for Burton immediately and could even replace Ertz down the road

I feel like I'm short changing the Packers on the explanation side of things, it's just there's not so much explaining to do. Both of their picks thus far have filled gaping holes, what more needs to be said? I guess I can explain the trade I have Green Bay trading Cleveland's own pick in the fourth round back to them to move up ten spots and nab a CB I imagine will be at the top of a lot of boards at this point. I like it, cause it lets me go 4101 Cleveland Browns (From Cleveland via Green Bay). How absurd. I'm kinda surprised to see Hughes fall into the second, to be honest, but that run I was expecting on DBs at the end of the first round never really materialized. Green Bay's the beneficiary, as they're able to move up and grab a guy who was being mocked to them in the first round back in February, and how much has changed, really? The remaking of their defense continues.

Hughes will have less than a 2 hour drive from his college to his new team. I'm not the biggest fan of Hughes but CB is a need for the Bucs and he has gotten first round grades from some. A good fit here.

The Rams are desperate for help at corner. None of their defensive players are household names. Hughes will start immediately because he is talented but also because the Rams don't have anyone to challenge him.

Whoever the QB is in NY, it won't matter how good they are if the other team can keep scoring on them. Eli Apple may be a bad apple, and Janoris Jenkins can't do this on his own. Add in the lost of DRC, and plugging in Hughes here makes a lot of sense. That, and other positional depth, means you take the BPA here
Tampa needs to desperately improve their secondary, and with no elite Safeties available and going Saquon in the first, they instead get a top dog Corner who can help lock down half the field
Hughes is a terrific press corner who can play outside and also is an oustanding special teams player, making him an immediate impact player.

Oakland did well to add Rashaan Melvin, a young CB coming off an excellent season, but their CB is group is far form set. Last year's 1st rounder Gareon Conley only played two games due to injury, and Melvin is still a bit of a risky signing. Oakland's pass defense ranked near the bottom last year, and getting an aggressive press-man corner could help them big time. Mike Hughes, while a bit undersized, is incredibly physical at the line of scrimmage and he short area quickness is excellent. He may start out in the slot at the next level, but he is a much needed addition to Oakland's secondary.

Unlike last year, the Patriots actually have picks to work with in 2018, so they can afford to go for some value at a secondary need, and I REALLY like the value here. With Jason McCourty and Stephon Gilmore at CB, the Patriots don’t have a need out there at this current time, but Eric Rowe is pretty underwhelming as their slot corner. Hughes can be groomed inside for a bit, and eventually take over as starter opposite Gilmore once McCourty is gone.
Browns could use the depth at CB. Hughes is a great candidate who has some serious upside
Very good coverage corner on the perimeter, gave up 0 touchdowns last season.
Colts get the last CB I have with a potential 1st round grade in Hughes.
There was no hesitation for me in this pick. The Packers are in dire need of cornerbacks and Hughes is my CB3 very close behind Oliver.
fast
Pretty good. Raiders draft him a lot
With losing Fuller, adding Hughes which has very mixed rankings as high as pick 14, a long side Josh Norman could be a formidable duo. Hughes is a very good cover corner and good ball skills.

Oakland did well to add Rashaan Melvin, a young CB coming off an excellent season, but their CB is group is far form set. Last year's 1st rounder Gareon Conley only played two games due to injury, and Melvin is still a bit of a risky signing. Oakland's pass defense ranked near the bottom last year, and getting an aggressive press-man corner could help them big time. Mike Hughes, while a bit undersized, is incredibly physical at the line of scrimmage and he short area quickness is excellent. He may start out in the slot at the next level, but he is a much needed addition to Oakland's secondary.

The Vikings bolstered their defensive line in a big way with the signing of Sheldon Richardson, but they need help in the secondary. Rhodes is elite, but Waynes is pedestrian and Newman is a 40 yo FA.

The Patriots didn't see anybody that they were absolutely in love with at 31. They were approached by Tampa to move down while also moving up in the 4th so they took it. 7 picks later, they really regretted their decision as 4 guys they were considering at 31 go between 32 and 37 (Alexander, Rudolph, Vanderesch, and Oliver). So they settle with Mike Hughes who is a scrappy corner that fills a need in their secondary.
With Davis and Melvin gone the colts desperately need some sort of boost to the secondary and so pick up the man from UCF that some scouts rate very highly.

After Malcolm Butler played zero defensive snaps in Super Bowl LII, it became clear that New England would let him move on this offseason. Even if Butler had stayed, corner is one New England's weakest positions, so they go Hughes with this pick. Hughes is known for his aggresive play style and would fit New England well.
Not a perfect fit in CAR's zone defense but he's easily my best CB available and I think he has the versatility to play in any scheme
McCray isn't this world beater athlete, but what he is a very consistent LB who can contribute right away. He'll be able to rotate from Day 1 and make their corps much stronger
McCray is another solid LB and would be a good rotational piece for the Eagles. Could defo add some competiton for starts aswell.

Seattle's been the most vocal of the teams who want to trade down, and I generally find when a team announces they want to trade down ahead of time to the point everyone knows it they usually pull it off. Maybe that's cause they're willing to accept less in a trade (the Patriots actually underpay here, just slightly), or maybe it's cause they've had conversations with so many teams that they have a lot of contingencies in place. I don't know. I just know it usually works. New England has enough picks to jump up in the draft and they gotta find a guy to replace Solder. For my money, McGlinchey's the only first round OT in the draft, the rest are all jumbled together and could go in any kind of order. The Pats don't want to mess with those guys, they want the best guy, and this is only one pick off where they found Solder back in 2011. There's some symmetry to it. That has absolutely nothing to do with the pick, I just thought it was neat.
OT is arguably their biggest need and McGlinchey is a great value here.

Jags need an instant starter for their OL, and when you look at this draft, Glinch may be the safest RT pick. He also may only having the ceiling of an RT, but he'll be a damn good one. Instant upgrade here which will help everyone
New England needs a tackle, and McGlincy, if anything, is consisting. Despite a roller coaster of rankings over the season, this is a solid value at 31 and he can contribute Day 1

The Ravens find themself in the funny position of getting another Notre Dame OT. This time they're addressing RT, and McGlinchy projects well at that position. McGlinchey has been instrumental in helping Josh Adams create his Heisman campaign, and having someone that can block like McGlinchey on the right side should help Collins.

A big boy to protect the boy at QB. Keeping your new franchise QB on the pitch is a surefire way to not be bad, and McGlinchey is the best OT in the class. He helps elevate this offence to a new level.
LT is a bigger need for NE than RT, but McGlinchey is able to start right away at RT, just don't ask him to play at a high level at RT. Possibly switch Cannon to LT.

I don't think that tackle is as urgent a need for the Browns as some might think but with the talented McGlinchey falling, the Browns use their multiple seconds to move up and secure him. He will compete with Shon Coleman for the starting spot.
Chargers could use a FS and James is somehow still on the board but James is more effective in the box. McGlinchey can help out at RT as a dominant run blocker

The Giants did well to sign Nate Solder and lock down one side of their line, even if it was a bit expensive, but the right side of the line still needs some help after losing Justin Pugh to free agency. Mike McGlinchey, who entered the season as OT1 but has slipped a bit, is a very talented player who brings a lot of strengths but also some weaknesses that need to be ironed out. He's a strong first punch, he can shift his weight well, and technique wise he's very sound. Glinch struggled a lot with speed last season, so starting him out on the right side and providing TE chips could help him out big time.

With the trade of Cordy Glenn you would think that they have someone
in place to start for him. I really don't think they do but McGlinchey
could fit the bill fine for the Bills. McGlinchey is a good tackle 
prospect that needs to work on his footwork and run blocking but
I think he will have a solid long career.

It’s between McGlinchey and Hernandez for me, but like the Redskins at 13, they've brought this kid in for a private visit, a workout, went to his combine workout, and went to his private workout. The Bengals either love this kid, or are pulling the most elaborate smokescreen ever to get a position of need taken. I'm going with the former.

Buffalo already grabbed their QB-of-the-Future. Now, it’s time to improve the supporting cast around him, and protection should be their number one priority. Promising young tackle Dion Dawkins’ emergence in 2017 led the team to feel comfortable enough to move on from Cordy Glenn this offseason. This did a create a need for Buffalo on the right side of the OL, though. Now, I’m not a huge fan of McGlinchey on the left side due to some inconsistencies in his handling of speed rushers, but I think he can be a top-notch RT. He’s a seasoned team leader with great technique and experience in multiple blocking schemes. He might as well be a free agent, because he’s that ready to fill someone’s need at RT.
BILLS

With teams at the tail end of the draft all possibilities to take OT, the Browns trade their #35, 114 and swap 5ths to come up and take Joe Thomas’ replacement. McGlinchey is better than the hive mind has been saying he is and the Browns could do a whole lot worse than coming out of the first round with a haul of Darnold, McGlinchey and Bradley Chubb.
Offensive line is the Vikings biggest hole. They decide to protect their new quarterback, pretty simple decision.
A good run blocking right tackle that can add to this improved line. He is a solid pass blocker which is the main concern on the Chargers line, but he is capable enough.
This pick was hard for me (and all the Pats picks) I was in the middle of this mock when I saw the trade news. This is what I came up with for now.
Some may think this is too early for Mike, but he is my top tackle of this draft. Ravens really need some help at this position and Mike helps alleviate the issue.
should go lower
The non-nelson ND OL player

The Bengals draft McGlinchey, the best offensive lineman on the board and an immediate starter at RT.  The Bengals have quite a bit of needs on the line, so getting McGlinchey this late is a good selection.
The Ravens typically go BPA and I think McGlinchey is that at this point. He fits a need too seeing as how necessary RT is a need for them.
Definitley a steal for the Jags. Best RT fills in a need.
Fluid, athletic technician. Needs to improve strength.

The Giants did well to sign Nate Solder and lock down one side of their line, even if it was a bit expensive, but the right side of the line still needs some help after losing Justin Pugh to free agency. Mike McGlinchey, who entered the season as OT1 but has slipped a bit, is a very talented player who brings a lot of strengths but also some weaknesses that need to be ironed out. He's a strong first punch, he can shift his weight well, and technique wise he's very sound. Glinch struggled a lot with speed last season, so starting him out on the right side and providing TE chips could help him out big time.

Sad news to hear about Joe Thomas retirement, and with it is a need for a LT for the Browns. They addressed the RT spot with Chris Hubbard, but I think Shon Coleman is more of a depth T than a starting LT.

Definitely not the best case scenario for Cleveland after trading back, but LT is a postion we absolutely cannot leave this draft without. McGlinchey isn't an elite talent, but he's the best in a class without a lot of sure bets at his position. Wrestled a lot with Josh Jackson here, but pure positional need trumped my personal rankings.

New England lost Solder in FA and they have a 40 year old to protect, so getting another tackle has to be the first thing on their mind. McGlinchey is considered the best in the class by some, and he may turn out to be. His strength and size are great, but his feet can move a little slow at times.
Raiders need a RT, and McGlinchey is one of the best Tackles in the game.
This offensive line is absolutely terrible, so they finally decide to get a first round talent to address it, and McGlinchey will be able to slot into right tackle and at least stop Wilson from dying

The Vikings have a near-perfect roster, so they use this pick to strenghten the weakest part of it: their offensive line. McGlinchey is a strong tackle who is very athletic for his size. Although there are some criticisms about his speed, his strength and technique make up for it.
I wouldn't be suprised if he competes with Flowers for the RT spot and wins it as a rookie

After a solid run as one of the NFL’s most dominant teams, the Seahawks are preparing to enter into a bit of a rebuilding stage. The Seahawks have just one pick in the first three rounds, and with a lot of holes to fill expect them to heavily shop this pick. If they can’t find a suitor, they could go in numerous directions. The Seahawks offensive line has been woeful during the Russell Wilson era, perhaps they finally reward him for his service by investing a top selection on the OL. They could also take a CB to fill Richard Sherman’s shoes.
With Flowers a no-show to workouts (and sucking butt on the field) the Giants take a day 1 right tackle

This is the most questionable pick so far, mainly because theres only a very slim chance the Seahawks even stay put. And they could really use more picks to rebuild that defenense....But fuck it, they need a damn OLine, and Its annoying watching them essentially waste Russell Wilson giving him absolutely no time. McGlinchey definitely struggles vs the speed rush. But dude is a bully and he makes a lot of sense after the Chargers got Connor Williams.

McGlinchey has great technique and instinct coming out of college. He will need to add weight and strength if he wants to last in the NFL but i have no reason to believe he won't be. ND seems to be the new school for OL anyways right?

I expect some Jags fans will call for my head when I don't give them Andrews here, but I already explained why I don't think it's the right move in the explanation for the sixty first pick, so go check that one out. And yes, yes, I know you've brought him in for two visits, so I could very well have my head up my ass with my explanation up there (50% chance, that's where my head usually is), but your visit list at least what I can find of it (on Walter football) strikes me as suspicious. I mean for the most part it's fine, but here's what I don't get about it... where are the QBs? I mean sure, you've met with Baker but come on, we know you're not getting him. No, he's not a traditional DB, he's one of the newfangled swiss army knife DBs, like the honey badger. Use him to exploit matchups, or to keep opposing offenses from exploiting matchups. Play him in the slot, or at safety or LB, or even outside sometimes, move him around, let him terrorize. Just don't stick him in one position and make him stay there, that's not his game. My hunch is anyone willing to draft him this high knows that. In fact I suspect they'll be enamored with him, and Saban's endorsement doesn't hurt. I think he can be a transformative player, and do for the Chargers defense what Polamalu did for the Steelers, Reed for the Ravens or Earl Thomas for the Seahawks. I think he's smart enough you could basically tell him "just do the best thing", and he would, over and over again. In the first mock I did back in February, I had Stewart going in the first round. That shows you what I think of him. But I'm trying to read the tea leaves here and lay the draft out as close as possible to how I think it's gonna go, and it's starting to look like Stewart's gonna come off the board in the 2nd or 3rd sometime, giving someone a steal. Regrettably, for this Lions fan, that someone is the Bears. The only thing going against Stewart is he's not a freak athlete. It didn't stop him from basically shutting down the entire ACC for three years, but he's not one of those guys who's gonna wow at the combine. Instead he's a tough as balls, sticky tactician. He rarely got beat whether in press or off coverage, he attacked when the ball was in the air, he's a sure tackler. He just understands angles and positioning and he rarely gets beat. He's a bit of a poor man's Carlton Davis actually, by which I mean a slightly smaller Carlton Davis so I probably should have just said that instead, since the 'poor man's' business is kinda insulting. Actually, he reminds me of Malcolm Butler, except he's faster. He's faster than Richard Sherman and Josh Norman and Joe Haden too and quite a bit faster than the guy we drafted in the second last year, Teez Tabor. So no, he's not a burner, but he's got the skills to stick around for a long time. And since Chicago's got Kyle Fuller and Prince Amukamara and a bunch of question marks at CB (including Marcus Cooper), they gotta come out of this thing with another one. He can also be flexed to safety in a pinch.

I think a guy like Hines could prove to be the missing ingredient in an offense like the Jags. They've got some big play receivers, but everything out of the backfield is smashmouth and plodding (that's hyperbole, Jags fans, I know Fournette's not a plodder, what I mean is he's up the gut and in your face). Hines changes that. Suddenly you have to account for any toss sweeps they might run or fake. You have to account for him on screen passes and outlets into the flat, you have to account for him on handoffs when you're thinking pass, you have to keep him from getting the edge. I don't necessarily think the Jags offense is the most creative, but I don't think it has to be. Just putting Hines onto the field changes the way a defense will play you. Can you imagine spreading them out only for Fournette to keep going up the gut? It'll be unfair. He can be for the Jags what Bush and Sproles were for the Saints (and what Kamara is today), what Dion Lewis was for the Pats, what Corey Clement is for the Eagles. The explosive chess piece, the game changer, the variable. (Hmmm... I kinda like The Variable as a nickname). I like him in Jacksonville better than pretty much anywhere else.

Sure, he had a shit combine, but lots of guys have bad combines who go on to have stellar careers, the most important of whom, for our purposes, was his dad, Zeus. He of the long NFL career (that would have been longer had a ref not blinded him). You also have to put Brown's numbers into some context. Anyone expecting him to test well wasn't watching the same tape I watched. His main asset as a tackle is his freakish size, his play strength (more on that in a minute) and his good enough feet at that size to keep his QB clean (of all the tests at the combine he bombed, he actually had an average 3 cone drill). He's always been a bit of a successful lumberer, which made his evaluation difficult even before the combine. Now, there's also the narrative that says something along the lines of "I don't care about his tape, his combine shows he's not willing to put in the work. This is a job, man." To which I would counter so a guy who starts playing football in high school, shows up at OU at over 400 pounds then works his way down to 340 by his senior year isn't willing to work? That was the lightest he'd been since seventh grade. Of course he performed poorly on the bench, he's basically been on a diet for four years, he's got that bad weight loss body and man boobs, you all know what I'm talking about. Those kinds of bodies fill out as a person matures. Once he gets in an NFL strength program, he's gonna be as strong as anyone else in the league. If anything, I'm impressed with his work ethic. Most teams aren't expecting to draft a guy in the fourth round who can come in and play right away. They may hope for it, but for the most part guys drafted around here take a year or two to acclimate to the league, which is why you see so many more WTF picks as BPA starts to supersede need. You're just not gonna fill a lot of needs this late. That's not necessarily true with Seattle and their CBs. They take great pride in identifying guys who are unique fits to their scheme and developing them so they can contribute early. Richard Sherman was famously a fifth round pick. Shaquill Griffin went at the end of the third, Byron Maxwell in the sixth. They found Brandon Browner in the CFL but he was an UDFA before that. You look at Meeks's scouting report and it reads like all of the stars from Seattle's past. Tall and a little slow, tough, smart (though at 31 3/4 inches, his arm length falls just short of the 32 inch marker Seattle traditionally used, but they bucked that tradition last year with Griffin, whose arms were exactly 31 3/4 inches long as well). The slow is what makes them fall, the tough, smart and tall is what makes them perfect for Seattle. And I'd argue Meeks is perhaps more prepared for the pros than all of the aforementioned guys. He grew up the son of a NFL defensive coach, his technique is subsequently excellent, and apparently he's a film and workout junkie. He's got everything you want in a CB except speed, and when I see guys like him, the first thing I think is 'Seattle'. (Though now that other teams are running Seattle's defense they've got some competition).
Secondary help

I toyed with having the Bears move down which I'm sure they'd very much like to do, but I just don't see Arizona or Buffalo jumping this high to snag Jackson, the last of the QBs, if they jump at all. Then I toyed with the idea of mocking Edmunds here, but in the end, I think in a division with Rodgers, Stafford and Cousins, Edmunds would have a tough adjustment to the league. I think he's gonna be the kind of guy who makes a lot of flash plays early in his career, but who also gets schooled by savvy QBs on play action fakes and the like. His athleticism's through the roof, but his football IQ still needs some work. Better, from Chicago's perspective, to get a more immediate contributor, and one who also happens to help keep QB baby clean. He's a different kind of weapon for QB baby, but he helps all the same. Plus they just hired his college OL coach, it feels like kismet. I don't have guard as the Bears biggest need, but at the top of the draft it's about talent over need.

If we go by his visit list then the running backs Elway has the most interest in are Barkley, Jones and Penny. Given Barkley and Jones are gone, Elway offers the Jags a fifth round pick to move up three spots and jump the Seahawks and Vikings (the latter more incidental than not) so he can grab the last of the backs he wants. Penny's a tricky guy to figure out. It's easy to love him if you just watch highlight reels of him knifing through defenses and in general, making them look silly. It's easy to love the ease with which he catches the ball and glides the length of the field. But it's when you watch the other plays, the ones where he's not as involved, that you begin to have some doubts. For one he's a bad blocker, I'm just coming out with it. People have tried to make excuses for him or suggest he wasn't told to stay in to block very often, I don't buy it. There's plenty of examples of him blocking, and he looks bad in almost all of them. To me, that's a red flag. So many RBs are coming into the league nowadays with at least some semblance of blocking know how. College teams are asking more and more of their backs, they're in the shotgun a lot, they generally have a good sense of where to be and when to get there. This class is especially impressive. Except Penny. And FOs aren't gonna want to see their QB get killed when a RB misses a block. When a rookie RB doesn't see the field, it's almost always cause he's struggling in that department. That said, with the ball in his hands he's electric. We saw it at the Senior Bowl. In fact the Senior Bowl might be a microcosm of his career. All week we heard about how he wasn't impressing, how he was struggling with schemes and his blocking was below par. Then the game started and he won MVP (alright, he didn't, but he could have). Maybe that's how his career will go. In the coach's doghouse, then he gets put in and lights it up. Stevan Ridley had the same sort of career. Let's hope Penny's ends up better than his. As a pure runner of the football, Barkley might be the only guy who's better.

Penny was the nations leading rusher and is the BPA for the Bills who are making their sixth pick in the first 100 picks of the draft. McCoy is getting up there in age and Penny could take some wear and tear off McCoy and eventually be his replacement

Pittsburgh has to come out of this draft with an ILB, and preferably one who can start right away. I'm not sure I've ever seen a more gaping hole on a team that fancies itself a contender (not their fault, that hole, but still). I've heard a lot of Steelers fans say 'but we signed Bostic'. Alright, I hear you, but Bostic's been entirely average his whole career which is why the Steelers are his fifth team, despite him only being 26. Yes, he had a pretty good year last year, and maybe it's the start of a longer term improvement, but even if that's the case, Pittsburgh still needs another ILB. Williams and Matakevich should be backups only. I've also seen Steelers fans say they want to add one of those LB/S hybrids next to Bostic, which was kinda the role Shazier played. I'm not buying that either (or at least I think Burnett will cover that role on passing downs). Shazier's not a guy you can replace simply by grabbing a guy with similar measurements. He was a special cat, and his loss hurts. And the real bane of the Steelers D was their play against the run. Adding a hybrid guy next to Bostic won't help, they need a true ILB who can help out in the passing game, not the other way around. Stuff the run for two downs, bring a DB in for Bostic on passing downs, dominate. Given the way their season ended, and given there's actually some value at the position around here, my hunch is they'd really like to fill it. In that spirit, I imagine they've been trying to trade up for awhile. My Lions would have been receptive to trading down, but decided on the Pats deal as they wouldn't have to drop down as far. Of course they might have had the Steelers included their second round pick, but that would have been a rip off on the trade chart and I doubt the Steelers jump. I don't know, maybe they would have, but they haven't shown that in the past (the narrative is they don't really trade up, but that's not true, it's just been awhile), plus, while Roquan would plug nicely into their defense, he doesn't help them too much in the running game, and that's where Pittsburgh really needs help (see Jax games). Highly unlikely they'll overpay that much. Then the Bengals would have given them the Cincy salute, the Bills would be worried about the Pats or Jags jumping over them for Rudolph if they dropped to 28th, the Lions a second time would have been worried about the Titans grabbing Carter themselves, and the Panthers want to stay put and nab the draft faller. I expect the call to the Titans was made only as a cursory deal they had to expect they'd lost out on the last viable first
I considered Evans as a pick in the first at least half a dozen times. I somehow managed to talk myself out of the pick each time. No more. Indy gets a steal. Excellent OBLB

It's hard to say you can really know a guy's tendencies after only two drafts, but one thing Quinn has done in both of them is hammer a need position. Last year it was linebacker, two years ago the offensive line. I doubt if he intended to come back to the d line so quickly, but when a guy like Green falls into your lap (and given his physical gifts, yes, I believe this is falling), you adjust. Green is an fascinating guy. My hunch is if he'd stayed in school he might have played his way into a top fifteen pick next year. He's got everything you want in an athlete along the d line, he just needs some refinement (he's only 20). But that has the potential to make this a real value pick, and if there is one thing I feel confident saying about Quinn, it's that he's always looking for value (like his Patriot mentors). My guess is Green's fallen a little from where his talent says he should go due to fit. Is he a big end? A UT? A 5 tech? He's not really a perfect fit for any of those (he might grow into a fit, but he's not one right now). At USC he felt kinda wasted inside and did his best work when he flexed to the edge, but he's not an NFL

Tennessee patched many holes this offseason, and one of the few remaining ones is along their 3-4 DL front. Jurrell Casey is a do it all player, and recently signed Bennie Logan is a great runn-stoping addition, so it makes sense to add a pass-rushing piece like Rasheem Green. Putting him in a 5T role would be an excellent usage of his strengths.

Carolina will be fine with the pass rush in the short-term, but they need some long-term upside besides Daeshon Hall. Green provides that at an excellent value. I considered him as the pick a few times over the past 10 or so picks.

You'll have a chance to yell at me below, Chargers fans, but while I've got your attention, allow me to at least explain myself. It'll only take one word Telesco. Alright fine, that's simplifying, but you have to admit he does some zany stuff on draft day. One of the things he's most fond of is grabbing "his guy," regardless of need, in the second round. He's even traded up a few times to do it. He keeps things pretty close to the vest so it's hard to say who his guy's gonna be, so I'm going with my gut a little bit here, (shit, this whole thing's an exercise in going with my gut, really). But it's the second and third round running backs that tend to get drafted by teams who don't have running back as their strongest need, and yet a GM or two falls in love with them anyway. Think Mixon to Cincy last year, or Kamara to the Saints, Foreman to the Texans, Connor to the Steelers. Prosise to the Seahawks the year before, Jeremy Hill to the Bengals, Charles Sims to the Bucs back before that. It's an epidemic. And while I'm sure you'll pick up Gordon's fifth year option before the season starts, that doesn't mean you'll actually sign him to it (see the Lions and Ebron), so the need exists, even if it falls behind an OT and a DT, for instance. And Jones is an easy guy to fall in love with. Kind of the forgotten guy amongst the early

Le'Veon Bell may hold out. Even if he doesn't his long term future doesn't seem certain in Pittsburgh. Jones is a patient runner who could split carries with Conner and maybe take over as the lead back if Bell is hurt, sits out, or leaves in the future

So I've already described how the macro version of 'draft misinterpretation' works, it's the one we all experience, the one that's controlled by the narrative. The most well known examples of this are Andrew Billings and Mike Mitchell, where the entire draft community was just so totally wrong about them, but it happens every year. Every time you say 'I can't believe so and so's falling this far', or 'man, what a reach' (for instance, perhaps right here, with this pick), that's us being influenced by the narrative. But there's a micro version of this narrative too, and it's far more interesting. It tends to develop where the draft discussion is more insulated, on team specific forums and message boards, outside of the influence of the rest of us heathens. There, a view might be espoused, and it might get seconded by someone else, until the whole community just sort of accepts that it's the way it is. As someone who's frequented lots of these forums over the past few days, I've seen my share of the micro love, but my favorite example of it is on one of the Seahawks boards, where everyone there is just certain Ronald Jones is going in the top 20 picks. When someone suggests they might be able to get him later, they tend to get shot down in a hail of dismissals and are rarely heard from again. Now, maybe they're right and we're all wrong, it wouldn't be totally shocking to see Jones go that early, but it's certainly a viewpoint not shared by the majority of us. And as it turned out, if they wanted to, they could have snagged him at 33. But with Suh in the division Hernandez was too tempting to pass up, so it's on to plan B at running back, Royce Freeman. I expect this one will get a few ooohs and aaaahs from the crowd and a few WTFs from both the draft forums at large and specifically Seahawks fans (though there's bound to be a few more Ducks fans among them). I do think the Seahawks would have preferred a back like Jones or Michel or Penny as they would have better complimented Chris Carson and Mike Davis, but that's not the way the draft fell and the Seahawks really don't have the capital to move up. And I think they really do need
CARDINALS

I know, Titans fans, I know. I did you a solid with the trade down, but now this? I mean, I'm sure some of you like it but I'm guessing most of you would have preferred Justin Reid or Ronnie Harrison, and I thought about that, I really did, but I find myself leaning Hubbard for a number of reasons. First of all, this is a deep class at safety. I doubt Reid will be there by your second round pick, but it wouldn't shock me if Harrison got close (and Bates too, though he's the wrong kind of safety). So I think you can kick that one down the road a bit. Also, you guys have a pretty obvious need at edge, and edge>safety, every day. Even if Dodd improves there's still a hole on one side and Hubbard would fill it nicely. I also think the Pats are gonna be interested in Hubbard, and generally, when I think the Pats are gonna be interested, I think the Titans (and Lions, tbf) are gonna be interested too. They value a lot of the same things in guys, that's just how it is. But mostly I think Hubbard is gonna be one of Vrabel's favorites. Now I know they've been compared a lot and while some of those comparisons are obvious same school, roughly the same height and weight, both white dudes

One of the things that New England lacked last year was a consistent pass rush. Trey Flowers had a solid season and James Harrison was a decent patch, but depth as a whole was lacking. Derek Rivers will be back, but the Patriots could stand to add a consistent force in Sam Hubbard. Hubbard, to me, is more of a disruptor than a finisher, but that's not exactly a bad thing. He has excellent athleticism, and he's able create pressure in the backfield on a consistent basis. He's still raw and has some room to grow into his frame, but his ability to collapse the pocket would help out big time.

Even with Ziggy Ansah back in the fold, the Lions are still in need of an edge rusher. There are some concerns about Hubbard’s speed after his pro day, but I’m not put off by it all that much. He still shined in the quickness drills at the Combine, and short-area quickness means way more than top-end speed for a pass rusher. I also like his fit in Matt Patricia’s defense as I do think he’s capable of playing upright or with his hand in the dirt. Patricia will find a role suited perfectly for Hubbard’s skill set.

Barkley is the total package of vision, athleticism, explosiveness, as well as pass-catching capabilites that makes him the ideal modern running back. Barkley would also do well to take a lot of pressure off Winston and balance the offense.

Indy has the easiest pick in the draft in my opinion. The top-3 non-QBs all fit their needs, so its really just the best player that falls to 1.06. In this instance, I picked Saquon Barkley to pair with Andrew Luck in the backfield. Absolute transcendant RB talent that can play on all three downs and thrive in any system. Only knock on him is a lack of physicality in his runs, which rings pretty hollow to me. #1 on my Big Board at 6 overall, absolute slam dunk for Indy.

The Buc stops here for Saquon. He's one of the most electric running backs I've ever witnessed. He dances around players like a ballerina but get too close and he'll roll over you like a rhino. He's in a class of his own, and is going to help take a ton of pressure off of Jameis. Think Dak/Zeke v2. He would never fall this low if there weren't so many QB needy teams, and a lot of good QBs.

The Colts are jumping up and down as the best player in the draft falls to them at 6. This gives a huge running game to help out Andrew Luck and maybe finally take a little bit of pressure off him, if he even exists still.

The Colts trade down with the Jets just to end up with a guy they would have taken at pick 3 anyway. A pass rusher and a better offensive line is their biggest priority, but with Chubb and Nelson gone, Indianapolis uses the number 6 pick on the most talented player in the draft in Saquon Barkley. RB is not the Colts' biggest need, but picking Barkley will certainly make the fans happy, and he is too good to pass up here. Barkley is an explosive talent who immediately improves the Colts' offense. He will be a steal for any team that picks him; he's fast, agile, strong, and is a threat at RB, WR, and kick returner.

Man, I hope Griffin hasn't been sitting around in the green room since the draft started, this is a long damn time to wait. But I also think it's roughly the sweet spot for him. If he wasn't missing a hand, I think he'd go anywhere from the late first to the mid second. Conversely, if he hadn't performed so well at the Senior Bowl and combine, I think he'd be looking at making a team as a 7th/UDFA. This feels like a good compromise. And don't think the story of Griffin doesn't play a large role, he's a PR dream, the marketer's job is gonna be cake. That said, you don't draft a guy because he's gonna help your image, or to be the top story on NFL Network. He has to be worth drafting, and Shaquem Griffin is worth drafting. In fact he might *still be underrated. The fact is the Dolphins could desperately use a linebacker who can do the things Griffin can do. He can cover (former DB), he can get after the passer, he can straight fly. I expect the missing hand to prevent him from making maybe 5 10 plays a season, while I expect his talent, heart, instincts and will to account for an extra fifty plays made. My math's not what it used to be (or ever was, tbh), but that seems like a net gain of forty

I know this might seem nuts to you guys right now, Bears fans, but I really don't think Howard's long for your team. He might have even been traded by draft day, maybe to the Colts for a third or fourth round pick (the draft's too deep at RB to get much else), or as part of a first round trade up (obviously I'm not banking on that one, as I didn't have it happening). Even if he's still on your roster by the time the draft rolls around, I think you guys start planning for a future without him. A RB who's bad in the passing game just doesn't fit Nagy's offense. And if Howard's not in your plans, what else to you have? Cohen? I think we can all agree he's great, but he's not an every down back. And don't forget this is the summer of Mitch. It's almost a cliche' by this point, but it's also a smart move to give your franchise QB everything it takes to succeed. That's why if I hadn't gone RB here, I was looking WR. But the depth at WR is great, and now that the trade down with Baltimore has got you back into the third round, you can address it later. And I don't want to downplay how perfect a fit I think Michel would be for Nagy's offense. He's like a combo of Kamara and Hunt, and we already know one of those guys fits like a glove. When he makes it to this spot, I think Pace pulls the trigger. And the more you think about it, the more it makes sense, right? This is the kind of draft day stuff that always happens. The teams that take RBs in the second/third aren't usually the ones with the glaring, obvious need. It tends to be a secondary need, and then when they shred the league and end up in ROY conversations, you can't imagine why you didn't like the pick at the time (see Kamara, Hunt). It also helps that there's no edge talent worth taking here, which I agree is a dire need (and it looks like Pace knows it too, which is why you're bringing in so many mid round edge guys). You could make the argument Sweat or Key might go this high, but they've got some red flags that are gonna scare teams (Sweat injury history; Key duh). So why not throw a bone to your new coach, your QB, and by November or so, your fanbase?
The Lions patience on waiting for a RB pays off. Michel is one of the most exciting backs in the draft and is a great value in the third round

It's no secret that Detroit has running game issues. It's been 4 years since they've had an 100 yard rusher. The top back available here is Sony Michel, an explosive back with great vision. Many have compared him to Alvin Kamara due to playing in a duo system at Georgia, but he has the frame and all-around game to be a full time starter. Michel follows his blockers well, he has legitimate breakaway speed, and he takes sharp cuts to make way into the open field. Combined with a pass-catching back like Riddick, Michel should be able to to bring the running threat that Detroit needs.

At this point I think we can essentially scrap the narrative. By the fourth round, picks are coming hot and heavy and as often as not, it's full of guys we thought were later round picks (Howard Wilson, Michael Roberts, Grover Stewart, De'Vondre Campbell), guys we thought wouldn't even be drafted (Antonio Morrison, Alex Lewis, Derrick Kindred, Dean Lowry) or even a few guys we've never heard of (Rodney Gunter?... who looks like a hell of a pick). In fact this whole round is probably too chalk if I'm honest, though I doubt you guys will see it that way. No, CB isn't Tennessee's direst need, but neither was WR when they took Taylor in the third last year. Neither was DT when they took Austin Johnson in the 2nd a year prior. And neither is Johnson, here, though the depth after Butler, Ryan and Jackson leaves something to be desired. If one of those guys gets hurt, they'll be glad they have Johnson as a safety valve. I think Robinson's gonna like Johnson cause he's not so wowed by guys with flashy combine numbers, but by guys who produced. And Johnson produced. The sticky man to man cover guy started all but five games his freshman year, was named all Big

Here's what's tough to figure out about the Steelers what kind of safety do they want to add? If they're looking at covering for their first team, a free safety makes the most sense, as Davis is far more questionable as a starter than Burnett. We have no idea how he'll perform switching to FS (you have to think the Steelers would have some idea, but then why didn't they shift him there last year, when Mitchell proved that he sucked?). On the flip side, if they're looking for a more long term solution, a SS makes more sense, as Davis is only 24 while Burnett is 29. One of those guys will need replacing before the other. However, if they're looking for fit in a nickel, 3 safety look (something they used a lot with Shazier), maybe they think Burnett would flex into the hybrid role and Davis into the strong role he played last year, in which case a FS would make more sense. Unless they think Davis should stay at free safety during a 3 safety look, in which case they'd be looking for more of a SS, and if they also kept Burnett at SS when they went nickel, then they'd be looking for more of a hybrid guy, possibly even a LB. Whew. And of course they've given nothing away with their visits as they've brought in all three types, from free safeties like Bates to strong safeties like Harrison to hybrid linebackers like Baker and O'Daniel. So, what the hell are we supposed to think? My hunch? BPA among those guys. Harrison and Bates are gone so their out of the picture, which would appear to leave Baker (though he's got some issues, especially in coverage). But then there's this late
His slow 40 time hurt his stock a bit but I think hes good enough to be CB 3 and could be useful in certain situations.

Taven Bryan the next J.J. Watt? No. Taven Bryan the next Howie Long. I mean, not exactly, but tell me that didn't give you a little stir, Raiders fans. Tell me you didn't make you feel all warm inside. My uncle's a Raiders fans, I know how you guys get. Every Time someone brings up Howie Long around him he always, always says "Howie Long was a ball player". That's all, just that. I need to record him and make a sound drop out of it. So if the draft plays out like this, I'm thinking the Jags take a look around at all the offensive linemen and tight ends who haven't been taken up to this point and think to themselves shiiiit, we can still grab one of our guys further down. Plus, we all know the end of the first's a hot spot for trade action, it happens all the time. You got the fifth year option, you got the pending overnight wait, you got droppers getting back in range. It's a cornucopia of trade circumstance. Now I will admit, I wanted this one to happen so bad I basically forced the trade chart to bend to my will and I might have jacked it up in the process. It's always dicey including future picks and I prefer not to do it, but hey, it's a thing that happens. And the Jags are the type of loaded team that's always adding future picks, that's how you stay on top. So I made it work, in the end (and it's a little more palatable from the Raiders perspective given they added another second rounder via the earlier trade down with Arizona). I don't know how happy you Raiders fans are gonna be with this trade, it's a lot to give up and McKenzie's typically a guy who likes to trade down rather than up. But there's a new sheriff in town as they say, and the draft's his coming out party. It's time to start putting his imprint on the team. And tell me Bryan doesn't seem like a player Gruden's gonna love. You won't, cause you can't. And man do the Raiders need someone just like him, yet another reason I have them trading up. After Bryan's off the board, you're on to your Nathan Shepherds and Da'Shawn Hands and Harrison Phillipses. It's a precipitous drop off.
He isn't a sexy pre-draft name but he is the BPA on my board and the Titans could use some help up front. He is an amazing athlete for his size and I think he has the chance to be a steal at 25
Unlike Jurrell Casey, Bryan is a disruptive force in the middle of the defensive line. OT is also an option here but DT is by far the team's weakest position on the field.
The fall stops here, and the Vikings now find young, powerful talent to rotate in as a Pass Rushing DE. Bryan is far from consistent, but his flashes are very bright. This is a solid pickup here.

Kind of a shock pick, but a great value pick. The Jags need to make some tough cuts next year and Bryan is basically BPA which makes some of that D-Line expendable.
BPA at a need here. Bryan helps their rotation of Collins and Price. Struggles with getting pushed out of the play too much, which makes me worrisome.
