Cleveland landed some young and talented players last for the defensive interior, which allows them to try and go big by taking the high upside Taven Bryan. Bryan has freakish athleticism and has shown on film the ability to make explosive plays. However, consistency is quite easily his biggest issue. Some games he'll look like the most dominant player on the field, but others he can be somewhat of a liability. Taven is a bit of a freelance who struggles to keep gap repsonsibility. If he can go somewhere with good DL coaching to try and work with him on maintaining repsonsibilities, he can be a huge mismatch down low.

Trade details: See pick #35. Bryan is nowhere near his potential ceiling. He flashes at times, but then he also looks absolutely lost a second later. He’s not ready to contribute right now, but Gregg Williams has a history of developing good defensive lineman. He also has a long history with Browns DL coach, Clyde Williams, who has worked with the likes of Robert Quinn, Aaron Donald, Michael Brockers, and the Browns’ 2017 DL next to Williams. This is a good place for Bryan to grow.

Acquiring Brandon Fusco has made this selection a little easier. Defensive Tackle is arguably their biggest need and Taven Bryan could play either tackle or edge. They definitely need to address wide receiver and tight end at some point, but their is solid value to be had at both positions later in the draft.

I loved his display of athleticism at the combine. Atlanta fans should be happy to get a player as talented as him.
Bryan has the talent to play either 3T or 5T and is proably a day 1 starter in Tennessee

The Rams are going for it, we all know that, but they've got a couple of pretty gaping holes in their lineup that may or may not be able to be filled by draft picks, but they don't have a lot of other options. Some inexpensive guys are gonna have to perform. Pass rusher is one of them, and they'll hope they've sorted that one out at least partly with the selection of Turay. Another is ILB after shipping Ogletree off, and while I don't know if Scales is the answer or not, I know he'll have plenty of room to run around and make plays behind Suh and Donald. Scales isn't the greatest athlete at ILB, but he's one of the draft's smartest and most instinctive. After years of Ogletree and his missteps, smart and instinctive is gonna seem pretty good. Pair him with another fast linebacker (Barron?), and Scales will clean up in the middle of the Rams D. His reaction time and trust in what he sees makes him play faster than he times. I think he's perfect for the Rams, and I think teams that try to wait on him are gonna be surprised by how high he goes. He's also the source of one of my favorite forum one liners Jorah Mormont has Tegray Scales. I wish I could remember where I saw it so I could give the author credit, but alas, I've looked at a lot of posts over the last couple of weeks and they're all starting to run together. Houston doesn't mind adding another couple of picks to move down a few spots.
The Giants need desperate LB help, Scales is another solid LB that can tackle and would have some starting reps day 1.

The Seahawks could damn near go anywhere with this pick they got so many needs which is crazy to me, just crazy. It feels like ten years since I've come into a season and the Seahawks haven't been loaded, but here we are. That's how it goes when you don't have a QB on a rookie contract anymore, you gotta trim the fat and a lotta the meat. But let's not act like they couldn't use a safety anyway, who knows how much longer Earl's around for, and Kam's got those injuries, man, they're piling up. Sure they drafted a couple of guys last year, Delano Kash Pride Hill (winner, multiple name contests) and Tedric Thompson, they tried to look out for this day, but Thompson might get his shot at corner, not safety. And even if they both get their shot, there's two holes that need filling, and in the NFL that generally means it takes at least three guys to fill it (one to fail, two to work out). Edmunds has the good blood lines of his dad and brothers, football's gonna be important to him, he was a leader on that Hokie defense. He does his best work at the line but he's no slouch in coverage either. Great athlete, the fact that he started his career as a corner still shows in his game. He can be over aggressive at times and whiff on a tackle or two which can make him look silly, he's gonna have to learn to break down and lay a form hit on a guy, but I'd rather that than the opposite.
Edmunds isn't great in man coverage but he is a good zone defender and a good hitter/tackler
Panthers double up on safety here with Tremaine Edmunds' brother, Terrell. Edmunds is a very athletic guy, who will at the bare minimum compete on special teams, but is very rangy.

Edmunds is an athletic freak, like his brother Tremaine, but he appears to be limited to box duties, at least early in his career, due to some inconsistencies with his instincts. This will hurt his stock some, but even as a traditional SS, he’s a future starter and would be a great option to groom behind Shawne Williams. His upside makes this pick a potential steal, though.

Adding Edmunds along with Harrison would be a great pairing. Harrison can play zone coverage and cover the middle of the field while Edmunds can use his speed and length to become and big playmaker in that secondary. Edmunds defo has the potential to start day 1.

I expect this to irk a few Browns fans, who would have rather I give them one of the offensive tackles available. While I'm sure you'll add one at some point in the draft, everything I read says Shon Coleman's gonna get first crack at it, it's what he played in college, and he's already working with Joe Thomas on learning the position. That gets Chris Hubbard on the field (who I'm a huge fan of), and that to me doesn't look like a position that needs to be addressed in the second round. Sure it could be if the need met the value, but the value here is with Settle. He's a guy someone's gonna take high, he's got rarely seen gifts for a guy his size. The key's gonna be whether he can keep his weight down or not, but if he does he's got all pro potential. He's a giant, dancing bear, and he'll fit snugly right into the middle of Cleveland's line next to Ogunjobi on first and second down, then on passing downs they can bring out the death lineup of Chubb, Ogbah, Garrett and Ojunjobi. Eventually maybe Settle stays in too, he's got enough giddy up even on his huge frame. But after trading away Danny Shelton, they've got an opening for a mammoth in the middle.
A steal here, Tim Settle is a young freaky NT who can anchor the KC line for possibly up to a decade from now.

Settle is outstandingly "meh"

How is it North Carolina State wasn't playing in the national championship game? It's bizarre how many high level draft picks they have in this class. Keeps Lamar healthy

Brown's the kind of guy who's absolutely gonna intrigue an NFL brain trust. In fact he's such a great athlete it wouldn't surprise me if he's long gone by now. Worst case he's an elite special teams guy, best case he works himself into Jacksonville's nickel role ahead of DJ Hayden or Jaylen Myrick. Cause if you can turn the piece of clay that is Tony Brown into a player, you might have a pro bowler on your hands. WR2 with upside

I'm not buying all these Colts Roquan rumors, they smack of the type of bullshit smokescreening we always get at this time of year. All of a sudden it's everywhere like it was crafted to be tweeted and retweeted until it's a dead solid certainty that the Colts are taking Roquan Smith. Well I for one don't believe it. Now I do believe they like him, sure, but everyone likes him. I doubt you could find a team one that wouldn't want him as part of their squad. But enough to draft him this high, ahead of so many other good players? That's where I have the problem. He's still a small(ish) chase linebacker who has to be covered up, and no matter how good his tape is (and I agree with everyone that it's great), those guys don't get taken high, they just don't. If Ballard does pull the trigger, he'll be bucking decades of history to do it. I also expect the Colts really do want to get faster at LB, that makes perfect sense. But there's another guy a guy with a much higher ceiling, a guy you wouldn't have to cover up who's pretty damn fast himself. Edmunds possesses a strong combination of size and elite athleticism at 6’5”, 250 pounds. Well last time I mocked this I said the word safe and was crucified, so let me try again. he is not old

Still peeved at me over the Barkley trade, Bucs fans? I know it's been awhile since we've seen you, took the whole of Friday off, but don't you worry about a dull draft, you're about to have an exciting season. And OK sure you just added Pierre Paul and Vinny Curry via FA, but both of those guys will be thirty by the time the season ends, Noah Spence can't stay healthy, and William Gholston is an expensive run defender who can't get to the QB. That's not the way you keep winning. Lewis got on my radar at the Senior Bowl. I thought he was better than Davenport during the practices. Then he went to the combine and crushed it. I don't know if the Bucs are a Sparq team, but my hunch is every team is a little Sparqy, everyone uses metrics, and they could all use the kind of player with the Sparq score Lewis put up. He was the third highest scorer behind only Lorenzo Carter and Josh Sweat, and ahead of guys like Harold Landry and Ogbonnio Okoronkwo. And he's got almost twenty pounds on 'em! So much for the average athleticism he was alleged to have. So, back to the tape, why wasn't he a Buckeye legend? Well I've already been over how Ohio State likes to rotate and shift guys around. I usually like to try and avoid trades between teams from the same division, but an in depth skimming of the past five drafts shows there's been exactly one every year. So this is my one. The Pats and Bills strike me as professional enough organizations to see past any bitterness that might exist from their years as rivals, they'll do what's best for their teams. And the best thing for New England is to add picks. The best thing for Buffalo is to draft this future star. I think Crosby's got a chance to be one of the best players to come out of this draft, and I think the Bills are lucky to find him still on the board here. In the mock I did back in February I had him as a (pretty high) first rounder. On most early iterations of this I've had him at the tail end of the first or the upper end of the second. But shit keeps happening in the league, and this is the end result Crosby for a bargain. I think his versatility will fit perfectly on the Bills line, who all of a sudden have a plethora of holes. I think Crosby's a starting tackle in the league (his light feet at the Senior Bowl took everyone by surprise), but I think he could be an all pro at guard or center. So start him off at guard, if Bodine doesn't work out, move him over. If Newhouse doesn't work out, move him over. Either way, you've solved a lot of problems with one guy.
The Cards are old at OT. Crosby profiles as a strong run blocking RT with plenty of potential to improve his ability as an OT. Should be a starter for a long time
The Dolphins need an injection of youth, skill, and strength at the LT position. Crosby isn't a popular first-round selection but I can TyrELL he will be a success at the position.

Jason Peters, who is now 36 and coming off an Achilles tear, likely doesn't have much time left. Lane Johnson has solidified himself as one of the very best RTs in the league and I'd be surprised if Philly tries to move him, so they need a future player to takeover once Peters is gone. Tyrell Crosby anchored Oregon's OL and is a developed pass-blocker. His technique is fairly wonky, but he operates from a strong base and uses his hands well. He's also great as a run-blocker, making him a capable early starter if needed.

After moving on from Josh Sitton, the Bears are looking to fill in the LG spot. Matt Nagy is bringing a zone blocking scheme to Chicago, and he’s hired former Oregon head coach, Mark Helfrich, as offensive coordinator. Crosby played his college games in a ZBS and has proven to be reliable in that scheme. He even played a couple of seasons under Helfrich. He played left tackle in college but projects better as a guard or RT in the NFL. The ideal outlook for him with this pick would be to start at guard, but eventually move outside to replace Bobby Massie at RT.

Great OLine talent, can play either RT or LT. One of my favorite players in the draft.

I could easily see some team falling in love with Nwosu and drafting him before this. In fact I think he'll be in play for my Lions at 51 if some other guys don't drop, the way I had it go here. He's got that look of someone who's gonna be a player in the league for 15 years. I thought he looked the best of any edge player during the combine drills. He was smooth, he didn't waste a lot of motion, his punches were violent. I think he could even play some inside linebacker given his size, speed (4.65) and fluidity. It would take some time for him to adjust, obviously, but I don't think it's a reach. NFL FOs are starting to draft these kinds of versatile defenders earlier and earlier, and whether Nwosu can be a viable option inside or not, he's got everything you want on the outside. He's athletic and mean, he looks to hit ball carriers as hard as he can, he looks good when he drops into coverage. He's new ish to the game and still learning, and he'll have to do some work in an NFL strength and conditioning program so he can hold the edge against the run, but the efforts there, and he's gonna do nothing but get better.
Similar to Green Nwosu is another player that hasn't shown consistency on tape but has all the potnetial in the world.

I'm sticking with my take from my first mock, despite its heat and despite the fact Denver fans aren’t gonna like it. Vea is one of my favorite players in the draft, I think he would have set the combine on fire had he not pulled his hammy (and the one drill he did finish, he ran a great time for a man his size and his ten yard split was fantastic). Denver's done a decent job in FA of filling some of its holes, and I'll be honest, I just think the positional value of DT over OG (and Nelson) holds up here. I have the draft as deeper at guard than DT (not by a lot, admittedly) and honestly, I think Vea is every bit the prospect Nelson is (and I love Nelson too). I actually think the Seahawks O line, despite what everyone seems to think, is the least of their concerns. Or not the least, probably, that'd be QB, but I think I certainly wouldn't put it anywhere near the top of the list. They've done a good job of cobbling together a respectable unit, and I know in Seahawks country anyway, a lot of them think the problem was Cable. But the unit is paper thin, and virtually every one of them has spent time in and out of the lineup, and it would be shortsighted if Seattle didn't have a plan in case of injury given what's happened the past couple of years. It's not fair to Wilson, hell, it's not fair to the rest of their team, let alone the fans. On top of that, Suh + Donald. But I think they know that. They've spent the offseason espousing the need to upgrade their running game, their actions have backed it up, and I think it keeps going during the draft. It's time to turn a weakness into a strength. Also, and I can't stress this enough, Suh + Donald. A guy like Hernandez should be just what the doctor ordered to help keep Russ upright in the face of the Rams heat, though I would expect a few holding calls now and again, Hawks fans. But the best way to stop strong, brawny, nasty athletic guys is with your own, and Hernandez is just too nasty a guy and too perfect a fit here to slide any further (and if he beats out Fluker, all the better).

I know lots of Lions fans want Guice but he won't be much good if you can't run. Hernandez is an excellent prospect at guard and will help right what has been a disappointing offensive line for years.

Normally, I like to get some idea what an FO is thinking by reading their visit list. I just feel like it's the best indicator of their true intentions, especially now, during the subterfuge season, when their words are all lies, lies, lies. That's not to say the visit list is infallible, of course. Some teams use visits more than others, and I'm sure some teams use it to send false messages as well (seems like a Belichick thing to do). But on the whole I think it's the best way to discover a team's intent at this time of year. Well, getting a read on what the Jags might do by reading their visit list seems like it might be an exercise in futility. One look at their boards and it's TE, OG, WR, over and over again, with some OT and QB sprinkled in. Well they've only met with two TEs, one interior lineman, and three wide receivers, two of them later round guys. Meanwhile they've met with five linebackers, three offensive tackles, four safeties, and only one QB, Baker Mayfield, who will not be available for them to pick. And a lot of their visits are with late rounders/UDFA types. So what gives? Are they trolling us? Maybe they only use the visits for their late round and UDFA moves, I can't figure it out. Last year they met with Fournette and Cam Robinson for sure (their first two picks), but there was no mention of meetings with any of the other guys they ended up drafting, though they did meet with other guys who played the positions of the other guys they drafted (For the record 3 DEs, drafted Smoot; 9 LBs, drafted Brown; 4 WRs, drafted Westbrook). Help me out if I'm wrong here, Jags fans, am I way off on this? Did you meet with some of the other guys you drafted and I just missed it? The reason I mention all of this is cause I had some beef with the way the Jags fans are thinking, so I decided to do a deep dive. And I wasn't alone, BTW. Sprinkled into all those posts on TE, OG, WR were a few lonely Jags fans who wondered, the way I do, why the Jags would take a TE so high? Maybe they do want to go to a two TE set, fine. But they brought in two guys in the offseason (Seferian Jenkins and Niles Paul), and while those aren't the guys who stop you from taking a TE, don't they kinda stop you from taking a strictly pass

Gettleman said his first order of business was to fix the offensive line, he started the process in the first round and he continues it here. And the interior of the line is one place you can hope to find a starter in the fourth round, especially with a guy like Teller. I mentioned my beef with overrating "mean streak" players up at pick 122, in my explanation for the Chiefs nabbing Alex Cappa (you should read it, it's a tour de force), and Teller certainly falls into that category. He's more nasty and driven than athletic and technically sound and for whatever reason, he regressed in 2017. If you look at his 2016 tape, you'll see a guy who moves defensive linemen with his hands and makes it looks easy. You'll see a guy who's balanced and strong, a guy who drove defenders back in the run game, and who easily kept defenders away from his QB. You see glimpses of it in 2017, but far less frequently. He went from nasty to lazy, driven to uncaring. He lacked as a puller, he didn't seek out contact. Frankly, it was bizarre. But he rehabbed his stock some at the Senior Bowl, and if he can recapture his form from 2016, he could be a steal at this point.
The Giants need OL help, it's no secret. and grabbing Teller at the top of 3 helps them protect their new investment at QB, and even work to improve their run game.

Vikings need to recover their Line back to where it was this year, and Teller can absolutely step in and Start Day 1 which is what they need. This is a smart choice for a team who need to protect their new investment
Teller is one of the strongest, most solid guards in this class. Very high ceiling as a player and would start immediately next to Trent Williams.

Teller looked like an early second-round pick last year, but a down year saw his stock stumble. Good coaching could turn this pick into a great value.
